{"title_page": "Wally's Wonderland", "text_new": "{{short description|American thriller film}}{{Notability|Films|date=March 2020}}{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Wally's Wonderland\n| image          = Wallys Wonderland JPG.jpg\n| alt            = \n| director       = [[Kevin Lewis]]\n| producer       = [[Grant Cramer]]<br>Jeremy Davis<br>David Ozer\n| writer         = G.O. Parsons\n| starring       = [[Nicolas Cage]]<br>[[Caylee Cowan]]<br>[[Beth Grant]]<br>Emily Tosta\n| editing        = Ryan Liebert\n| studio         = JD Entertainment<br>Landafar Entertainment<br>Landmark Studio Group\n| runtime        = 97 minutes\n| cinematography = David Newbert\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Wally's Wonderland''''' is an upcoming American [[Thriller film|thriller]] film directed by [[Kevin Lewis]] and starring [[Nicolas Cage]], Emily Tosta, [[Beth Grant]], [[Grant Cramer]] and [[Caylee Cowan]]. \n\n==Synopis==\nThe Janitor ([[Nicolas Cage]]) is a quiet drifter who is tricked into a janitorial job at the condemned Wally's Wonderland. His mundane tasks suddenly become an all-out fight for survival against wave after wave of demonic animatronics. He teams up with a group of teens who also find their way into the park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/charles-roven-atlas-entertainment-launches-literary-division-1203494568/|title=Film News Roundup: Charles Roven\u2019s Atlas Entertainment Launches Literary Division|last=McNary|first=Dave|last2=McNary|first2=Dave|date=2020-02-06|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/nicolas-cage-star-genre-thriller-wallys-wonderland-haunted-amusement-park-1202771823/|title=Nicolas Cage To Star In Genre Thriller \u2018Wally\u2019s Wonderland\u2019|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|last2=Wiseman|first2=Andreas|date=2019-10-29|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Nicolas Cage]] as the Janitor\n*Emily Tosta as Liv\n*[[Caylee Cowan]] as Kathy\n*[[Beth Grant]] as Sheriff Lund\n*[[Grant Cramer]] as Jerry Wallace\n*[[Ric Reitz]] as Tex Macadoo\n*[[Chris Warner]] as Jed Love\n*Terayle Hill as Bobby\n*Christian Delgrosso as Aaron\n*Kai Kadlec as Chris\n*Jessica Graves Davis as Siren Sara\n\n==Production==\n\nFilming took place in and around [[Atlanta, Georgia]].\n\nThe picture was announced in October 2019 by Deadline, directed by American film-maker [[Kevin Lewis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/nicolas-cage-star-genre-thriller-wallys-wonderland-haunted-amusement-park-1202771823/|title=Nicolas Cage To Star In Genre Thriller \u2018Wally\u2019s Wonderland\u2019|work=[[Deadline (magazine)|Deadline]]|publisher= Andreas Wiseman |date=29 October 2019|accessdate= 3 February 2020|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/party-five-emily-tosta-joins-nicolas-cage-wallys-wonderland-1202851916/|title= \u2018Party Of Five\u2019 Star Emily Tosta Joins Nicolas Cage In Genre Thriller \u2018Wally\u2019s Wonderland\u2019 |work=[[deadline.com]]|publisher=[[deadline.com]]|date=5 February 2020|accessdate= 3 February 2020|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|8114980|Wally's Wonderland}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American thriller film}}{{Notability|Films|date=March 2020}}{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Wally's Wonderland\n| image          = Wallys Wonderland JPG.jpg\n| alt            = \n| director       = [[Kevin Lewis]]\n| producer       = [[Grant Cramer]]<br>Jeremy Davis<br>David Ozer\n| writer         = G.O. Parsons\n| starring       = [[Nicolas Cage]]<br>[[Caylee Cowan]]<br>[[Beth Grant]]<br>Emily Tosta\n| editing        = Ryan Liebert\n| studio         = JD Entertainment<br>Landafar Entertainment<br>Landmark Studio Group\n| runtime        = 97 minute\n| cinematography = David Newbert\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Wally's Wonderland''''' is an upcoming American [[Thriller film|thriller]] film directed by [[Kevin Lewis]] and starring [[Nicolas Cage]], Emily Tosta, [[Beth Grant]], [[Grant Cramer]] and [[Caylee Cowan]]. \n\n==Synopis==\nThe Janitor ([[Nicolas Cage]]) is a quiet drifter who is tricked into a janitorial job at the condemned Wally's Wonderland. His mundane tasks suddenly become an all-out fight for survival against wave after wave of demonic animatronics. He teams up with a group of teens who also find their way into the park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/charles-roven-atlas-entertainment-launches-literary-division-1203494568/|title=Film News Roundup: Charles Roven\u2019s Atlas Entertainment Launches Literary Division|last=McNary|first=Dave|last2=McNary|first2=Dave|date=2020-02-06|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/nicolas-cage-star-genre-thriller-wallys-wonderland-haunted-amusement-park-1202771823/|title=Nicolas Cage To Star In Genre Thriller \u2018Wally\u2019s Wonderland\u2019|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|last2=Wiseman|first2=Andreas|date=2019-10-29|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Nicolas Cage]] as the Janitor\n*Emily Tosta as Liv\n*[[Caylee Cowan]] as Kathy\n*[[Beth Grant]] as Sheriff Lund\n*[[Grant Cramer]] as Jerry Wallace\n*[[Ric Reitz]] as Tex Macadoo\n*[[Chris Warner]] as Jed Love\n*Terayle Hill as Bobby\n*Christian Delgrosso as Aaron\n*Kai Kadlec as Chris\n*Jessica Graves Davis as Siren Sara\n\n==Production==\n\nFilming took place in and around [[Atlanta, Georgia]].\n\nThe picture was announced in October 2019 by Deadline, directed by American film-maker [[Kevin Lewis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/nicolas-cage-star-genre-thriller-wallys-wonderland-haunted-amusement-park-1202771823/|title=Nicolas Cage To Star In Genre Thriller \u2018Wally\u2019s Wonderland\u2019|work=[[Deadline (magazine)|Deadline]]|publisher= Andreas Wiseman |date=29 October 2019|accessdate= 3 February 2020|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/party-five-emily-tosta-joins-nicolas-cage-wallys-wonderland-1202851916/|title= \u2018Party Of Five\u2019 Star Emily Tosta Joins Nicolas Cage In Genre Thriller \u2018Wally\u2019s Wonderland\u2019 |work=[[deadline.com]]|publisher=[[deadline.com]]|date=5 February 2020|accessdate= 3 February 2020|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|8114980|Wally's Wonderland}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n", "name_user": "FilmLover72", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wally%27s_Wonderland"}
{"title_page": "David Ross (businessman)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = David Ross\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = David Peter John Ross\n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|1965|7|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Grimsby]], England\n| nationality               = British\n| education                 = [[Uppingham School]]\n| alma_mater                = [[University of Nottingham]]\n| occupation                = Businessman \n| known for                 = Co-founder of [[Carphone Warehouse]]\n| net_worth                 = \u00a31.0 billion (April 2015)<ref name=STRL />\n| years_active              = 1988&ndash;present \n| spouse                    = \n| partner                   = \n| children                  = 1 son\n| relatives                 = [[Carl Ross]] (grandfather)\n| website                   = {{URL|http://www.davidpeterjohnross.com}}\n}}\n\n'''David Peter John Ross''' (born 10 July 1965) is an English billionaire businessman, and one of the co-founders (with [[Charles Dunstone]] and [[Guy Johnson (businessman)|Guy Johnson]]) of [[Carphone Warehouse]]. At the peak valuation of his business interests in 2008, Ross was one of the 100 richest people in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"independent2008\">{{cite news|last=|first=|date=9 December 2008|work=[[The Independent]]|title=David Ross: The tycoon who fell to earth|quote=This year's Sunday Times Rich List recorded Mr Ross as the 87th-richest man in the UK with an estimated personal wealth of \u00a3873m.|accessdate=13 December 2008|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/david-ross-the-tycoon-who-fell-to-earth-1058023.html | location=London}}</ref>  In 2008, ''[[Forbes]]'' ranked him #843 in the world's richest billionaires; his net worth was estimated at US$1.4 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2008/10/billionaires08_David-Ross_B7ZH.html|title=The World's Billionaires: #843 David Ross|work=[[Forbes]]|date=5 March 2008|accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref> In April 2015, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' estimated his net worth at \u00a31.0 billion.<ref name=STRL>{{cite news|title=Sunday Times Rich List|work=The Sunday Times|issue=page 34|date=26 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRoss was born on 10 July 1965.<ref name=\"Debrett's\" /> He is a grandson of [[Carl Ross]], who created one of the UK's largest commercial fishing firms from the family business, which eventually became [[Ross Group]], and took over the Great Grimsby Coal, Salt and Tanning Company (known as [[Cosalt]]), which was founded in 1873 as a cooperative that supplied fishing fleets. Both businesses were listed on the London Stock Exchange.<ref name=\"guardianwray\" />\n\nRoss was educated at [[Uppingham School]].<ref name=\"Debrett's\" /> At the age of 16, his father sent him to work on a building site in Algeria, which he later described: \"It was a defining moment because it was so bad I had to get away from it and be able to control my destiny\".<ref name=\"independent2008\" /> He graduated with a BA degree in law from the [[University of Nottingham]] and worked at [[Arthur Andersen]] from 1988, qualifying as a [[Chartered Accountant]] in 1991.<ref name=\"independent2008\" /><ref name=\"Debrett's\" />\n\n==Business activities==\n\n===Carphone Warehouse===\n{{main|Carphone Warehouse}}\nRoss had become friends with Charles Dunstone while at Uppingham. Dunstone went on to found Carphone Warehouse from a flat in [[Marylebone Road]], London, using \u00a36000 of his savings. Two years later, he asked Ross to join the business as finance director.<ref name=\"guardianwray\">{{cite news |title=The 'secret weapon' that blew up in Dunstone's face |first=Richard |last=Wray |work=The Guardian |date=9 December 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/dec/09/profile-david-ross |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>{{efn|Some sources say that Ross and Dunstone jointly founded the Carphone Warehouse business in 1989,<ref name=\"guardian2008\" /> and others that the pair co-founded it in 1991.<ref name=\"Debrett's\" /> There are also sources that say the initial funding of \u00a36000 came jointly, rather than just from Dunstone.<ref name=\"telegraph2008\" />}} Four years later, the business had twenty stores and thereafter continued to grow rapidly through a process of both acquisition and internal development.<ref name=\"guardian2008\" />\n\nWhile Dunstone became the public face of Carphone Warehouse, Ross (described by Dunstone as his \"secret weapon\"<ref name=\"guardianwray\" />), developed and drove the high-street retail footprint of the company by buying [[Tandy stores|Tandy]] in the UK, and developing markets in Europe and the United States. The business also expanded into other telecommunications areas, establishing the [[TalkTalk Group|TalkTalk]] [[ISP]] in 2003 and taking over other providers such as [[AOL]].<ref name=\"guardian2008\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/dec/08/carphonewarehousegroup-telecoms|title=Profile: David Ross|work=The Guardian|date=8 December 2008|accessdate=2015-01-08| location=London |first=Abhinav |last=Ramnarayan}}</ref> When Ross assisted the [[Initial Public Offering|IPO]] of Carphone Warehouse in 2000, the company had been so successful that the partners had not needed to borrow or involve outsiders: Dunstone owned half, Ross a third, and Guy Johnson most of the rest.<ref name=\"TimesProfile\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article5310334.ece|title=David Ross: glitz and glamour of the upper-class 'barrow boy' with all the right connections|work=The Times|date=9 December 2008|accessdate=2015-01-08 |location=London |first=Dan |last=Sabbagh |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nRoss was finance director from 1991 until 1996 and then joint-[[Chief Operating Officer]] of the company<ref name=\"independent2014\" /> until 2003.<ref name=\"Debrett's\" /> He started to reduce his role from 2003,<ref name=\"TimesProfile\"/> was appointed deputy chairman in July 2005<ref name=\"TelghResig\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/3681461/Carphone-Warehouse-co-founder-David-Ross-quits-after-disclosure-failure.html|title=Carphone Warehouse co-founder David Ross quits after disclosure failure|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=8 December 2008|accessdate=2015-01-08 |location=London |first=Amy |last=Wilson}}</ref> and by 2008 was a non-executive director.<ref name=\"independent2014\" />{{efn|Unlike ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', Debrett's says was non-executive deputy chairman from 2003 to 2008.<ref name=\"Debrett's\" />}}\n\nThe successful involvement of Ross in Carphone Warehouse created a demand for his services at other businesses.<ref name=\"telegraph2008\" /> He was the chairman of [[National Express]] from 2001<ref name=\"Debrett's\">{{cite web |url= http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/r/25479/David%20Peter%20John+ROSS.aspx |title=Authorised Biography \u2013 Debrett\u2019s People of Today, David Ross, Esq |work=[[Debrett's]] |accessdate=10 June 2011}}</ref>{{efn|Some sources say Ross was chairman of National Express from 2004.<ref name=\"guardian2008\" />}} and also had directorships of several other companies, including publishing and newspaper group [[Trinity Mirror]], Big Yellow Storage,<ref name=\"Debrett's\" />  and Frontiers Capital.<ref name=\"guardian2008\"/>\n\n===Kandahar Real Estate===\nA private investment business called Kandahar had been formed by Ross, comprising a team that had gained much experience of the UK high-street property market as the number of Carphone Warehouse stores had grown. In 2006, Ross set up a [[commercial property]] [[joint venture]] with the [[Morgan Stanley]] [[investment bank]]. His 50 per cent investment in the venture, which was known as Kandahar Real Estate Ltd, came from injecting the one-million square foot high-street private property portfolio of Kandahar, while Morgan Stanley injected the newly completed [[Drake Circus Shopping Centre]] in [[Plymouth]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.shopping-centre.co.uk/news/archivestory.php/aid/1496/Carphone_tycoon_buys_into_Plymouth_centre.html |work=Shopping Centre |date=20 November 2006 |title=Carphone tycoon buys into Plymouth centre |publisher=JLD Media |accessdate=2015-01-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108112436/http://www.shopping-centre.co.uk/news/archivestory.php/aid/1496/Carphone_tycoon_buys_into_Plymouth_centre.html |archive-date=8 January 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The joint venture was worth \u00a3500 million but hit problems soon after due to the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]]; in 2007 it had to arrange a \u00a3460 million refinancing deal through the [[HBOS]] bank.<ref name=\"telegraph2008\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/3686324/Loans-cast-shadow-over-empire.html |title=Loans cast shadow over empire |publisher=Daily Telegraph|date=8 December 2008 |accessdate=2015-01-08 |location=London |first=Helia |last=Ebrahimi}}</ref>\n\n===2008 resignations and aftermath===\nRoss resigned from Carphone Warehouse, National Express and Big Yellow in December 2008 after using a large proportion of his shares in the businesses as [[Collateral (finance)|collateral]] for personal loans without informing the companies, which is a breach of [[stock market]] rules.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/jun/11/david-ross-shares-carphone-big-yellow |title=Multi-millionaire entrepreneur David Ross sells shares in Carphone Warehouse and Big Yellow|first= Nick |last=Fletcher|work=[[The Guardian]] |date=11 June 2009 |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|GMG]] |location=[[London, England|London]] |issn=0261-3077 |oclc=60623878 |accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=BBC8>{{cite news |title=Shock exit of Carphone co-founder |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7770668.stm |newspaper=BBC News |date=8 December 2008 |accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/telecoms/3685872/Carphone-Warehouse-founder-under-fire-over-debts.html|title=Carphone Warehouse founder under fire over debts|publisher=Daily Telegraph|date=8 December 2008|accessdate=2015-01-08 |location=London |first1=Helia |last1=Ebrahimi |first2=Amy |last2=Wilson}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, the [[Financial Services Authority]] (FSA) said that the rules on the issue, governed by the [[EU Market Abuse Directive]], were unclear and inconsistently applied across the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ft.com/cms/s/5f7c866a-dede-11dd-9464-000077b07658,Authorised=false.html?_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F5f7c866a-dede-11dd-9464-000077b07658.html&_i_referer=#axzz1vmdhqrk6 |title=Ross set to escape action by FSA over disclosure |work=Financial Times |accessdate=19 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph20090109\">{{cite news |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Katherine |last=Griffiths |date=9 January 2009 |title=FSA gives directors amnesty as it clarifies rules after David Ross share controversy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/privateequity/4208492/FSA-gives-directors-amnesty-as-it-clarifies-rules-after-David-Ross-share-controversy.html |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> Although noting that the practice was also restricted by disclosure rules of the stock market's [[Listing Rules]], the FSA said that other directors had used their shares in a similar fashion<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2dc5f42a-e8ee-11dd-a4d0-0000779fd2ac,Authorised=false.html?_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F2dc5f42a-e8ee-11dd-a4d0-0000779fd2ac.html&_i_referer=#axzz1vmdhqrk6 |title=Executive used Barclays stake as collateral for loan from Citi |work=Financial Times |accessdate=19 June 2012 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and offered a short amnesty for declarations to be made by any directors who might have engaged in such practices.<ref name=\"telegraph20090109\" />\n\nThe Drake Circus shopping centre, which was the largest asset in the Kandahar portfolio, was sold to [[British Land]] in January 2011 for \u00a3240m.<ref>{{cite news |title=British Land buys Drake Circus |work=The Independent |date=7 January 2011 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/british-land-buys-drake-circus-2178025.html |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> Other sales followed as the portfolio was divested during the year, including shopping centres in [[Bishops Stortford]], [[Caterham]], [[Ipswich]] and [[Market Harborough]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Kandahar portfolio draws to a close |url=http://www.costar.co.uk/en/assets/news/2011/November/LIM-poised-for-Ipswich-as-Kandahar-portfolio-draws-to-a-close/ |first=Helen |last=Roxburgh |date=22 November 2011 |publisher=Costar |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\n===Cosalt===\nLike his grandfather and father before him, Ross was chairman of Cosalt, which by his time had become primarily a group of companies involved in offshore safety. He took on the role in 2007 and had a 12-month hiatus between 2008 and 2009 due to the problems relating to his pledging of shares as collateral, which had included those he held in Cosalt itself. Despite selling its marine division to raise \u00a327 million, the company was in dire financial circumstances by 2011, when Ross held 15 per cent of the shares and had loaned it money. Following a profits warning in October, Ross proposed to turn it into a privately owned business, offering \u00a3400,000 to have it delisted from the stock market, where it had had a presence since 1971. Despite doubling his offer and pumping more money into the company through his investment vehicle, disaffected shareholders rejected it. Some individual shareholders tried in December 2012 to have the [[Takeover Panel]] and Financial Services Authority investigate Ross amid claims that he had abused his position in an attempt to buy the business cheaply. Ross said that he had acted altruistically and that the company's pension fund liabilities were now twice its value. By that time, trading in shares had been suspended due to a failure to comply with regulatory requirements by April of that year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ailing Cosalt may go private |date=18 November 2011 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/ailing-cosalt-may-go-private-6263971.html?origin=internalSearch |work=The Independent |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/ross-set-to-take-cosalt-private-with-knockdown-offer-6268174.html?origin=internalSearch |work=The Independent |title=Ross set to take Cosalt private with knockdown offer |first=James |last=Moore |date=26 November 2011 |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Marine firm investors attack David Ross |date=2 December 2012 |work=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/marine-firm-investors-attack-david-ross-8373573.html?origin=internalSearch |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>{{efn|Regulatory issues arose because the inability to resolve refinancing issues meant that the company did not file accounts for the 2011 financial year. The accounts could not be filed on a [[going concern]] basis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pwc.co.uk/assets/pdf/cosalt_proposals.pdf |publisher=PwC |title=Joint Administrators' Proposals for Achieving the Purpose of Administration |date=27 March 2013 |page=5 |accessdate=2014-10-26}}</ref>}}\n\nUnable to obtain funding from existing or new lenders, or by a deal with pension fund trustees, the company was put into administration in February 2013. Ross and two banks were owed \u00a317 million and Ross held 46 per cent of the shares.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Independent |title=Carphone founder's family firm Cosalt folds |date=15 February 2013 |first=Nick |last=Goodway |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/carphone-founders-family-firm-cosalt-folds-8497632.html?origin=internalSearch |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>{{efn|Ross had bought more shares in Cosalt as his attempt to privatise the company went on.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ross buys 74m Cosalt shares |date=16 December 2011 |publisher=shareprice.com |url=http://www.shareprice.com/share-news/p88bqqvhp1.html |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>}}\n\nThe business had a \u00a350 million pension deficit when it fell into administration. According to ''[[Private Eye]]'', after its collapse Ross bought the company's assets at \"knockdown prices\" and recovered \"far more of his money than anyone else.\"<ref name=\"eye1377\">{{cite news |date=17 October 2014 |title=Go for gold! |newspaper=Private Eye |page=29 |issue=1377 }}</ref> Partners from [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] were joint administrators of the business. Amongst their actions was the subsequent sale of the Ballyclare workwear division to Ross for \u00a35.8 million. They said: \"This sale ensured continued trading for the business and continued employment of all the companies' staff&nbsp;... The alternative offers would have resulted in further insolvencies within the Group which would have resulted in lower realisations and increased costs\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pwc.co.uk/assets/pdf/cosalt_proposals.pdf |publisher=PwC |title=Joint Administrators' Proposals for Achieving the Purpose of Administration |date=27 March 2013 |page=7 |accessdate=2014-10-26}}</ref> In the same year, Ross also acquired Simon Jersey, adding to his workwear portfolio.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thebusinessdesk.com/northwest/news/564569-david-ross-acquires-simon-jersey.html |work=The Business Desk |title=David Ross acquires Simon Jersey |date=13 January 2014 |first=James |last=Graham |accessdate=2015-02-03}}</ref>\n\nThe decision of the [[Insolvency Service]] not to disqualify directors of Cosalt from holding future office has been questioned in [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Parliament]]. [[Jo Swinson]], then a minister, said that \"there was insufficient evidence of relevant misconduct for it to be in the public interest to investigate further since the issues raised are unlikely to be viewed by the Court as serious enough\". She also said a potential criminal prosecution of the directors for failure to file accounts had been rejected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2014-12-17.219223.h |title=Cosalt: Written question - 219223 |date=7 January 2015 |work= |publisher= UK Parliament |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\n===Other business activities===\nIn 2013, Ross resigned as Deputy Chairman of the Humberside [[Local Enterprise Partnership]]. He had become involved when Cosalt was investing in the area with proposals for wind-generated energy but the collapse of that company meant that he had little in the way of involvement in local business and was having to spend more of his time elsewhere. The Ballyclare workwear division was based in [[Barnsley]] and [[Stockport]], neither of which are on Humberside.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Ross: 'I will do all I can to support Humber LEP' |work=The Grimsby Telegraph |date=10 April 2013 |url=http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/David-Ross-support-Humber-LEP/story-18663396-detail/story.html#ixzz3OFjYbvly |archive-url=https://archive.today/20150115062930/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/David-Ross-support-Humber-LEP/story-18663396-detail/story.html%23ixzz3OFjYbvly |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 January 2015 |accessdate=2015-01-08 }}</ref>\n\nRoss, who has a strong personal interest in sport, was for some time on the board of [[Wembley Stadium]]<ref name=\"TimesProfile\" />{{clarify|reason=I think this means WSNL but the source does not say that|date=January 2015}} and, with his friend [[Gary Lineker]], was part of the consortium which rescued [[Leicester City Football Club]] from [[receivership]], before it was later sold to [[Milan Mandari\u0107]].<ref name=\"guardian2008\" />\n\n==Other activities==\n\n===Politics===\nRoss is a member of ''The Leader's Group'' of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite news |work=The Independent |title=Millions of taxpayers' cash spent on venture capital fund run by Tory donor |first=Jane |last=Merrick |date=6 July 2014 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/millions-of-taxpayers-cash-spent-on-venture-capital-fund-run-by-tory-donor-9587243.html |accessdate=2015-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.conservatives.com/Donate/Donor_Clubs.aspx |title=Donor Clubs |publisher=Conservative Party |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> The group has been described by ''[[The Independent]]'' as \"an elite diners' club whose members get frequent access to [[David Cameron]] in exchange for donating more than \u00a350,000 a year\".<ref name=\"independent2014\" /> In total, he had donated more than \u00a3700,000 to the party by February 2020, including \u00a310,000 for [[Boris Johnson]]'s leadership campaign in 2019.<ref>{{cite journal|work=Private Eye|title=Freeport Freebie|date=21 February 2020|issue=1516|page=11}}</ref>\n\n===Charitable activities and the arts===\nRoss was appointed by [[Tony Blair]] to the board of the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]] for a four-year term in February 2006. This was to satisfy the Gallery's desire to recruit \"a person with senior level of financial, accounting, strategic planning and risk management skills\".<ref>{{cite web |title=David Ross appointed to board of the National Portrait Gallery |publisher=10 Downing Street |date=17 February 2006 |url=http://www.pm.gov.uk/output/page9080.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403011057/http://www.pm.gov.uk/output/page9080.asp |archivedate=2007-04-03 |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> There were accusations of [[cronyism]] later in that year when it emerged that the Gallery had commissioned a photographic portrait of Ross, among other telecoms-related subjects, but the Gallery noted that he had not been involved with the organisation at the time of commissioning.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cronyism row hits National Portrait Gallery over pictures of future trustee |first=Guy |last=Adams |date=13 October 2006 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/cronyism-row-hits-national-portrait-gallery-over-pictures-of-future-trustee-419875.html |work=The Independent |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> {{as of|2015}}, he is a trustee of the Gallery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.npg.org.uk/about/corporate/trustees-and-trustees-meetings/list-of-trustees.php |title=List of trustees |publisher=National Portrait Gallery |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, Ross participated in \"The Dallaglio Flintoff Cycle Slam 2012\" charity cycle ride from [[Olympia, Greece]] to [[Stratford, London]] in aid of [[Andrew Flintoff]] and [[Lawrence Dallaglio]]'s respective charities.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/9250772/Halfords-back-Flintoff-and-Dallaglio-to-boost-pedal-power.html |title=Halfords back Flintoff and Dallaglio to boost pedal power|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=[[London, UK|London]]|accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> He hosts the annual [[Nevill Holt Opera]] festival.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2008/0324/162.html |title=Opera Man|work=Forbes |first=Chaniga |last=Vorasarun |date=3 July 2008 |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\nRoss, brought up in [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]], sponsored the David P J Ross Vault at [[Lincoln Castle]], which houses [[Lincoln Cathedral]]'s copy of the 1215 [[Magna Carta]] and the 1217 [[Charter of the Forest]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Foyle|first1=Jonathan|title=Lincoln: a Magna Carta city|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eedf66b8-bd0a-11e4-9902-00144feab7de|website=Financial Times|accessdate=11 April 2018|date=6 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nRoss founded the David Ross Foundation in 2006. It believes that \u201cevery child and young person has passions and talents\u201d and that its intention is to \"help them discover their strengths by offering them a wide range of world class educational opportunities\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidrossfoundation.co.uk/about/|title=About The David Ross Foundation|publisher=David Ross Foundation|accessdate=2015-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128084440/http://www.davidrossfoundation.co.uk/about/|archive-date=28 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> It has funded the David Ross Education Trust, which operates various [[Academy (English school)|academies]] and at least one [[free school (England)|free school]] in England.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" /> Its first academy was sponsored in 2007; by July 2014 it was running 25 educational establishments in the country.<ref name=\"independent2014\">{{cite news |work=The Independent |title='Conflict of interest': Outcry at plan to put multimillionaire Tory donor David Ross in charge of Ofsted  |first=Richard |last=Garner |date=4 July 2014 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/conflict-of-interest-outcry-at-plan-to-put-tory-donor-in-charge-of-ofsted-9585747.html |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2015}}, he is a member of Nottingham University's Council.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/universitycouncil/members.aspx |title=Members \u2013 The University of Nottingham |publisher=University of Nottingham |year=2015|accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> He had been shortlisted for the role of chairman of [[Ofsted]] by an independent panel in 2014 but his involvement went no further due to objections from the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] regarding a potential conflict of interest relating to his past political donations.<ref name=\"independent2014a\">{{cite news |work=The Independent |title=New Ofsted boss embarrassed by problems at his own academy chain |first=Andrew |last=Grice |date=31 July 2014 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/new-ofsted-boss-embarrassed-by-problems-at-his-own-academy-chain-9641045.html?origin=internalSearch |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>{{efn|There had been speculation that, aside from the issue of political donations, appointing Ross as Ofsted chairman would also create a conflict of interest because of his direct involvement with academies.<ref name=\"independent2014\" /> However, David Hoare, who was eventually selected for the role, also had an involvement but was free of political ties.<ref name=\"independent2014a\" />}}\n\n===Sport===\nAfter [[Boris Johnson]] was elected [[Mayor of London]] in May 2008, Ross was his nominee to the board of the [[London Organising Committee for the Olympic Games|London Organising Committee]] of the [[2012 Olympic Games]]. He resigned from this position December 2008 in the wake of the same event that led to his departure from the board of Carphone Warehouse.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/dec/09/boris-carphone-warehouse?guni=Article:in%20body%20link |title=David Ross resigns from Olympics panel and National Express board |first1=Richard |last1=Wray |first2=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne |last2=Mulholland |date=9 December 2008 |accessdate=2015-01-09}}</ref> Johnson has also appointed Ross to the board of the [[London Legacy Development Corporation]] which has responsibility for redevelopment of Olympic Park in Legacy mode<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/media/mayor-press-releases/2012/12/baroness-grey-thompson-dbe-appointed-to-strengthen-2012-legacy|title=Baroness Grey-Thompson DBE appointed to strengthen 2012 legacy team|date=3 December 2012|publisher=london.gov.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planningresource.co.uk/article/1162714/phone-boss-quit-locog-appointed-2012-legacy-board|title=Phone boss who quit LOCOG appointed to 2012 legacy board|last=Cook|first=Ben|date=4 December 2012|publisher=planningresource.co.uk}}</ref> and to London United, the body that supported the capital's bid to be [[2018 FIFA World Cup#Host selection|host city for the 2018 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard-olympics/article-23713608-details/Boris+Johnson+on+London%27s+role+in+World+Cup+bid/article.do|title=Boris Johnson on London's role in 2018 World Cup bid|publisher=The Evening Standard|date=30 June 2009|first=Matthew|last=Beard|accessdate=2015-01-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706075319/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard-olympics/article-23713608-details/Boris+Johnson+on+London's+role+in+World+Cup+bid/article.do|archive-date=6 July 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCurrently in 2013, Ross is a member of the [[Commonwealth Games England]] board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weareengland.org/home/news/captains-of-industry-and-sport-join-commonwealth-games-england?search=|title=Captains of industry and sport join Commonwealth Games England|date=17 September 2009|publisher=weareengland.org}}</ref> He is also a non-executive director of the [[British Olympic Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teamgb.com/news/carphone-warehouse-co-founder-answers-call-boa-board|title=Carphone Warehouse Co-Founder Answers Call of BOA Board|date=2 June 2011|publisher=teamgb.com}}</ref>\n\nRoss has supported his [[alma mater]], the [[University of Nottingham]] to build a brand new \u00a340 million sports centre in the University Park Campus, named the [[David Ross Sports Village]], which opened in October 2016.<ref>[https://www.nottingham.ac.uk/currentstudents/news/2017/olympic-seal-of-approval-for-new-david-ross-sports-village.aspx Olympic seal of approval for new David Ross Sports Village], 18th May 2017, The University of Nottingham</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRoss has a son with Michelle \"Shelley\" Ross, a former partner whom he did not marry but who happened to have the same surname. He has also been in relationships with high-profile women such as [[Saffron Aldridge]] and Ali Cockayne.<ref name=\"guardianwray\" />\n\nRoss's main residence is the 13th-century, [[Listed building|Grade I-listed]] [[Nevill Holt]] estate, near [[Market Harborough]], [[Leicestershire]], on which he has spent millions. In addition, he has, or has had, homes in [[Kensington]] and [[Mustique]], and in Switzerland,<ref name=\"guardianwray\" /> where he spent some time as a [[tax exile]].<ref name=\"guardian2014\">{{cite news |title=Wealthy Tory donor David Ross in line for top Ofsted job |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/jul/04/wealthy-tory-donor-david-ross-ofsted-chair |first=Richard |last=Adams |date=4 July 2014 |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> He owned a second [[country estate]], at [[Brampton Ash]] in [[Northamptonshire]]; his stepsister, Fiona, was murdered there in 2006 and in 2008 he decided to sell it. He has a reputation for partying and a love of shooting, pursuing the latter interest with people such as Lineker and [[Richard Branson]]. In 2007 he bought {{convert|4500|ha|acres}} of [[grouse moor]] in [[Yorkshire]].<ref name=\"guardianwray\" />\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ross, David}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Nottingham]]\n[[Category:English accountants]]\n[[Category:British billionaires]]\n[[Category:Chief operating officers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Uppingham School]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = David Ross\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = David Peter John Ross\n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|1965|7|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Grimsby]], England\n| nationality               = British\n| education                 = [[Uppingham School]]\n| alma_mater                = [[University of Nottingham]]\n| occupation                = Businessman \n| known for                 = Co-founder of [[Carphone Warehouse]]\n| net_worth                 = \u00a31.0 billion (April 2015)<ref name=STRL />\n| years_active              = 1988&ndash;present \n| spouse                    = \n| partner                   = \n| children                  = 1 son\n| relatives                 = [[Carl Ross]] (grandfather)\n| website                   = {{URL|http://www.davidpeterjohnross.com}}\n}}\n\n'''David Peter John Ross''' (born 10 July 1965) is an English billionaire businessman, and one of the co-founders (with [[Charles Dunstone]] and [[Guy Johnson (businessman)|Guy Johnson]]) of [[Carphone Warehouse]]. At the peak valuation of his business interests in 2008, Ross was one of the 100 richest people in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"independent2008\">{{cite news|last=|first=|date=9 December 2008|work=[[The Independent]]|title=David Ross: The tycoon who fell to earth|quote=This year's Sunday Times Rich List recorded Mr Ross as the 87th-richest man in the UK with an estimated personal wealth of \u00a3873m.|accessdate=13 December 2008|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/david-ross-the-tycoon-who-fell-to-earth-1058023.html | location=London}}</ref>  In 2008, ''[[Forbes]]'' ranked him #843 in the world's richest billionaires; his net worth was estimated at US$1.4 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2008/10/billionaires08_David-Ross_B7ZH.html|title=The World's Billionaires: #843 David Ross|work=[[Forbes]]|date=5 March 2008|accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref> In April 2015, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' estimated his net worth at \u00a31.0 billion.<ref name=STRL>{{cite news|title=Sunday Times Rich List|work=The Sunday Times|issue=page 34|date=26 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRoss was born on 10 July 1965.<ref name=\"Debrett's\" /> He is a grandson of [[Carl Ross]], who created one of the UK's largest commercial fishing firms from the family business, which eventually became [[Ross Group]], and took over the Great Grimsby Coal, Salt and Tanning Company (known as [[Cosalt]]), which was founded in 1873 as a cooperative that supplied fishing fleets. Both businesses were listed on the London Stock Exchange.<ref name=\"guardianwray\" />\n\nRoss was educated at [[Uppingham School]].<ref name=\"Debrett's\" /> At the age of 16, his father sent him to work on a building site in Algeria, which he later described: \"It was a defining moment because it was so bad I had to get away from it and be able to control my destiny\".<ref name=\"independent2008\" /> He graduated with a BA degree in law from the [[University of Nottingham]] and worked at [[Arthur Andersen]] from 1988, qualifying as a [[Chartered Accountant]] in 1991.<ref name=\"independent2008\" /><ref name=\"Debrett's\" />\n\n==Business activities==\n\n===Carphone Warehouse===\n{{main article|Carphone Warehouse}}\nRoss had become friends with Charles Dunstone while at Uppingham. Dunstone went on to found Carphone Warehouse from a flat in [[Marylebone Road]], London, using \u00a36000 of his savings. Two years later, he asked Ross to join the business as finance director.<ref name=\"guardianwray\">{{cite news |title=The 'secret weapon' that blew up in Dunstone's face |first=Richard |last=Wray |work=The Guardian |date=9 December 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/dec/09/profile-david-ross |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>{{efn|Some sources say that Ross and Dunstone jointly founded the Carphone Warehouse business in 1989,<ref name=\"guardian2008\" /> and others that the pair co-founded it in 1991.<ref name=\"Debrett's\" /> There are also sources that say the initial funding of \u00a36000 came jointly, rather than just from Dunstone.<ref name=\"telegraph2008\" />}} Four years later, the business had twenty stores and thereafter continued to grow rapidly through a process of both acquisition and internal development.<ref name=\"guardian2008\" />\n\nWhile Dunstone became the public face of Carphone Warehouse, Ross (described by Dunstone as his \"secret weapon\"<ref name=\"guardianwray\" />), developed and drove the high-street retail footprint of the company by buying [[Tandy stores|Tandy]] in the UK, and developing markets in Europe and the United States. The business also expanded into other telecommunications areas, establishing the [[TalkTalk Group|TalkTalk]] [[ISP]] in 2003 and taking over other providers such as [[AOL]].<ref name=\"guardian2008\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/dec/08/carphonewarehousegroup-telecoms|title=Profile: David Ross|work=The Guardian|date=8 December 2008|accessdate=2015-01-08| location=London |first=Abhinav |last=Ramnarayan}}</ref> When Ross assisted the [[Initial Public Offering|IPO]] of Carphone Warehouse in 2000, the company had been so successful that the partners had not needed to borrow or involve outsiders: Dunstone owned half, Ross a third, and Guy Johnson most of the rest.<ref name=\"TimesProfile\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article5310334.ece|title=David Ross: glitz and glamour of the upper-class 'barrow boy' with all the right connections|work=The Times|date=9 December 2008|accessdate=2015-01-08 |location=London |first=Dan |last=Sabbagh |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nRoss was finance director from 1991 until 1996 and then joint-[[Chief Operating Officer]] of the company<ref name=\"independent2014\" /> until 2003.<ref name=\"Debrett's\" /> He started to reduce his role from 2003,<ref name=\"TimesProfile\"/> was appointed deputy chairman in July 2005<ref name=\"TelghResig\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/3681461/Carphone-Warehouse-co-founder-David-Ross-quits-after-disclosure-failure.html|title=Carphone Warehouse co-founder David Ross quits after disclosure failure|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=8 December 2008|accessdate=2015-01-08 |location=London |first=Amy |last=Wilson}}</ref> and by 2008 was a non-executive director.<ref name=\"independent2014\" />{{efn|Unlike ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', Debrett's says was non-executive deputy chairman from 2003 to 2008.<ref name=\"Debrett's\" />}}\n\nThe successful involvement of Ross in Carphone Warehouse created a demand for his services at other businesses.<ref name=\"telegraph2008\" /> He was the chairman of [[National Express]] from 2001<ref name=\"Debrett's\">{{cite web |url= http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/r/25479/David%20Peter%20John+ROSS.aspx |title=Authorised Biography \u2013 Debrett\u2019s People of Today, David Ross, Esq |work=[[Debrett's]] |accessdate=10 June 2011}}</ref>{{efn|Some sources say Ross was chairman of National Express from 2004.<ref name=\"guardian2008\" />}} and also had directorships of several other companies, including publishing and newspaper group [[Trinity Mirror]], Big Yellow Storage,<ref name=\"Debrett's\" />  and Frontiers Capital.<ref name=\"guardian2008\"/>\n\n===Kandahar Real Estate===\nA private investment business called Kandahar had been formed by Ross, comprising a team that had gained much experience of the UK high-street property market as the number of Carphone Warehouse stores had grown. In 2006, Ross set up a [[commercial property]] [[joint venture]] with the [[Morgan Stanley]] [[investment bank]]. His 50 per cent investment in the venture, which was known as Kandahar Real Estate Ltd, came from injecting the one-million square foot high-street private property portfolio of Kandahar, while Morgan Stanley injected the newly completed [[Drake Circus Shopping Centre]] in [[Plymouth]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.shopping-centre.co.uk/news/archivestory.php/aid/1496/Carphone_tycoon_buys_into_Plymouth_centre.html |work=Shopping Centre |date=20 November 2006 |title=Carphone tycoon buys into Plymouth centre |publisher=JLD Media |accessdate=2015-01-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108112436/http://www.shopping-centre.co.uk/news/archivestory.php/aid/1496/Carphone_tycoon_buys_into_Plymouth_centre.html |archive-date=8 January 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The joint venture was worth \u00a3500 million but hit problems soon after due to the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]]; in 2007 it had to arrange a \u00a3460 million refinancing deal through the [[HBOS]] bank.<ref name=\"telegraph2008\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/3686324/Loans-cast-shadow-over-empire.html |title=Loans cast shadow over empire |publisher=Daily Telegraph|date=8 December 2008 |accessdate=2015-01-08 |location=London |first=Helia |last=Ebrahimi}}</ref>\n\n===2008 resignations and aftermath===\nRoss resigned from Carphone Warehouse, National Express and Big Yellow in December 2008 after using a large proportion of his shares in the businesses as [[Collateral (finance)|collateral]] for personal loans without informing the companies, which is a breach of [[stock market]] rules.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/jun/11/david-ross-shares-carphone-big-yellow |title=Multi-millionaire entrepreneur David Ross sells shares in Carphone Warehouse and Big Yellow|first= Nick |last=Fletcher|work=[[The Guardian]] |date=11 June 2009 |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|GMG]] |location=[[London, England|London]] |issn=0261-3077 |oclc=60623878 |accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=BBC8>{{cite news |title=Shock exit of Carphone co-founder |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7770668.stm |newspaper=BBC news |date=8 December 2008 |accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/telecoms/3685872/Carphone-Warehouse-founder-under-fire-over-debts.html|title=Carphone Warehouse founder under fire over debts|publisher=Daily Telegraph|date=8 December 2008|accessdate=2015-01-08 |location=London |first1=Helia |last1=Ebrahimi |first2=Amy |last2=Wilson}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, the [[Financial Services Authority]] (FSA) said that the rules on the issue, governed by the [[EU Market Abuse Directive]], were unclear and inconsistently applied across the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ft.com/cms/s/5f7c866a-dede-11dd-9464-000077b07658,Authorised=false.html?_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F5f7c866a-dede-11dd-9464-000077b07658.html&_i_referer=#axzz1vmdhqrk6 |title=Ross set to escape action by FSA over disclosure |work=Financial Times |accessdate=19 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph20090109\">{{cite news |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Katherine |last=Griffiths |date=9 January 2009 |title=FSA gives directors amnesty as it clarifies rules after David Ross share controversy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/privateequity/4208492/FSA-gives-directors-amnesty-as-it-clarifies-rules-after-David-Ross-share-controversy.html |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref> Although noting that the practice was also restricted by disclosure rules of the stock market's [[Listing Rules]], the FSA said that other directors had used their shares in a similar fashion<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2dc5f42a-e8ee-11dd-a4d0-0000779fd2ac,Authorised=false.html?_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F2dc5f42a-e8ee-11dd-a4d0-0000779fd2ac.html&_i_referer=#axzz1vmdhqrk6 |title=Executive used Barclays stake as collateral for loan from Citi |work=Financial Times |accessdate=19 June 2012 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and offered a short amnesty for declarations to be made by any directors who might have engaged in such practices.<ref name=\"telegraph20090109\" />\n\nThe Drake Circus shopping centre, which was the largest asset in the Kandahar portfolio, was sold to [[British Land]] in January 2011 for \u00a3240m.<ref>{{cite news |title=British Land buys Drake Circus |work=The Independent |date=7 January 2011 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/british-land-buys-drake-circus-2178025.html |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> Other sales followed as the portfolio was divested during the year, including shopping centres in [[Bishops Stortford]], [[Caterham]], [[Ipswich]] and [[Market Harborough]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Kandahar portfolio draws to a close |url=http://www.costar.co.uk/en/assets/news/2011/November/LIM-poised-for-Ipswich-as-Kandahar-portfolio-draws-to-a-close/ |first=Helen |last=Roxburgh |date=22 November 2011 |publisher=Costar |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\n===Cosalt===\nLike his grandfather and father before him, Ross was chairman of Cosalt, which by his time had become primarily a group of companies involved in offshore safety. He took on the role in 2007 and had a 12-month hiatus between 2008 and 2009 due to the problems relating to his pledging of shares as collateral, which had included those he held in Cosalt itself. Despite selling its marine division to raise \u00a327 million, the company was in dire financial circumstances by 2011, when Ross held 15 per cent of the shares and had loaned it money. Following a profits warning in October, Ross proposed to turn it into a privately owned business, offering \u00a3400,000 to have it delisted from the stock market, where it had had a presence since 1971. Despite doubling his offer and pumping more money into the company through his investment vehicle, disaffected shareholders rejected it. Some individual shareholders tried in December 2012 to have the [[Takeover Panel]] and Financial Services Authority investigate Ross amid claims that he had abused his position in an attempt to buy the business cheaply. Ross said that he had acted altruistically and that the company's pension fund liabilities were now twice its value. By that time, trading in shares had been suspended due to a failure to comply with regulatory requirements by April of that year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ailing Cosalt may go private |date=18 November 2011 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/ailing-cosalt-may-go-private-6263971.html?origin=internalSearch |work=The Independent |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/ross-set-to-take-cosalt-private-with-knockdown-offer-6268174.html?origin=internalSearch |work=The Independent |title=Ross set to take Cosalt private with knockdown offer |first=James |last=Moore |date=26 November 2011 |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Marine firm investors attack David Ross |date=2 December 2012 |work=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/marine-firm-investors-attack-david-ross-8373573.html?origin=internalSearch |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>{{efn|Regulatory issues arose because the inability to resolve refinancing issues meant that the company did not file accounts for the 2011 financial year. The accounts could not be filed on a [[going concern]] basis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pwc.co.uk/assets/pdf/cosalt_proposals.pdf |publisher=PwC |title=Joint Administrators' Proposals for Achieving the Purpose of Administration |date=27 March 2013 |page=5 |accessdate=2014-10-26}}</ref>}}\n\nUnable to obtain funding from existing or new lenders, or by a deal with pension fund trustees, the company was put into administration in February 2013. Ross and two banks were owed \u00a317 million and Ross held 46 per cent of the shares.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Independent |title=Carphone founder's family firm Cosalt folds |date=15 February 2013 |first=Nick |last=Goodway |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/carphone-founders-family-firm-cosalt-folds-8497632.html?origin=internalSearch |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>{{efn|Ross had bought more shares in Cosalt as his attempt to privatise the company went on.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ross buys 74m Cosalt shares |date=16 December 2011 |publisher=shareprice.com |url=http://www.shareprice.com/share-news/p88bqqvhp1.html |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>}}\n\nThe business had a \u00a350 million pension deficit when it fell into administration. According to ''[[Private Eye]]'', after its collapse Ross bought the company's assets at \"knockdown prices\" and recovered \"far more of his money than anyone else.\"<ref name=\"eye1377\">{{cite news |date=17 October 2014 |title=Go for gold! |newspaper=Private Eye |page=29 |issue=1377 }}</ref> Partners from [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] were joint administrators of the business. Amongst their actions was the subsequent sale of the Ballyclare workwear division to Ross for \u00a35.8 million. They said: \"This sale ensured continued trading for the business and continued employment of all the companies' staff&nbsp;... The alternative offers would have resulted in further insolvencies within the Group which would have resulted in lower realisations and increased costs\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pwc.co.uk/assets/pdf/cosalt_proposals.pdf |publisher=PwC |title=Joint Administrators' Proposals for Achieving the Purpose of Administration |date=27 March 2013 |page=7 |accessdate=2014-10-26}}</ref> In the same year, Ross also acquired Simon Jersey, adding to his workwear portfolio.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thebusinessdesk.com/northwest/news/564569-david-ross-acquires-simon-jersey.html |work=The Business Desk |title=David Ross acquires Simon Jersey |date=13 January 2014 |first=James |last=Graham |accessdate=2015-02-03}}</ref>\n\nThe decision of the [[Insolvency Service]] not to disqualify directors of Cosalt from holding future office has been questioned in [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Parliament]]. [[Jo Swinson]], then a minister, said that \"there was insufficient evidence of relevant misconduct for it to be in the public interest to investigate further since the issues raised are unlikely to be viewed by the Court as serious enough\". She also said a potential criminal prosecution of the directors for failure to file accounts had been rejected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2014-12-17.219223.h |title=Cosalt: Written question - 219223 |date=7 January 2015 |work= |publisher= UK Parliament |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\n===Other business activities===\nIn 2013, Ross resigned as Deputy Chairman of the Humberside [[Local Enterprise Partnership]]. He had become involved when Cosalt was investing in the area with proposals for wind-generated energy but the collapse of that company meant that he had little in the way of involvement in local business and was having to spend more of his time elsewhere. The Ballyclare workwear division was based in [[Barnsley]] and [[Stockport]], neither of which are on Humberside.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Ross: 'I will do all I can to support Humber LEP' |work=The Grimsby Telegraph |date=10 April 2013 |url=http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/David-Ross-support-Humber-LEP/story-18663396-detail/story.html#ixzz3OFjYbvly |archive-url=https://archive.today/20150115062930/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/David-Ross-support-Humber-LEP/story-18663396-detail/story.html%23ixzz3OFjYbvly |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 January 2015 |accessdate=2015-01-08 }}</ref>\n\nRoss, who has a strong personal interest in sport, was for some time on the board of [[Wembley Stadium]]<ref name=\"TimesProfile\" />{{clarify|reason=I think this means WSNL but the source does not say that|date=January 2015}} and, with his friend [[Gary Lineker]], was part of the consortium which rescued [[Leicester City Football Club]] from [[receivership]], before it was later sold to [[Milan Mandari\u0107]].<ref name=\"guardian2008\" />\n\n==Other activities==\n\n===Politics===\nRoss is a member of ''The Leader's Group'' of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite news |work=The Independent |title=Millions of taxpayers' cash spent on venture capital fund run by Tory donor |first=Jane |last=Merrick |date=6 July 2014 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/millions-of-taxpayers-cash-spent-on-venture-capital-fund-run-by-tory-donor-9587243.html |accessdate=2015-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.conservatives.com/Donate/Donor_Clubs.aspx |title=Donor Clubs |publisher=Conservative Party |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> The group has been described by ''[[The Independent]]'' as \"an elite diners' club whose members get frequent access to [[David Cameron]] in exchange for donating more than \u00a350,000 a year\".<ref name=\"independent2014\" /> In total, he had donated more than \u00a3700,000 to the party by February 2020, including \u00a310,000 for [[Boris Johnson]]'s leadership campaign in 2019.<ref>{{cite journal|work=Private Eye|title=Freeport Freebie|date=21 February 2020|issue=1516|page=11}}</ref>\n\n===Charitable activities and the arts===\nRoss was appointed by [[Tony Blair]] to the board of the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]] for a four-year term in February 2006. This was to satisfy the Gallery's desire to recruit \"a person with senior level of financial, accounting, strategic planning and risk management skills\".<ref>{{cite web |title=David Ross appointed to board of the National Portrait Gallery |publisher=10 Downing Street |date=17 February 2006 |url=http://www.pm.gov.uk/output/page9080.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403011057/http://www.pm.gov.uk/output/page9080.asp |archivedate=2007-04-03 |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> There were accusations of [[cronyism]] later in that year when it emerged that the Gallery had commissioned a photographic portrait of Ross, among other telecoms-related subjects, but the Gallery noted that he had not been involved with the organisation at the time of commissioning.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cronyism row hits National Portrait Gallery over pictures of future trustee |first=Guy |last=Adams |date=13 October 2006 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/cronyism-row-hits-national-portrait-gallery-over-pictures-of-future-trustee-419875.html |work=The Independent |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> {{as of|2015}}, he is a trustee of the Gallery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.npg.org.uk/about/corporate/trustees-and-trustees-meetings/list-of-trustees.php |title=List of trustees |publisher=National Portrait Gallery |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, Ross participated in \"The Dallaglio Flintoff Cycle Slam 2012\" charity cycle ride from [[Olympia, Greece]] to [[Stratford, London]] in aid of [[Andrew Flintoff]] and [[Lawrence Dallaglio]]'s respective charities.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/9250772/Halfords-back-Flintoff-and-Dallaglio-to-boost-pedal-power.html |title=Halfords back Flintoff and Dallaglio to boost pedal power|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=[[London, UK|London]]|accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> He hosts the annual [[Nevill Holt Opera]] festival.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2008/0324/162.html |title=Opera Man|work=Forbes |first=Chaniga |last=Vorasarun |date=3 July 2008 |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\nRoss, brought up in [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]], sponsored the David P J Ross Vault at [[Lincoln Castle]], which houses [[Lincoln Cathedral]]'s copy of the 1215 [[Magna Carta]] and the 1217 [[Charter of the Forest]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Foyle|first1=Jonathan|title=Lincoln: a Magna Carta city|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eedf66b8-bd0a-11e4-9902-00144feab7de|website=Financial Times|accessdate=11 April 2018|date=6 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nRoss founded the David Ross Foundation in 2006. It believes that \u201cevery child and young person has passions and talents\u201d and that its intention is to \"help them discover their strengths by offering them a wide range of world class educational opportunities\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidrossfoundation.co.uk/about/|title=About The David Ross Foundation|publisher=David Ross Foundation|accessdate=2015-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128084440/http://www.davidrossfoundation.co.uk/about/|archive-date=28 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> It has funded the David Ross Education Trust, which operates various [[Academy (English school)|academies]] and at least one [[free school (England)|free school]] in England.<ref name=\"guardian2014\" /> Its first academy was sponsored in 2007; by July 2014 it was running 25 educational establishments in the country.<ref name=\"independent2014\">{{cite news |work=The Independent |title='Conflict of interest': Outcry at plan to put multimillionaire Tory donor David Ross in charge of Ofsted  |first=Richard |last=Garner |date=4 July 2014 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/conflict-of-interest-outcry-at-plan-to-put-tory-donor-in-charge-of-ofsted-9585747.html |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2015}}, he is a member of Nottingham University's Council.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/universitycouncil/members.aspx |title=Members \u2013 The University of Nottingham |publisher=University of Nottingham |year=2015|accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> He had been shortlisted for the role of chairman of [[Ofsted]] by an independent panel in 2014 but his involvement went no further due to objections from the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] regarding a potential conflict of interest relating to his past political donations.<ref name=\"independent2014a\">{{cite news |work=The Independent |title=New Ofsted boss embarrassed by problems at his own academy chain |first=Andrew |last=Grice |date=31 July 2014 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/new-ofsted-boss-embarrassed-by-problems-at-his-own-academy-chain-9641045.html?origin=internalSearch |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref>{{efn|There had been speculation that, aside from the issue of political donations, appointing Ross as Ofsted chairman would also create a conflict of interest because of his direct involvement with academies.<ref name=\"independent2014\" /> However, David Hoare, who was eventually selected for the role, also had an involvement but was free of political ties.<ref name=\"independent2014a\" />}}\n\n===Sport===\nAfter [[Boris Johnson]] was elected [[Mayor of London]] in May 2008, Ross was his nominee to the board of the [[London Organising Committee for the Olympic Games|London Organising Committee]] of the [[2012 Olympic Games]]. He resigned from this position December 2008 in the wake of the same event that led to his departure from the board of Carphone Warehouse.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/dec/09/boris-carphone-warehouse?guni=Article:in%20body%20link |title=David Ross resigns from Olympics panel and National Express board |first1=Richard |last1=Wray |first2=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne |last2=Mulholland |date=9 December 2008 |accessdate=2015-01-09}}</ref> Johnson has also appointed Ross to the board of the [[London Legacy Development Corporation]] which has responsibility for redevelopment of Olympic Park in Legacy mode<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/media/mayor-press-releases/2012/12/baroness-grey-thompson-dbe-appointed-to-strengthen-2012-legacy|title=Baroness Grey-Thompson DBE appointed to strengthen 2012 legacy team|date=3 December 2012|publisher=london.gov.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planningresource.co.uk/article/1162714/phone-boss-quit-locog-appointed-2012-legacy-board|title=Phone boss who quit LOCOG appointed to 2012 legacy board|last=Cook|first=Ben|date=4 December 2012|publisher=planningresource.co.uk}}</ref> and to London United, the body that supported the capital's bid to be [[2018 FIFA World Cup#Host selection|host city for the 2018 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard-olympics/article-23713608-details/Boris+Johnson+on+London%27s+role+in+World+Cup+bid/article.do|title=Boris Johnson on London's role in 2018 World Cup bid|publisher=The Evening Standard|date=30 June 2009|first=Matthew|last=Beard|accessdate=2015-01-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706075319/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard-olympics/article-23713608-details/Boris+Johnson+on+London's+role+in+World+Cup+bid/article.do|archive-date=6 July 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCurrently in 2013, Ross is a member of the [[Commonwealth Games England]] board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weareengland.org/home/news/captains-of-industry-and-sport-join-commonwealth-games-england?search=|title=Captains of industry and sport join Commonwealth Games England|date=17 September 2009|publisher=weareengland.org}}</ref> He is also a non-executive director of the [[British Olympic Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teamgb.com/news/carphone-warehouse-co-founder-answers-call-boa-board|title=Carphone Warehouse Co-Founder Answers Call of BOA Board|date=2 June 2011|publisher=teamgb.com}}</ref>\n\nRoss has supported his [[alma mater]], the [[University of Nottingham]] to build a brand new \u00a340 million sports centre in the University Park Campus, named the [[David Ross Sports Village]], which opened in October 2016.<ref>[https://www.nottingham.ac.uk/currentstudents/news/2017/olympic-seal-of-approval-for-new-david-ross-sports-village.aspx Olympic seal of approval for new David Ross Sports Village], 18th May 2017, The University of Nottingham</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRoss has a son with Michelle \"Shelley\" Ross, a former partner whom he did not marry but who happened to have the same surname. He has also been in relationships with high-profile women such as [[Saffron Aldridge]] and Ali Cockayne.<ref name=\"guardianwray\" />\n\nRoss's main residence is the 13th-century, [[Listed building|Grade I-listed]] [[Nevill Holt]] estate, near [[Market Harborough]], [[Leicestershire]], on which he has spent millions. In addition, he has, or has had, homes in [[Kensington]] and [[Mustique]], and in Switzerland,<ref name=\"guardianwray\" /> where he spent some time as a [[tax exile]].<ref name=\"guardian2014\">{{cite news |title=Wealthy Tory donor David Ross in line for top Ofsted job |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/jul/04/wealthy-tory-donor-david-ross-ofsted-chair |first=Richard |last=Adams |date=4 July 2014 |accessdate=2015-01-08}}</ref> He owned a second [[country estate]], at [[Brampton Ash]] in [[Northamptonshire]]; his stepsister, Fiona, was murdered there in 2006 and in 2008 he decided to sell it. He has a reputation for partying and a love of shooting, pursuing the latter interest with people such as Lineker and [[Richard Branson]]. In 2007 he bought {{convert|4500|ha|acres}} of [[grouse moor]] in [[Yorkshire]].<ref name=\"guardianwray\" />\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ross, David}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Nottingham]]\n[[Category:English accountants]]\n[[Category:British billionaires]]\n[[Category:Chief operating officers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Uppingham School]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) people]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Caps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Ross_(businessman)"}
{"title_page": "Thammasat University massacre", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Thammasat University massacre\n| image       = File:6 \u0e15\u0e38\u0e25\u0e32.jpg\n| location    = [[Thammasat University]] and [[Sanam Luang]] in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|13|45|21.07|N|100|29|27.16|E|region:TH_type:edu|display=inline, title}}\n| target      = Student protesters\n| date        = 6 October 1976\n| fatalities  = 46 (official); 100+ (unofficial)\n| injuries    = 167 (official)\n| perps       = [[Royal Thai Armed Forces]]<br/>[[Royal Thai Police]]<br/>[[Village Scouts]]<br/>[[Nawaphon]]<br/>[[Red Gaur]]<br/>Pro Government Civilians\n}}\n\nThe '''Thammasat University massacre''' (in Thailand known simply as '''the 6 October event''', {{lang-th|\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e15\u0e38\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c 6 \u0e15\u0e38\u0e25\u0e32}} {{RTGS|het kan hok tula}}) was an attack by Thai state forces and far-right paramilitaries on student protesters on the campus of [[Thammasat University]] and the adjacent [[Sanam Luang]] Square in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]], on 6 October 1976. Prior to the massacre, four to five thousand students from various universities had demonstrated for more than a week against the return of former military dictator [[Thanom Kittikachorn]] to Thailand from [[Singapore]].\n\nA day before the massacre, the Thai press reported on a play staged by student protesters the previous day, which allegedly featured the mock hanging of then [[Vajiralongkorn|Crown Prince Vajiralongkorn]]. In response to this rumored outrage, military and police, as well as paramilitary forces surrounded the university. Just before dawn on 6 October with the protesters trapped within the campus, the government forces opened fire on them. The brutal attack lasted until noon, eventually devolving into chaos with mob beatings, rapes and lynchings. To this day, the number of casualties remains in dispute between the Thai government and survivors of the massacre. According to the government, 46 died in the killings, with 167 wounded and 3,000 arrested. Many survivors claim that the death toll was well over 100.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\">{{cite book|last1=Handley|first1=Paul M|title=The King Never Smiles; A Biography of Thailand's Bhumibol Adulyadej|date=2006|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven|isbn=0-300-10682-3|url=https://www.academia.edu/8599856/Paul_M._Handley-The_King_Never_Smiles;_A_Biography_of_Thailands_Bhumibol_Adulyadej-Yale_University_Press_2006_|accessdate=5 October 2016}}</ref>{{RP|236}}\n\n== Massacre ==\n\n=== Immediate causes ===\nThe [[1973 Thai popular uprising|14 October 1973 uprising]] overthrew the unpopular regime of Field Marshal Thanom Kittikachorn, and saw him flee Thailand together with Field Marshal [[Praphas Charusathien]] and Colonel Narong Kittikachorn, collectively known as the \"three tyrants\".<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|209}} Growing unrest and instability from 1973 to 1976, as well as the fear of communism from neighboring countries spreading to Thailand and threatening the interests of the monarchy and the military, convinced the latter to bring former leaders Thanom and Praphas back to Thailand to control the situation. In response to Praphas's return on 17 August, thousands of students demonstrated at Thammasat University for four days until a clash with [[Red Gaur]] and [[Nawaphon]] left four dead.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|233}} On 19 September, Thanom returned to Thailand and headed straight from the airport to [[Wat Bowonniwet Vihara]], where he was ordained as a monk in a private ceremony. Massive anti-Thanom protests broke out as the government faced an internal crisis after Prime Minister [[Seni Pramoj]]'s attempt to tender his resignation was rejected by the Thai Parliament. On 24 September, in [[Nakhon Pathom]], west of Bangkok, two labor-cum-activists, putting up anti-Thanom posters were beaten to death and hung from a wall, an act that was soon established to be the work of Thai police.<ref name=\"doct6\">{{cite web |title=4. \u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e01\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35 6 \u0e15\u0e38\u0e25\u0e32\u0e2f |url=https://doct6.com/learn-about/how/chapter-4 |website=https://doct6.com |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Buabmee |first1=Sunantha Buabmee |last2=Rojanaphruk |first2=Pravit |title=SCHOLARS SAVE \u2018RED GATE,\u2019 THE BACKDROP TO OCT. 1976 MASSACRE |url=https://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2019/07/03/scholars-save-red-gate-the-backdrop-to-oct-1976-massacre/ |website=Khaosod English |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|235}} A dramatization of this hanging was staged by student protesters at Thammasat University on 4 October. Either deliberately or as an unfortunate coincidence, the student at the end of the garrote bore a resemblance to Crown Prince [[Vajiralongkorn]].<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|235}} The following day, as Seni struggled to put together his cabinet, the newspaper ''Dao Siam'' ({{lang|th|\u0e14\u0e32\u0e27\u0e2a\u0e22\u0e32\u0e21}}) published a photograph of the mock hanging on its front page.<ref name=\"Mallet\">{{cite journal|last1=Mallet|first1=Marian|title=Causes and Consequences of the October '76 Coup|journal=Journal of Contemporary Asia|date=1978|volume=8|issue=1|url=http://thirdworld.nl/causes-and-consequences-of-the-october-76-coup|accessdate=5 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20161011162840/http://thirdworld.nl/causes-and-consequences-of-the-october-76-coup|archivedate=11 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{RP|90}} With the tacit approval of [[Bhumibol Adulyadej|King Bhumibol]], announcers on army-controlled radio stations accused the student protesters of [[L\u00e8se majest\u00e9 in Thailand|l\u00e8se-majest\u00e9]] and mobilized the king's paramilitary forces, the Village Scouts, Nawaphon, and Red Gaurs to \"kill the communists\".<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|235}} At dusk on 5 October, some 4,000 people from these paramilitary forces as well as military and police personnel gathered outside Thammasat University where student protesters had been protesting for weeks. This set the scene for the Thammasat University massacre the following day.<ref name=\"Mallet\" />{{RP|90}}`\n\n=== Massacre ===\n[[File:Beating corpse with a chair, 6 October 1976.jpg|thumb|A crowd looks on, some with smiles on their faces, as a man uses a folding chair to beat the hanged body of a student just outside the university. This photograph, which illustrates the brutality and lynch-mob mentality surrounding the event, has since become a symbol for the massacre, and has inspired numerous works of art.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rithdee|first1=Kong|title=In the eye of the storm|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/lifestyle/art/1098817/in-the-eye-of-the-storm|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Bangkok Post|publisher=Post Publishing|date=30 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Supawattanakul|first1=Kritsada|title=Coming to terms with a brutal history|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1103521/coming-to-terms-with-a-brutal-history|accessdate=6 October 2016|work=Bangkok Post|date=6 October 2016|format=Opinion}}</ref>]]\nAt dawn on 6 October, the military and the police as well as the three paramilitary forces blocked exits from the university and began shooting into the campus, using [[M16 rifle|M-16s]], [[M1 carbine|M1s and M2s]], pistols, grenade launchers, and even armor-piercing recoilless rifles.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|235\u2013236}}<ref>{{cite news|title=OCT. 6 MASSACRE: THE PHOTOGRAPHER WHO WAS THERE|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2016/10/05/oct-6-massacre-photographer/|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Khaosod English|agency=Associated Press (AP)|date=5 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005113218/http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2016/10/05/oct-6-massacre-photographer/|archive-date=5 October 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Prevented from leaving the campus or even sending wounded to the hospital, the students begged for a ceasefire. Trapped and with nowhere to go, the attacks continued.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}} The actors in the mock hanging had already turned themselves in to Seni at the prime minister's office.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}} When one student came out with a white flag to surrender, he was shot and killed.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}} After a free-fire order was issued by the Bangkok police chief, the campus was stormed, with [[Border Patrol Police]] leading the attack.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}} Students diving into the [[Chao Phraya River]] were shot at by naval vessels while others who surrendered, lying down on the ground, were picked up and beaten, many to death.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}} Some were hung from trees and beaten,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rojanaphruk|first1=Pravit|title=THE WILL TO REMEMBER: SURVIVORS RECOUNT 1976 THAMMASAT MASSACRE 40 YEARS LATER|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2016/10/05/will-remember-survivors-recount-1976-massacre-40-years-later/|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Khaosod English|date=5 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113014018/http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2016/10/05/will-remember-survivors-recount-1976-massacre-40-years-later/|archive-date=13 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> others were set afire. Female students were raped, alive and dead, by police and Red Gaurs.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}}  Although the majority of victims were shot by troops, some were injured and even killed by the ensuing mob of people that took part in the chaos. The mob also desecrated many of the bodies. The massacre continued for several hours, and was only halted at noon by a rainstorm.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}}\n\n=== Immediate aftermath ===\nOn the afternoon of 6 October after the massacre, the major factions of the military which formed the general staff agreed in principle to overthrow Seni, a plot that King Bhumibol was well aware of and approved, which in turn ensured the success of the coup-makers.<ref name=\"Mallet\" />{{RP|91}} Later that night, Admiral [[Sangad Chaloryu]], the newly appointed supreme commander, announced that the military, under the name of the \"National Administrative Reform Council\" (NARC) had seized power to \"prevent a Vietnamese-backed communist plot\" and to preserve the \"Thai monarchy forever\".<ref name=\"Mallet\" />{{RP|91}} The king appointed the anti-communist and royalist judge [[Thanin Kraivichien]] to lead a government that was composed of those who were loyal to the king. Thanin and his cabinet restored the repressive climate which had existed before 1973.<ref name=\"Mallet\" />{{RP|91}}\n\n== Significance ==\n\n=== Return of bureaucratic polity ===\nFor forty years from 1932 when the absolute monarchy was abolished, until 1973 when military rule was overthrown in favor of democracy, military officers and civil servants held sway in Thai politics and dominated the government, with King Bhumibol serving as the ceremonial head of state in accordance with his role as a [[Constitutional monarchy|constitutional monarch]] established by the 1932 constitution. The Thai political system was known as a \"bureaucratic [[polity]]\" which was dominated by the military and civilian bureaucrats.<ref>Riggs, Fred (1976). \"The Bureaucratic Polity as a Working System\". In Clark Neher, ed., ''Thailand: From Village to Nation''. Cambridge: Schenkman Books, pp. 406\u2013424.</ref> The massacre disproved the argument that the bureaucratic polity was on the retreat as the military came to play a central role once more in Thai politics, a situation that would continue throughout the 1970s and 1980s until the [[1988 Thai general election|1988 general election]] when all seats were democratically elected, including that of the prime minister, who from 1976 to 1988 was appointed by the king.\n\n=== Withdrawal symptoms ===\nFollowing in the footsteps of previous military strongmen like [[Plaek Phibunsongkhram]] and [[Sarit Thanarat]], Thanom became prime minister in 1963 following Sarit's death. He oversaw a massive influx of financial aid from the United States and Japan, fuelling the Thai economy, as well as increasing American cultural influence. But by the early-1970s, the US was withdrawing its troops from Indochina. In such a context, the Thai middle class and lower-middle class who had supported student efforts in 1973 to topple the Thanom regime were more a product of their immediate history than devotees of democracy.<ref name=\"Anderson\">{{cite journal|last1=Anderson|first1=Ben|title=Withdrawal Symptoms: Social and Cultural Aspects of the October 6 Coup|journal=Bulletin of Concerned Asian Scholars|date=Jul\u2013Sep 1977|volume=9|issue=3|pages=13\u201318|url=http://criticalasianstudies.org/assets/files/bcas/v09n03.pdf|accessdate=5 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106234159/http://criticalasianstudies.org/assets/files/bcas/v09n03.pdf|archive-date=6 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{RP|18}} They lacked political experience and so had no real idea of the consequences of ending the dictatorship. The regime was simultaneously blamed both for failing to exact fuller commitments from its allies and for excessive subservience to Washington.<ref name=\"Anderson\" />{{RP|18}} The support given by the Thai middle class and lower-middle class to the 1973 student protests was not an unconditional stamp of approval for democratic processes and the chaos that followed. The \"chaotic democracy\" from 1973 to 1976 was seen as having threatened the economic interests of the middle class and lower-middle class who favored stability and peace above democracy. In light of this, while they supported the mass demonstrations against the Thanom regime leading up to the uprising on 14 October 1973, they turned their backs on democracy, hence Anderson's use of the phrase \"withdrawal symptoms\", and welcomed the return to dictatorship on 6 October 1976, heralding the end of the period of chaotic democracy.\n\n== Left-wing Conspiracy Theory ==\n\n=== Overview ===\n{{more citations needed|section|date=October 2017|reason=first paragraph has no citations}}\nDespite being the most popular assumption among left-wing scholars, there are not empirical evidences which concluded that King Bhumibol had supported student protesters in their demonstrations in 1973 that led to the downfall of the Thanom regime and resulted in the period of \"chaotic democracy\" from 1973 to 1976, but had turned against the students and played a crucial, if not the most important, role in bringing about the massacre and a return to military rule after a three-year flirtation with democracy.\n\nAccording to the conspiracy theory, \u201cthere were two reasons for this about-face.\u201d \u201cFirst, Thailand's neighbors either were facing communist insurgencies or had fallen to communist rule and become communist countries.\u201d \u201cThe US was withdrawing its military presence from the region. The pivotal year in the trajectory of the king's involvement in politics was 1975. [[South Vietnam]] fell to the communists and the [[Communist Party of Vietnam]] was able to unify the country under its rule and drive out the US. In Cambodia, the communist [[Khmer Rouge]] [[Fall of Phnom Penh|captured Phnom Penh]] and began a reign of terror that would only end in 1979. The 1975 incident that arguably shook the Thai monarchy to the core was the overthrow by the [[Lao People's Revolutionary Party]] of the [[Lao Royal Family]], to which the Thai monarchy traditionally had cultural and historical ties. Second, the period of chaotic democracy brought instability and chaos as demonstrations, strikes, and protests took place much more frequently. They threatened the economic interests of the monarchy managed by the [[Crown Property Bureau]], which favored a stable and peaceful economic environment that would allow its businesses to thrive.\u201d\n\n\u201cKing Bhumibol wielded his influence through a \"[[network monarchy]]\" that was centered on [[Privy Council of Thailand|Privy Council]] President [[Prem Tinsulanonda]]. One of the main features of the network monarchy was that the monarch intervened actively in political developments, largely by working through proxies such as privy councillors and trusted military figures.<ref>McCargo, Duncan (2005). \"Network Monarchy and Legitimacy Crises\". ''The Pacific Review'', Vol. 18, No. 4, p. 501.</ref> This network monarchy suggests that, contrary to the popular belief that the king was a constitutional monarch and above politics, rather he had been intimately involved in Thai politics and had often intervened in order to secure his political and economic interests. The instability brought about by the student protesters until 1976 as well as the growing specter of communist threat in the region, especially after the \"domino effect\" where Vietnam, Cambodia, and Laos fell in succession to the communists, convinced King Bhumibol to see the protesters as a threat to his rule. The Thai state and its politicians subsequently branded these students, as well as workers and farmers, as \"communists\" and a \"fifth column for the [[Communist Party of Thailand]] (CPT) and [[North Vietnam]].\"<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|220}} In reality, there was little evidence for the claim that protesters, including students protesting at Thammasat University, were communists. While the CPT had grown in strength, they were far from a unified force and they appealed to peasants by focusing on social injustices while avoiding attacking the monarchy and Buddhism. Their gains were fuelled more by the government's alienation of the peasantry.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|220}} This suggests that the term \"communists\" was applied very liberally and indiscriminately and more often than not, deliberately, to those who were deemed to be the sources of instability that threatened the monarchy and the king. In the Thai state's view, communism was simply the enemy of the nation, religion (Buddhism), and monarchy, and a sworn enemy of \"Thainess\".<ref name=Thongchai-1994>Winichakul, Thongchai (1994). ''Siam Mapped: A History of the Geo-Body of Siam''. Honolulu: University of Hawai\u2019i Press.</ref>{{RP|169\u2013170}} One of the more persistent counterinsurgency strategies was to link socialists, communists, and the Left to external threats.<ref name=\"Thongchai-1994\" />{{RP|169\u2013170}} In order to deal effectively with the \"communist\" threat that would undermine his rule and status, in addition to deploying governmental forces such as the Thai military and police, King Bhumibol, through his network monarchy, also encouraged three paramilitary forces\u2014the Village Scouts, Nawaphon, and Red Gaurs\u2014to use violence against protesters from 1973 to 1976. This culminated in the Thammasat massacre.\u201d\n\n=== Village Scouts ===\n\u201cThe Village Scouts organization was a national [[paramilitary]] group sponsored by the King and Queen of Thailand since 1972 in order to promote national unity against threats to Thai independence and freedom, particularly against \"communism\".<ref name=Muecke>Muecke, Marjorie (1980). \"The Village Scouts of Thailand\". ''Asian Survey'', Vol. 20, No. 4.</ref>{{RP|407}} The movement was set up explicitly to protect the monarchy from communism. It focused on the central features of Thai identity: love of play, deep respect for the king and religion (Buddhism), and for ethnic Thai \"specialness\".<ref name=\"Muecke\" />{{RP|413}} The king was held to be central to the Thai nation, to be protected at all costs, alongside the nation and religion, forming the Thai nationalist [[shibboleth]], \"nation, religion, king\". The Village Scouts presence provided continuous proof of militant political support for nation-religion-king beyond the Bangkok upper classes, among the \"establishments\" of provincial capitals, small towns, and villages. It helped to legitimize private, localized repression of protesting peasants and student activists as essential for the preservation the status quo.<ref name=\"Anderson\" /> During the period 1973\u20131976, Village Scout membership rose to tens of thousands, almost all in rural, CPT-influenced Thailand. After an [[Internal Security Operations Command]] (ISOC) takeover, the Village Scouts metamorphosed into a [[fascist]]-style mass political movement that would play a major role in the ensuing massacre.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|224}}\u201d\n\n=== Nawaphon ===\n\u201c[[Nawaphon]] was an ISOC operation organized in 1974. It was composed of mainly low-level government functionaries and clerks, rural village and communal headmen, as well as a number of monks.<ref name=Keyes>Keyes, Charles (1978). \"Political Crisis and Militant Buddhism in Contemporary Thailand\". In Bardwell L. Smith, ed., ''Religion and Legitimation of Power in Thailand, Laos, and Burma''. Chambersburg: Anima Books.</ref>{{RP|151}} The name \"Nawaphon\" means \"nine strengths\", a reference to either the [[Chakri dynasty|Chakri Ninth Reign (King Bhumibol)]]<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|225}} or the nine points of Nawaphon's program to preserve Thai nationalism.<ref name=\"Keyes\" />{{RP|151}} The aim of Nawaphon was to protect the king from threats like communism. A key figure of the movement was the monk, Kittivudho Bhikkhu, who became its leader in 1975. In a June 1976 interview he was asked if killing leftists or communists would produce demerits or negative [[karma]], he said that such killing would not be demeriting because, \"...whoever destroys the nation, the religion or the monarchy, such bestial types are not complete persons. Thus, we must intend not to kill people but to kill the Devil; this is the duty of all Thai\".<ref name=\"Keyes\" />{{RP|153}} In 1967, he established Jittiphawan College. It was inaugurated by King Bhumibol and Queen Sirikit who returned regularly even after Kittivudho began to make incendiary speeches about the need to deal with student protesters and communists.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|225}} This suggests a close relationship between the Nawaphon movement and the royal family. Employing the slogan that \"killing communists is not demeritorious\", Kittivudho encouraged the killings of alleged communists from 1973 to 1976 and injected militant Buddhism into the Thai [[body politic]], eventually inciting his followers to commit violence at Thammasat University on 6 October. Earlier, Nawaphon was responsible for the killing of more than 20 prominent farmer activists in 1975.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|226}} The murders were an attempt to negate the farmers' new-found political agency and, by so doing, return them to their pre-October 1973 state of relative repression.<ref>Haberkorn, Tyrell (2009). \"An Unfinished Past: Assassination and the 1974 Land Rent Control Act in Northern Thailand\". ''Critical Asian Studies'', Vol. 41, No. 1, p. 28.</ref> The assassinations of farmer activists were part of the state campaign to suppress any potential threat to the king's rule, sanctioned and encouraged by the king as an integral part of his anti-communist purge.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}\u201d\n\n=== Red Gaurs ===\n\u201cThe [[Red Gaurs]] were ex-mercenaries and men discharged from the military for disciplinary infractions mixed with unemployed vocational school graduates, high-school dropouts, idle street corner boys, and slum toughs.<ref name=\"Anderson\" /> In the early-1970s, potential recruits were in dire economic straits, unable to obtain employment, and thus were easy targets of anti-student and anti-worker propaganda.<ref name=\"Anderson\" /> Their grievances were exploited by the state, notably the king's network, and their anger directed towards student protesters. They were recruited not on the basis of ideological commitment, but rather by promises of high pay, abundant liquor, brothel privileges, and the lure of public notoriety.<ref name=\"Anderson\" /> Unlike the Village Scouts and the Nawaphon, the motivation of the Red Gaurs was more sociological than ideological.\u201d\n\n=== Royal family involvement ===\n\u201cKing Bhumibol and the royal family took part frequently in Village Scout activities and attended ceremonies at Kittivudho's college and Red Gaur training camps, thus illustrating their close ties with these three paramilitary forces.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|227}} While all three forces differed in their nature, they were united by their allegiance to the king and, concomitantly, their hatred of communists. These paramilitary forces would subsequently be mobilized to attack the student protesters at Thammasat University to end their weeks-long protests.\u201d\n\n== Remembrance ==\nAccording to Ron Corben, the Thammasat University massacre continues to be a \"...scar on the Thai collective psyche...\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Corben|first1=Ron|title=Thailand to Mark 40th Anniversary of Bloody 1976 Massacre|url=http://www.voanews.com/a/thailand-to-mark-40th-anniversary-of-1976-massacre/3537620.html|accessdate=6 October 2016|work=VOA News|date=5 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005162257/http://www.voanews.com/a/thailand-to-mark-40th-anniversary-of-1976-massacre/3537620.html|archive-date=5 October 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The government has remained silent over its role, and that of the king, in the killing of student protesters. This silence is deeply embedded in a culture of [[wikt:impunity|impunity]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Editor2|title=Culture of impunity and the Thai ruling class: Interview with Puangthong Pawakapan|url=http://www.prachatai.com/english/node/6612|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Prachatai English|date=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004163018/http://www.prachatai.com/english/node/6612|archive-date=4 October 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In an analysis of the two amnesty laws passed in relation to the massacre, Thailand scholar Tyrell Haberkorn argues that they first created and then consolidated impunity for the coup and the massacre that preceded it.<ref name=Haberkorn-2015>Haberkorn, Tyrell (2015). \"The Hidden Transcript of Amnesty: The 6 October 1976 Massacre and Coup in Thailand\". ''Critical Asian Studies'', Vol. 47, No. 1.</ref>{{RP|47}} The first amnesty law, passed on 24 December 1976, legalized the coup and prevented those who seized power on the evening of 6 October from being held accountable.<ref name=\"Haberkorn-2015\" />{{RP|44}} The second amnesty law, passed on 16 September 1978, freed eighteen student activists still undergoing criminal prosecution and dismissed the charges against them.<ref name=\"Haberkorn-2015\" />{{RP|44}} The \"hidden transcripts\" of the two amnesties for massacre and coup that followed reveal the careful, calculated legal moves taken to protect those who were behind them.<ref name=\"Haberkorn-2015\" />{{RP|64}} Despite the rhetoric in the streets and on the radio about the need to protect the nation, the coup and the massacre that preceded it unsettled some inside the state, perhaps because they were aware of the extra-legal status of the massacre, perhaps because they worried about their own culpability, and perhaps because they were aware that the violations in need of amnesty were not only those of the criminal code but of the more basic code of being human.<ref name=\"Haberkorn-2015\" />{{RP|64\u201365}} Thus, both amnesty laws sought to produce impunity for state violence, particularly the king's involvement. There has been no state investigation into the violence and this impunity is both cause and effect of the silence, ambivalence, and ambiguity surrounding the event for both those who survived it and Thai society.<ref name=\"Haberkorn-2015\" />{{RP|46}}\n\nThai scholar [[Thongchai Winichakul]], one of the student protesters who was jailed for his participation in the protests at Thammasat University, argues that the clearest evidence of the evasive public memories of the uprisings and massacre are the names the events have come to be known by, and the most conspicuous site of contested memories is the controversy over the memorial for the events.<ref name=Thongchai-2002>Thongchai Winichakul (2002). \"Remembering/ Silencing the Traumatic Past\". In Shigeharu Tanabe and Charles F. Keyes eds., ''Cultural Crisis and Social Memory: Modernity and Identity in Thailand and Laos''. Honolulu: University of Hawaii Press.</ref>{{RP|265}} The massacre continues to be known in Thailand by the deliberately ambiguous term \"6 October event\". Thongchai argues that this non-committal name is loaded with many unsettled meanings, which imply the absence of any commitment and obscures the past because it is too heavily loaded with contesting voices, placing the massacre on the edge between recognizability and anonymity, between history and the silenced past, and between memory and forgetfulness.<ref name=\"Thongchai-2002\" />{{RP|266}} Thus, in \"remembering\" it, its nomenclature carries overt political significance that continues to reverberate in present-day Thai politics, particularly in relation to the role played by the state and King Bhumibol in the attack on student protesters.\n\nThe commemoration in 1996 represented a significant break in the silence. Yet, during the commemoration, what happened twenty years earlier was retold innumerable times, though without any reference to the undiscussable parts of that history.<ref name=\"Thongchai-2002\" />{{RP|274}} There was also no reaction, not even any comment, from the military or any conservative organization.<ref name=\"Thongchai-2002\" />{{RP|274}} More importantly, the denunciation of state crime avoided imputing blame to any specific individual and the victims' self-sacrifice for society's sake was honored.<ref name=\"Thongchai-2002\" />{{RP|274\u2013275}} The role played by King Bhumibol in inciting the military and police and paramilitary forces to attack the student protesters was not mentioned so as not to target the king as an \"individual\". Yet, this could also be interpreted as an attempt by the state to whitewash history by wishing away parts that it did not want the public to know or remember. In addition, by emphasizing the theme of healing and reconciliation in the remembrance, the Thai state, and by implication the king, have sought to make clear that the commemoration had no interest in and would not be involved in any talk of [[wikt:retribution|retribution]].<ref name=\"Thongchai-2002\" />{{RP|274}} Forty years later, the perpetrators remain unnamed and unpunished. Tyrell Haberkorn, the Thailand scholar, speculates that the death of Rama IX, King Bhumipol Adulyadej, may make it even more difficult to name the perpetrators as Rama IX's reign becomes more idealized.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Haberkorn |first1=Tyrell |title=The Anniversary of a Massacre and the Death of a Monarch |journal=The Journal of Asian Studies |date=2017 |volume=76 |issue=2 |page=269 |doi=10.1017/S0021911817000018 |url=https://www-cambridge-org.ccl.idm.oclc.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/4FD9FA295086CE51B654BCAD342D1F88/S0021911817000018a.pdf/anniversary_of_a_massacre_and_the_death_of_a_monarch.pdf |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-37520961 BBC News interview with Thongchai Winichakul]\n\n{{Thammasat University}}\n{{Thai coups}}\n{{History of Thailand since 1973}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thammasat University Massacre}}\n[[Category:1976 in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1976]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Political repression in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Protests in Thailand]]\n[[Category:School massacres]]\n[[Category:Thammasat University]]\n[[Category:History of Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Rebellions in Thailand]]\n[[Category:October 1976 events in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Thammasat University massacre\n| image       = File:6 \u0e15\u0e38\u0e25\u0e32.jpg\n| location    = [[Thammasat University]] and [[Sanam Luang]] in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|13|45|21.07|N|100|29|27.16|E|region:TH_type:edu|display=inline, title}}\n| target      = Student protesters\n| date        = 6 October 1976\n| fatalities  = 46 (official); 100+ (unofficial)\n| injuries    = 167 (official)\n| perps       = [[Royal Thai Armed Forces]]<br/>[[Royal Thai Police]]<br/>[[Village Scouts]]<br/>[[Nawaphon]]<br/>[[Red Gaur]]<br/>Pro Government Civilians\n}}\n\nThe '''Thammasat University massacre''' (in Thailand known simply as '''the 6 October event''', {{lang-th|\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e15\u0e38\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c 6 \u0e15\u0e38\u0e25\u0e32}} {{RTGS|het kan hok tula}}) was an attack by Thai state forces and far-right paramilitaries on student protesters on the campus of [[Thammasat University]] and the adjacent [[Sanam Luang]] Square in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]], on 6 October 1976. Prior to the massacre, four to five thousand students from various universities had demonstrated for more than a week against the return of former military dictator [[Thanom Kittikachorn]] to Thailand from [[Singapore]].\n\nA day before the massacre, the Thai press reported on a play staged by student protesters the previous day, which allegedly featured the mock hanging of then [[Vajiralongkorn|Crown Prince Vajiralongkorn]]. In response to this rumored outrage, military and police, as well as paramilitary forces surrounded the university. Just before dawn on 6 October with the protesters trapped within the campus, the government forces opened fire on them. The brutal attack lasted until noon, eventually devolving into chaos with mob beatings, rapes and lynchings. To this day, the number of casualties remains in dispute between the Thai government and survivors of the massacre. According to the government, 46 died in the killings, with 167 wounded and 3,000 arrested. Many survivors claim that the death toll was well over 100.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\">{{cite book|last1=Handley|first1=Paul M|title=The King Never Smiles; A Biography of Thailand's Bhumibol Adulyadej|date=2006|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven|isbn=0-300-10682-3|url=https://www.academia.edu/8599856/Paul_M._Handley-The_King_Never_Smiles;_A_Biography_of_Thailands_Bhumibol_Adulyadej-Yale_University_Press_2006_|accessdate=5 October 2016}}</ref>{{RP|236}}\n\n== Massacre ==\n\n=== Immediate causes ===\nThe [[1973 Thai popular uprising|14 October 1973 uprising]] overthrew the unpopular regime of Field Marshal Thanom Kittikachorn, and saw him flee Thailand together with Field Marshal [[Praphas Charusathien]] and Colonel Narong Kittikachorn, collectively known as the \"three tyrants\".<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|209}} Growing unrest and instability from 1973 to 1976, as well as the fear of communism from neighboring countries spreading to Thailand and threatening the interests of the monarchy and the military, convinced the latter to bring former leaders Thanom and Praphas back to Thailand to control the situation. In response to Praphas's return on 17 August, thousands of students demonstrated at Thammasat University for four days until a clash with [[Red Gaur]] and [[Nawaphon]] left four dead.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|233}} On 19 September, Thanom returned to Thailand and headed straight from the airport to [[Wat Bowonniwet Vihara]], where he was ordained as a monk in a private ceremony. Massive anti-Thanom protests broke out as the government faced an internal crisis after Prime Minister [[Seni Pramoj]]'s attempt to tender his resignation was rejected by the Thai Parliament. On 24 September, in [[Nakhon Pathom]], west of Bangkok, two labor-cum-activists, putting up anti-Thanom posters were beaten to death and hung from a wall, an act that was soon established to be the work of Thai police.<ref name=\"doct6\">{{cite web |title=4. \u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e01\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35 6 \u0e15\u0e38\u0e25\u0e32\u0e2f |url=https://doct6.com/learn-about/how/chapter-4 |website=https://doct6.com |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Buabmee |first1=Sunantha Buabmee |last2=Rojanaphruk |first2=Pravit |title=SCHOLARS SAVE \u2018RED GATE,\u2019 THE BACKDROP TO OCT. 1976 MASSACRE |url=https://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2019/07/03/scholars-save-red-gate-the-backdrop-to-oct-1976-massacre/ |website=Khaosod English |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|235}} A dramatization of this hanging was staged by student protesters at Thammasat University on 4 October. Either deliberately or as an unfortunate coincidence, the student at the end of the garrote bore a resemblance to Crown Prince [[Vajiralongkorn]].<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|235}} The following day, as Seni struggled to put together his cabinet, the newspaper ''Dao Siam'' ({{lang|th|\u0e14\u0e32\u0e27\u0e2a\u0e22\u0e32\u0e21}}) published a photograph of the mock hanging on its front page.<ref name=\"Mallet\">{{cite journal|last1=Mallet|first1=Marian|title=Causes and Consequences of the October '76 Coup|journal=Journal of Contemporary Asia|date=1978|volume=8|issue=1|url=http://thirdworld.nl/causes-and-consequences-of-the-october-76-coup|accessdate=5 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20161011162840/http://thirdworld.nl/causes-and-consequences-of-the-october-76-coup|archivedate=11 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{RP|90}} With the tacit approval of [[Bhumibol Adulyadej|King Bhumibol]], announcers on army-controlled radio stations accused the student protesters of [[L\u00e8se majest\u00e9 in Thailand|l\u00e8se-majest\u00e9]] and mobilized the king's paramilitary forces, the Village Scouts, Nawaphon, and Red Gaurs to \"kill the communists\".<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|235}} At dusk on 5 October, some 4,000 people from these paramilitary forces as well as military and police personnel gathered outside Thammasat University where student protesters had been protesting for weeks. This set the scene for the Thammasat University massacre the following day.<ref name=\"Mallet\" />{{RP|90}}`\n\n=== Massacre ===\n[[File:Beating corpse with a chair, 6 October 1976.jpg|thumb|A crowd looks on, some with smiles on their faces, as a man uses a folding chair to beat the hanged body of a student just outside the university. This photograph, which illustrates the brutality and lynch-mob mentality surrounding the event, has since become a symbol for the massacre, and has inspired numerous works of art.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rithdee|first1=Kong|title=In the eye of the storm|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/lifestyle/art/1098817/in-the-eye-of-the-storm|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Bangkok Post|publisher=Post Publishing|date=30 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Supawattanakul|first1=Kritsada|title=Coming to terms with a brutal history|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1103521/coming-to-terms-with-a-brutal-history|accessdate=6 October 2016|work=Bangkok Post|date=6 October 2016|format=Opinion}}</ref>]]\nAt dawn on 6 October, the military and the police as well as the three paramilitary forces blocked exits from the university and began shooting into the campus, using [[M16 rifle|M-16s]], [[M1 carbine|M1s and M2s]], pistols, grenade launchers, and even armor-piercing recoilless rifles.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|235-236}}<ref>{{cite news|title=OCT. 6 MASSACRE: THE PHOTOGRAPHER WHO WAS THERE|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2016/10/05/oct-6-massacre-photographer/|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Khaosod English|agency=Associated Press (AP)|date=5 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005113218/http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2016/10/05/oct-6-massacre-photographer/|archive-date=5 October 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Prevented from leaving the campus or even sending wounded to the hospital, the students begged for a ceasefire. Trapped and with nowhere to go, the attacks continued.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}} The actors in the mock hanging had already turned themselves in to Seni at the prime minister's office.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}} When one student came out with a white flag to surrender, he was shot and killed.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}} After a free-fire order was issued by the Bangkok police chief, the campus was stormed, with [[Border Patrol Police]] leading the attack.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}} Students diving into the [[Chao Phraya River]] were shot at by naval vessels while others who surrendered, lying down on the ground, were picked up and beaten, many to death.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}} Some were hung from trees and beaten,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rojanaphruk|first1=Pravit|title=THE WILL TO REMEMBER: SURVIVORS RECOUNT 1976 THAMMASAT MASSACRE 40 YEARS LATER|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2016/10/05/will-remember-survivors-recount-1976-massacre-40-years-later/|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Khaosod English|date=5 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113014018/http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2016/10/05/will-remember-survivors-recount-1976-massacre-40-years-later/|archive-date=13 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> others were set afire. Female students were raped, alive and dead, by police and Red Gaurs.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}}  Although the majority of victims were shot by troops, some were injured and even killed by the ensuing mob of people that took part in the chaos. The mob also desecrated many of the bodies. The massacre continued for several hours, and was only halted at noon by a rainstorm.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|236}}\n\n=== Immediate aftermath ===\nOn the afternoon of 6 October after the massacre, the major factions of the military which formed the general staff agreed in principle to overthrow Seni, a plot that King Bhumibol was well aware of and approved, which in turn ensured the success of the coup-makers.<ref name=\"Mallet\" />{{RP|91}} Later that night, Admiral [[Sangad Chaloryu]], the newly appointed supreme commander, announced that the military, under the name of the \"National Administrative Reform Council\" (NARC) had seized power to \"prevent a Vietnamese-backed communist plot\" and to preserve the \"Thai monarchy forever\".<ref name=\"Mallet\" />{{RP|91}} The king appointed the anti-communist and royalist judge [[Thanin Kraivichien]] to lead a government that was composed of those who were loyal to the king. Thanin and his cabinet restored the repressive climate which had existed before 1973.<ref name=\"Mallet\" />{{RP|91}}\n\n== Significance ==\n\n=== Return of bureaucratic polity ===\nFor forty years from 1932 when the absolute monarchy was abolished, until 1973 when military rule was overthrown in favor of democracy, military officers and civil servants held sway in Thai politics and dominated the government, with King Bhumibol serving as the ceremonial head of state in accordance with his role as a [[Constitutional monarchy|constitutional monarch]] established by the 1932 constitution. The Thai political system was known as a \"bureaucratic [[polity]]\" which was dominated by the military and civilian bureaucrats.<ref>Riggs, Fred (1976). \"The Bureaucratic Polity as a Working System\". In Clark Neher, ed., ''Thailand: From Village to Nation''. Cambridge: Schenkman Books, pp. 406-424.</ref> The massacre disproved the argument that the bureaucratic polity was on the retreat as the military came to play a central role once more in Thai politics, a situation that would continue throughout the 1970s and 1980s until the [[1988 Thai general election|1988 general election]] when all seats were democratically elected, including that of the prime minister, who from 1976 to 1988 was appointed by the king.\n\n=== Withdrawal symptoms ===\nFollowing in the footsteps of previous military strongmen like [[Plaek Phibunsongkhram]] and [[Sarit Thanarat]], Thanom became prime minister in 1963 following Sarit's death. He oversaw a massive influx of financial aid from the United States and Japan, fuelling the Thai economy, as well as increasing American cultural influence. But by the early-1970s, the US was withdrawing its troops from Indochina. In such a context, the Thai middle class and lower-middle class who had supported student efforts in 1973 to topple the Thanom regime were more a product of their immediate history than devotees of democracy.<ref name=\"Anderson\">{{cite journal|last1=Anderson|first1=Ben|title=Withdrawal Symptoms: Social and Cultural Aspects of the October 6 Coup|journal=Bulletin of Concerned Asian Scholars|date=Jul\u2013Sep 1977|volume=9|issue=3|pages=13\u201318|url=http://criticalasianstudies.org/assets/files/bcas/v09n03.pdf|accessdate=5 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106234159/http://criticalasianstudies.org/assets/files/bcas/v09n03.pdf|archive-date=6 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{RP|18}} They lacked political experience and so had no real idea of the consequences of ending the dictatorship. The regime was simultaneously blamed both for failing to exact fuller commitments from its allies and for excessive subservience to Washington.<ref name=\"Anderson\" />{{RP|18}} The support given by the Thai middle class and lower-middle class to the 1973 student protests was not an unconditional stamp of approval for democratic processes and the chaos that followed. The \"chaotic democracy\" from 1973 to 1976 was seen as having threatened the economic interests of the middle class and lower-middle class who favored stability and peace above democracy. In light of this, while they supported the mass demonstrations against the Thanom regime leading up to the uprising on 14 October 1973, they turned their backs on democracy, hence Anderson's use of the phrase \"withdrawal symptoms\", and welcomed the return to dictatorship on 6 October 1976, heralding the end of the period of chaotic democracy.\n\n== Left-wing Conspiracy Theory ==\n\n=== Overview ===\n{{more citations needed|section|date=October 2017|reason=first paragraph has no citations}}\nDespite being the most popular assumption among left-wing scholars, there are not empirical evidences which concluded that King Bhumibol had supported student protesters in their demonstrations in 1973 that led to the downfall of the Thanom regime and resulted in the period of \"chaotic democracy\" from 1973 to 1976, but had turned against the students and played a crucial, if not the most important, role in bringing about the massacre and a return to military rule after a three-year flirtation with democracy.\n\nAccording to the conspiracy theory, \u201cthere were two reasons for this about-face.\u201d \u201cFirst, Thailand's neighbors either were facing communist insurgencies or had fallen to communist rule and become communist countries.\u201d \u201cThe US was withdrawing its military presence from the region. The pivotal year in the trajectory of the king's involvement in politics was 1975. [[South Vietnam]] fell to the communists and the [[Communist Party of Vietnam]] was able to unify the country under its rule and drive out the US. In Cambodia, the communist [[Khmer Rouge]] [[Fall of Phnom Penh|captured Phnom Penh]] and began a reign of terror that would only end in 1979. The 1975 incident that arguably shook the Thai monarchy to the core was the overthrow by the [[Lao People's Revolutionary Party]] of the [[Lao Royal Family]], to which the Thai monarchy traditionally had cultural and historical ties. Second, the period of chaotic democracy brought instability and chaos as demonstrations, strikes, and protests took place much more frequently. They threatened the economic interests of the monarchy managed by the [[Crown Property Bureau]], which favored a stable and peaceful economic environment that would allow its businesses to thrive.\u201d\n\n\u201cKing Bhumibol wielded his influence through a \"[[network monarchy]]\" that was centered on [[Privy Council of Thailand|Privy Council]] President [[Prem Tinsulanonda]]. One of the main features of the network monarchy was that the monarch intervened actively in political developments, largely by working through proxies such as privy councillors and trusted military figures.<ref>McCargo, Duncan (2005). \"Network Monarchy and Legitimacy Crises\". ''The Pacific Review'', Vol. 18, No. 4, p. 501.</ref> This network monarchy suggests that, contrary to the popular belief that the king was a constitutional monarch and above politics, rather he had been intimately involved in Thai politics and had often intervened in order to secure his political and economic interests. The instability brought about by the student protesters until 1976 as well as the growing specter of communist threat in the region, especially after the \"domino effect\" where Vietnam, Cambodia, and Laos fell in succession to the communists, convinced King Bhumibol to see the protesters as a threat to his rule. The Thai state and its politicians subsequently branded these students, as well as workers and farmers, as \"communists\" and a \"fifth column for the [[Communist Party of Thailand]] (CPT) and [[North Vietnam]].\"<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|220}} In reality, there was little evidence for the claim that protesters, including students protesting at Thammasat University, were communists. While the CPT had grown in strength, they were far from a unified force and they appealed to peasants by focusing on social injustices while avoiding attacking the monarchy and Buddhism. Their gains were fuelled more by the government's alienation of the peasantry.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|220}} This suggests that the term \"communists\" was applied very liberally and indiscriminately and more often than not, deliberately, to those who were deemed to be the sources of instability that threatened the monarchy and the king. In the Thai state's view, communism was simply the enemy of the nation, religion (Buddhism), and monarchy, and a sworn enemy of \"Thainess\".<ref name=Thongchai-1994>Winichakul, Thongchai (1994). ''Siam Mapped: A History of the Geo-Body of Siam''. Honolulu: University of Hawai\u2019i Press.</ref>{{RP|169-170}} One of the more persistent counterinsurgency strategies was to link socialists, communists, and the Left to external threats.<ref name=\"Thongchai-1994\" />{{RP|169-170}} In order to deal effectively with the \"communist\" threat that would undermine his rule and status, in addition to deploying governmental forces such as the Thai military and police, King Bhumibol, through his network monarchy, also encouraged three paramilitary forces\u2014the Village Scouts, Nawaphon, and Red Gaurs\u2014to use violence against protesters from 1973 to 1976. This culminated in the Thammasat massacre.\u201d\n\n=== Village Scouts ===\n\u201cThe Village Scouts organization was a national [[paramilitary]] group sponsored by the King and Queen of Thailand since 1972 in order to promote national unity against threats to Thai independence and freedom, particularly against \"communism\".<ref name=Muecke>Muecke, Marjorie (1980). \"The Village Scouts of Thailand\". ''Asian Survey'', Vol. 20, No. 4.</ref>{{RP|407}} The movement was set up explicitly to protect the monarchy from communism. It focused on the central features of Thai identity: love of play, deep respect for the king and religion (Buddhism), and for ethnic Thai \"specialness\".<ref name=\"Muecke\" />{{RP|413}} The king was held to be central to the Thai nation, to be protected at all costs, alongside the nation and religion, forming the Thai nationalist [[shibboleth]], \"nation, religion, king\". The Village Scouts presence provided continuous proof of militant political support for nation-religion-king beyond the Bangkok upper classes, among the \"establishments\" of provincial capitals, small towns, and villages. It helped to legitimize private, localized repression of protesting peasants and student activists as essential for the preservation the status quo.<ref name=\"Anderson\" /> During the period 1973\u20131976, Village Scout membership rose to tens of thousands, almost all in rural, CPT-influenced Thailand. After an [[Internal Security Operations Command]] (ISOC) takeover, the Village Scouts metamorphosed into a [[fascist]]-style mass political movement that would play a major role in the ensuing massacre.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|224}}\u201d\n\n=== Nawaphon ===\n\u201c[[Nawaphon]] was an ISOC operation organized in 1974. It was composed of mainly low-level government functionaries and clerks, rural village and communal headmen, as well as a number of monks.<ref name=Keyes>Keyes, Charles (1978). \"Political Crisis and Militant Buddhism in Contemporary Thailand\". In Bardwell L. Smith, ed., ''Religion and Legitimation of Power in Thailand, Laos, and Burma''. Chambersburg: Anima Books.</ref>{{RP|151}} The name \"Nawaphon\" means \"nine strengths\", a reference to either the [[Chakri dynasty|Chakri Ninth Reign (King Bhumibol)]]<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|225}} or the nine points of Nawaphon's program to preserve Thai nationalism.<ref name=\"Keyes\" />{{RP|151}} The aim of Nawaphon was to protect the king from threats like communism. A key figure of the movement was the monk, Kittivudho Bhikkhu, who became its leader in 1975. In a June 1976 interview he was asked if killing leftists or communists would produce demerits or negative [[karma]], he said that such killing would not be demeriting because, \"...whoever destroys the nation, the religion or the monarchy, such bestial types are not complete persons. Thus, we must intend not to kill people but to kill the Devil; this is the duty of all Thai\".<ref name=\"Keyes\" />{{RP|153}} In 1967, he established Jittiphawan College. It was inaugurated by King Bhumibol and Queen Sirikit who returned regularly even after Kittivudho began to make incendiary speeches about the need to deal with student protesters and communists.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|225}} This suggests a close relationship between the Nawaphon movement and the royal family. Employing the slogan that \"killing communists is not demeritorious\", Kittivudho encouraged the killings of alleged communists from 1973 to 1976 and injected militant Buddhism into the Thai [[body politic]], eventually inciting his followers to commit violence at Thammasat University on 6 October. Earlier, Nawaphon was responsible for the killing of more than 20 prominent farmer activists in 1975.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|226}} The murders were an attempt to negate the farmers' new-found political agency and, by so doing, return them to their pre-October 1973 state of relative repression.<ref>Haberkorn, Tyrell (2009). \"An Unfinished Past: Assassination and the 1974 Land Rent Control Act in Northern Thailand\". ''Critical Asian Studies'', Vol. 41, No. 1, p. 28.</ref> The assassinations of farmer activists were part of the state campaign to suppress any potential threat to the king's rule, sanctioned and encouraged by the king as an integral part of his anti-communist purge.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}\u201d\n\n=== Red Gaurs ===\n\u201cThe [[Red Gaurs]] were ex-mercenaries and men discharged from the military for disciplinary infractions mixed with unemployed vocational school graduates, high-school dropouts, idle street corner boys, and slum toughs.<ref name=\"Anderson\" /> In the early-1970s, potential recruits were in dire economic straits, unable to obtain employment, and thus were easy targets of anti-student and anti-worker propaganda.<ref name=\"Anderson\" /> Their grievances were exploited by the state, notably the king's network, and their anger directed towards student protesters. They were recruited not on the basis of ideological commitment, but rather by promises of high pay, abundant liquor, brothel privileges, and the lure of public notoriety.<ref name=\"Anderson\" /> Unlike the Village Scouts and the Nawaphon, the motivation of the Red Gaurs was more sociological than ideological.\u201d\n\n=== Royal family involvement ===\n\u201cKing Bhumibol and the royal family took part frequently in Village Scout activities and attended ceremonies at Kittivudho's college and Red Gaur training camps, thus illustrating their close ties with these three paramilitary forces.<ref name=\"Handley-2006\" />{{RP|227}} While all three forces differed in their nature, they were united by their allegiance to the king and, concomitantly, their hatred of communists. These paramilitary forces would subsequently be mobilized to attack the student protesters at Thammasat University to end their weeks-long protests.\u201d\n\n== Remembrance ==\nAccording to Ron Corben, the Thammasat University massacre continues to be a \"...scar on the Thai collective psyche...\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Corben|first1=Ron|title=Thailand to Mark 40th Anniversary of Bloody 1976 Massacre|url=http://www.voanews.com/a/thailand-to-mark-40th-anniversary-of-1976-massacre/3537620.html|accessdate=6 October 2016|work=VOA News|date=5 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005162257/http://www.voanews.com/a/thailand-to-mark-40th-anniversary-of-1976-massacre/3537620.html|archive-date=5 October 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The government has remained silent over its role, and that of the king, in the killing of student protesters. This silence is deeply embedded in a culture of [[wikt:impunity|impunity]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Editor2|title=Culture of impunity and the Thai ruling class: Interview with Puangthong Pawakapan|url=http://www.prachatai.com/english/node/6612|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Prachatai English|date=3 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004163018/http://www.prachatai.com/english/node/6612|archive-date=4 October 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In an analysis of the two amnesty laws passed in relation to the massacre, Thailand scholar Tyrell Haberkorn argues that they first created and then consolidated impunity for the coup and the massacre that preceded it.<ref name=Haberkorn-2015>Haberkorn, Tyrell (2015). \"The Hidden Transcript of Amnesty: The 6 October 1976 Massacre and Coup in Thailand\". ''Critical Asian Studies'', Vol. 47, No. 1.</ref>{{RP|47}} The first amnesty law, passed on 24 December 1976, legalized the coup and prevented those who seized power on the evening of 6 October from being held accountable.<ref name=\"Haberkorn-2015\" />{{RP|44}} The second amnesty law, passed on 16 September 1978, freed eighteen student activists still undergoing criminal prosecution and dismissed the charges against them.<ref name=\"Haberkorn-2015\" />{{RP|44}} The \"hidden transcripts\" of the two amnesties for massacre and coup that followed reveal the careful, calculated legal moves taken to protect those who were behind them.<ref name=\"Haberkorn-2015\" />{{RP|64}} Despite the rhetoric in the streets and on the radio about the need to protect the nation, the coup and the massacre that preceded it unsettled some inside the state, perhaps because they were aware of the extra-legal status of the massacre, perhaps because they worried about their own culpability, and perhaps because they were aware that the violations in need of amnesty were not only those of the criminal code but of the more basic code of being human.<ref name=\"Haberkorn-2015\" />{{RP|64-65}} Thus, both amnesty laws sought to produce impunity for state violence, particularly the king's involvement. There has been no state investigation into the violence and this impunity is both cause and effect of the silence, ambivalence, and ambiguity surrounding the event for both those who survived it and Thai society.<ref name=\"Haberkorn-2015\" />{{RP|46}}\n\nThai scholar [[Thongchai Winichakul]], one of the student protesters who was jailed for his participation in the protests at Thammasat University, argues that the clearest evidence of the evasive public memories of the uprisings and massacre are the names the events have come to be known by, and the most conspicuous site of contested memories is the controversy over the memorial for the events.<ref name=Thongchai-2002>Thongchai Winichakul (2002). \"Remembering/ Silencing the Traumatic Past\". In Shigeharu Tanabe and Charles F. Keyes eds., ''Cultural Crisis and Social Memory: Modernity and Identity in Thailand and Laos''. Honolulu: University of Hawaii Press.</ref>{{RP|265}} The massacre continues to be known in Thailand by the deliberately ambiguous term \"6 October event\". Thongchai argues that this non-committal name is loaded with many unsettled meanings, which imply the absence of any commitment and obscures the past because it is too heavily loaded with contesting voices, placing the massacre on the edge between recognizability and anonymity, between history and the silenced past, and between memory and forgetfulness.<ref name=\"Thongchai-2002\" />{{RP|266}} Thus, in \"remembering\" it, its nomenclature carries overt political significance that continues to reverberate in present-day Thai politics, particularly in relation to the role played by the state and King Bhumibol in the attack on student protesters.\n\nThe commemoration in 1996 represented a significant break in the silence. Yet, during the commemoration, what happened twenty years earlier was retold innumerable times, though without any reference to the undiscussable parts of that history.<ref name=\"Thongchai-2002\" />{{RP|274}} There was also no reaction, not even any comment, from the military or any conservative organization.<ref name=\"Thongchai-2002\" />{{RP|274}} More importantly, the denunciation of state crime avoided imputing blame to any specific individual and the victims' self-sacrifice for society's sake was honored.<ref name=\"Thongchai-2002\" />{{RP|274-275}} The role played by King Bhumibol in inciting the military and police and paramilitary forces to attack the student protesters was not mentioned so as not to target the king as an \"individual\". Yet, this could also be interpreted as an attempt by the state to whitewash history by wishing away parts that it did not want the public to know or remember. In addition, by emphasizing the theme of healing and reconciliation in the remembrance, the Thai state, and by implication the king, have sought to make clear that the commemoration had no interest in and would not be involved in any talk of [[wikt:retribution|retribution]].<ref name=\"Thongchai-2002\" />{{RP|274}} Forty years later, the perpetrators remain unnamed and unpunished. Tyrell Haberkorn, the Thailand scholar, speculates that the death of Rama IX, King Bhumipol Adulyadej, may make it even more difficult to name the perpetrators as Rama IX's reign becomes more idealized.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Haberkorn |first1=Tyrell |title=The Anniversary of a Massacre and the Death of a Monarch |journal=The Journal of Asian Studies |date=2017 |volume=76 |issue=2 |page=269 |pages=281 |doi=10.1017/S0021911817000018 |url=https://www-cambridge-org.ccl.idm.oclc.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/4FD9FA295086CE51B654BCAD342D1F88/S0021911817000018a.pdf/anniversary_of_a_massacre_and_the_death_of_a_monarch.pdf |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-37520961 BBC News interview with Thongchai Winichakul]\n\n{{Thammasat University}}\n{{Thai coups}}\n{{History of Thailand since 1973}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thammasat University Massacre}}\n[[Category:1976 in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1976]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Political repression in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Protests in Thailand]]\n[[Category:School massacres]]\n[[Category:Thammasat University]]\n[[Category:History of Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Rebellions in Thailand]]\n[[Category:October 1976 events in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "refine ref details", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thammasat_University_massacre"}
