unk return|author=Jack Jorgensen|work=[[CBS Sports]]|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref><br>[[Natalya Neidhart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/ronda-rousey-wrestling-training-video/#.Wzm7CdJKjIV|title=Ronda Rousey Seen Training With Natalya In New Promotional Footage (VIDEO)|author= Ryan Satin|work= Pro Wrestling Sheets|date=December 1, 2017|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref><br>[[WWE Performance Center]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/brianmazique/2017/10/26/ronda-rousey-training-at-wwe-performance-center-probably-ends-her-ufc-career-for-good/#2d70b9847024|title=Ronda Rousey Training At WWE Performance Center Probably Ends Her UFC Career For Good|author=Brian Mazique|work=[[Forbes]]|date=October 27, 2017|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n| height       = 5 ft 7 in<ref name=\"WWEProfile\">{{cite web |title=Ronda Rousey - WWE Profile |url=https://www.wwe.com/superstars/ronda-rousey |website=[[WWE]] |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"OWW\">{{cite web |title=Ronda Rousey - OWW Profile |url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/r/ronda-rousey/ |website=Online World of Wrestling |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n| weight       = 134 lb<ref name=\"OWW\"/>\n| debut        = [[WrestleMania 34|April 8, 2018]] \n| retired      = \n}}\n|module2='''Mixed martial arts career'''\n{{Infobox martial artist|child=yes\n| image =\n| height = \n| weight = \n| weight_class = [[Featherweight (MMA)|Featherweight]] (2010\u20132011)<br>[[Bantamweight (MMA)|Bantamweight]] (2012\u20132016)\n| reach = 68 in<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ufc.com/event/UFC175/printFightCard |title=Fight Card \u2013 UFC 175 Weidman vs. Machida |publisher=UFC.com |accessdate=July 11, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717045748/http://www.ufc.com/event/UFC175/printFightCard |archive-date=July 17, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| style = [[Judo]]\n| stance = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| fighting_out_of = [[Santa Monica, California]], U.S.<br>Venice, California, U.S.\n| team = Glendale Fighting Club<br />Gokor Hayastan Academy<br />SK Golden Boys\n| trainer = [[Grappling]]: [[Gene LeBell]], [[Rener Gracie]], [[Gokor Chivichyan]], [[AnnMaria De Mars]]<br />[[Boxing]]: Edmond Tarverdyan\n| rank =6th dan black belt in [[Judo]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ronda-rousey-addresses-womens-equality-while-receiving-6th-164520587--mma.html |title=Ronda Rousey Addresses Women's Equality While Receiving 6th Degree Black Belt In Judo |work=Yahoo Sports |date=March 6, 2018 |accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref>\n| years_active = 2010\u20132016 ([[MMA]])\n| mma_kowin = 3\n| mma_subwin = 9\n| mma_decwin = \n| mma_koloss = 2\n| mma_subloss =\n| mma_decloss =\n| mma_draw =\n| mma_nc =\n| am_win = 3\n| am_subwin = 3\n| am_loss = 0\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Travis Browne]]<br />|August 28, 2017}}\n| relatives = [[AnnMaria De Mars]] (mother)\n| url = {{URL|rondarousey.com/}}\n| footnotes =\n| updated =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|Women's [[judo]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|the {{USA}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Judo at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing]]|[[Judo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 70 kg|70 kg]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Judo Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[2007 World Judo Championships|2007 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[2007 World Judo Championships#70 kg|70 kg]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Judo at the Pan American Games|Pan American Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2007 Pan American Games|2007 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Judo at the 2007 Pan American Games#Middleweight (70 kg)|70 kg]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Pan American Judo Championships|Pan American Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2004 Pan American Judo Championships|2004 Isla Margarita]]|63 kg}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2005 Pan American Judo Championships|2005 Caguas]]|63 kg}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[2006 Pan American Judo Championships|2006 Buenos Aires]]|63 kg}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2007 Pan American Judo Championships|2007 Montreal]]|70 kg}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Ronda Jean Rousey''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|a\u028a|z|i}};<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G5_4wcVyGUc|title=SNL Host Ronda Rousey Lets Beck \"The Wreck\" Bennett Try His Noggin Lock|date=January 20, 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> born February 1, 1987) is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], [[actress]], [[author]], and former [[mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] and [[judoka]]. She is currently signed to [[WWE]] as a wrestler.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/22244988/ronda-rousey-signs-wwe|title=Ronda Rousey signs with WWE|date=January 28, 2018|publisher=ESPN|via=ESPN.com}}</ref> Her longstanding nickname, \"Rowdy\", was inherited from late professional wrestler [[Roddy Piper]].<ref name=PaythePiper/>\n\nAfter becoming the first American woman to earn an [[List of Olympic medalists in judo|Olympic medal in judo]] by winning bronze at the [[Judo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 70 kg|2008 Summer Olympics]], Rousey began pursuing a career in mixed martial arts (MMA). She won her MMA debut for [[King of the Cage]] before going to [[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)|Strikeforce]], where she became the last-ever [[Strikeforce Women's Bantamweight Championship|Strikeforce Women's Bantamweight Champion]] before the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) bought Strikeforce in 2011.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2012/11/16/3654894/dana-white-confirms-ronda-rousey-signed-ufc-mma-news |title=Dana White confirms Ronda Rousey has signed with UFC |publisher=Mmafighting.com |date=November 16, 2012 |accessdate=November 17, 2012 |author=Luke Thomas}}</ref> She was their inaugural female champion when she was named [[UFC Women's Bantamweight Championship|UFC Women's Bantamweight Champion]]. Rousey took part in the first women's fight in UFC history when she successfully defended her title against [[Liz Carmouche]] at [[UFC 157]]. After setting the record for most UFC title defenses by a woman (6), Rousey had her first professional loss in MMA when she lost her title to [[Holly Holm]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/08/02/living/ronda-rousey-profile-feat/ |title=Why Ronda Rousey is such a big deal |author=Grinberg, Emanuella |date=August 3, 2015 |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first1=Tony |last1=Manfred |first2=Scott |last2=Davis |first3=Cork |last3=Gaines |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/most-dominant-athletes-alive-2015-4 |title=The 50 Most Dominant Athletes Alive |date=May 6, 2015 |newspaper=[[Business Insider]] |quote=She's not just undefeated, she's effectively untouched}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=L. Jon |last=Wertheim |url=https://www.si.com/mma/2015/05/12/ronda-rousey-ufc-mma-fighter-armbar |title=The unbreakable Ronda Rousey is the world's most dominant athlete |newspaper=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=May 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2015/05/13/ronda-rousey-lands-on-sports-illustrated-cover-as-the-worlds-most-dominant-athlete/ |newspaper=Washington Post |date=May 13, 2015 |title=Ronda Rousey lands on Sports Illustrated cover as 'the world's most dominant athlete' |first=Des |last=Bieler}}</ref> In 2018, she became the first female fighter to be inducted into the [[UFC Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kwese.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/24012278/ronda-rousey-becomes-first-female-inductee-ufc-hall-fame|title=Ronda Rousey becomes first female inductee into UFC Hall of Fame|work=ESPN|access-date=July 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Rousey began a career in [[professional wrestling]], signing a contract with WWE.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/22244988/ronda-rousey-signs-wwe|title=Ronda Rousey signs with WWE to perform as full-time pro wrestler|website=[[ESPN]]|first=Timothy|last=Fiorvanti|date=January 28, 2018}}</ref> She debuted at [[WrestleMania 34]], and later won the [[WWE Raw Women's Championship|Raw Women's Championship]], her first WWE and professional wrestling title, at [[SummerSlam (2018)|SummerSlam]]. She then headlined the inaugural WWE all-women's pay-per-view event when she successfully defended her title against [[Nikki Bella]] at [[WWE Evolution]]. Rousey had her first WWE loss when she lost her title in the first-ever women's [[WrestleMania]] main-event to [[Becky Lynch]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic non-elimination match|triple threat match]] at [[WrestleMania 35]]; this left her reign as Raw Women's Champion as the second-longest in the title's history at 231 days.\n\nRousey has also enjoyed success as an actress and author, appearing in the films ''[[The Expendables 3]]'' (2014),<ref name=MMAInsider>{{cite web |url=http://mmainsider.net/6582/ronda-rousey-to-star-in-the-expendables-3 |title=Ronda Rousey to Star In 'The Expendables 3' |publisher=MMA Insider.net |date=July 24, 2013 |access-date=July 24, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018031706/http://mmainsider.net/6582/ronda-rousey-to-star-in-the-expendables-3 |archive-date=October 18, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> ''[[Furious 7]]'' (2015),<ref name=FoxNewsLatino>{{cite web |author=Garcia, Victor |url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/sports/2013/08/12/ufc-ronda-rousey-adds-another-blockbuster-role-stirs-debate-on-her-career/ |title=UFC's Ronda Rousey Adds Another Blockbuster Role, Stirs Debate |publisher=[[Fox News Latino]] |date=August 12, 2013}}</ref> and ''[[Mile 22]]'' (2018),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/08/ronda-rousey-worry-encouragement-role-mile-22-mark-wahlberg-movie |title=Ronda Rousey to star in ''Mile 22'' |publisher=MMAJunkie |date=August 16, 2018}}</ref> and releasing her autobiography ''My Fight / Your Fight'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite book |title=Ronda Rousey: ''My Fight / Your Fight'' on Amazon |date=May 15, 2015|isbn = 978-1780894904}}</ref>\n\nRousey is the only woman to win a championship in both the UFC and WWE, as well as the only woman to headline a pay-per-view event in both companies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2015/9/14/9323431/video-of-ronda-rousey-on-ellen-degeneres-show-im-the-highest-paid-fighter-ufc-mma |title=Video of Ronda Rousey on Ellen DeGeneres show: 'I'm the highest paid fighter in UFC' |publisher=MMA Mania |date=September 14, 2015}}</ref> Rousey was voted the best female athlete of all-time in a 2015 ESPN fan poll, and [[Fox Sports]] described her as \"one of the defining athletes of the 21st century.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/ufc/story/ronda-rousey-ufc-sxsw-women-s-empowerment-gender-barriers-031615 |title=Ronda Rousey standing up for women's empowerment by breaking down gender barriers |publisher=Fox Sports |date=March 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/aug/17/adeline-gray-olympic-wrestler-ronda-rousey |title=Why Ronda Rousey has changed the world for women |newspaper=Guardian |date=August 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/mma/ufc-207-ronda-rousey-vs-amanda-nunes-preview-dan-hardy-a7502001.html |title=UFC 207: Ronda Rousey Made MMA What It Is |publisher=Indepdendent |date=December 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/13465064/best-female-athlete-ever-bracket?ex_cid=espnW_newsletter_09142015_1|title=Ronda Rousey tops Serena Williams, voted Best Female Athlete Ever |publisher=ESPNW |date=September 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRonda Jean Rousey was born in [[Riverside, California]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Avila |first1=David A. |title=Rousey lifts female fighters into the spotlight |url=http://www.pe.com/articles/female-761412-kos-boxing.html |website=Riverside Press-Enterprise |accessdate=July 31, 2015 |date=March 2, 2015}}</ref> on February 1, 1987, the youngest of three daughters of [[AnnMaria De Mars]] (''n\u00e9e'' Waddell) and Ron Rousey,<ref>{{cite web |author=Martin, Brian |url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20130222/rowdy-ronda-rousey-defends-her-title-at-ufc-157-first-womens-main-event |title='Rowdy' Ronda Rousey defends her title at UFC 157, first women's main event |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]] |date=February 22, 2013}}</ref> after whom she was named.<ref name=Esquire>Pilon, Mary (November 10, 2015). [http://www.esquire.com/sports/longform/a39499.wS5Po5/ronda-rousey-esquire-1115/?click=mvtest \"Caged: What Drives Ronda Rousey to Wake Up and Fight\"]. ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''.</ref> Her mother, a decorated judoka, was the first American to win a World Judo Championship (in 1984). Rousey is of English, Polish, Trinidadian, and Venezuelan ancestry.<ref>{{cite web |author=Rousey, Ronda |url=https://www.twitter.com/RondaRousey/status/174261056812756992 |title=yes, I'm half venezuelan, a quarter English, a quarter polish, 100% American ;) |publisher=[[Twitter]] |date=February 27, 2012}}</ref> Her Venezuelan maternal grandfather was partly of Afro-Venezuelan descent and her Trinidadian maternal great-grandfather, Alfred E Waddell, was a doctor who emigrated to Canada and became one of the first black physicians in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theroot.com/blogs/the_grapevine/2016/03/ronda_rousey_s_great_grandfather_was_dr_alfred_e_waddell_one_of_north_america.html|title=Ronda Rousey's Great-Grandfather Was Dr. Alfred E. Waddell, One of North America's 1st Black Physicians|date=March 24, 2016|work=The Root|access-date=March 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327104358/http://www.theroot.com/blogs/the_grapevine/2016/03/ronda_rousey_s_great_grandfather_was_dr_alfred_e_waddell_one_of_north_america.html|archive-date=March 27, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://judoinfo.com/demars.htm |title=Judo in the US: Interview with AnnMaria DeMars |publisher=Judoinfo.com |date=August 24, 2009 |accessdate=May 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.si.com/more-sports/2012/11/02/ronda-rousey-outtakes |work=Sports Illustrated |title=Five outtakes with Ronda Rousey |date=November 2, 2012}}</ref> Her stepfather is an [[aerospace engineer]].<ref>[http://sportsclash.com/players/mma-fighters/ronda-rousey/ \"Ronda Rousey\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720135624/http://sportsclash.com/players/mma-fighters/ronda-rousey/ |date=July 20, 2018 }}. Sportsclash. Retrieved January 11, 2016.</ref> Her biological father, after breaking his back sledding with his daughters and learning that he would be a paraplegic, committed suicide in 1995 when Rousey was eight.<ref name=Esquire /><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N-bpByHvAZs \"UFC 190: Extended Preview\"]. [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]. [[YouTube]]. July 18, 2015 3:32 mark</ref> AnnMaria pursued a [[Ph.D.]] in educational psychology at the [[University of California, Riverside]] as her daughters grew up.<ref name=Esquire /><ref>Alexander, Jim (July 24, 2015). [http://www.pe.com/articles/rousey-774710-fighting-hard.html \"ALEXANDER: Rousey's stardom goes way beyond UFC boundaries\"]. ''[[The Press Enterprise]]''.</ref>\n\nFor the first six years of her life, Rousey struggled with speech and could not form an intelligible sentence due to [[Developmental verbal dyspraxia|apraxia]], a neurological childhood speech sound disorder.<ref>{{cite web |author=Foss, Mike |title=Ronda Rousey discusses the rare disorder that made her think she was stupid as a child |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/08/ronda-rousey-discusses-the-rare-disorder-that-made-her-think-she-was-stupid-as-a-child |date=August 6, 2015 |newspaper=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> This speech disorder was attributed to being born with her umbilical cord wrapped around her neck. When Rousey was three years old, her mother and father moved from Riverside, California, to [[Jamestown, North Dakota]], to obtain intensive speech therapy with specialists at [[Minot State University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronda Rousey: The World's Most Dangerous Woman |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/sports/features/ronda-rousey-the-worlds-most-dangerous-woman-20150528 |accessdate=August 9, 2015|date=May 28, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wLerbRVQzaE |title=Raising Ronda Rousey by AnnMaria De Mars (aka Ronda Rousey's Mom) |date=February 21, 2013 |accessdate= |website=YouTube.com |publisher=MMAWeekly.com }}</ref> Rousey dropped out of high school and later earned her [[G.E.D.|GED]].<ref name=\"Sanneh\">{{cite journal |last=Sanneh |first=Kelefa |date=July 28, 2014 |title=Profiles: Mean Girl |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |volume=90 |issue=21 |pages=54\u201363 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/07/28/mean-girl |accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref> She was raised between Jamestown and [[Southern California]], retiring from her judo career at 21 and starting her MMA career at 22 when she realized that she did not want to spend her life in a conventional field of work.<ref name=UFCProfile>{{cite web |title=\"Rowdy\" Ronda Rousey \u2013 Official UFC Fighter Profile |url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Ronda-Rousey |publisher=UFC.com |accessdate=August 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Olympic judo career==\nRousey began [[judo]] with her mother at the age of 11. Rousey trained with her mother until she was 13, when she accidentally broke her mother's wrist.<ref name=\"UFC TOM 54\">{{cite magazine |last=Kelly |first=Seth |title=Can Anyone Beat Ronda Rousey? |date=2015 |magazine=UFC: The Official Magazine |page=54 |url=http://den.bigleo.com/2015/02/can-anyone-beat-ronda-rousey/}}</ref> At 17, Rousey was the youngest judoka to qualify for the [[2004 Olympic Games]] in [[Athens]]. Rousey lost in her first match to silver medalist [[Claudia Heill]] in the 63&nbsp;kg bracket. Also in 2004, Rousey won a gold medal at the World Junior Judo Championships in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]].\n\nIn April 2006, she became the first female U.S. judoka in nearly 10 years to win an A-Level tournament as she went 5-0 to claim gold at the Birmingham World Cup in [[Great Britain]]. Later that year, the 19-year-old won the bronze medal at the Junior World Championships, becoming the first U.S. athlete to win two Junior World medals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://judoinfo.com/rondarousey/|title=Ronda Rousey Interview \u2014 Judo Champion \u2013 Judo Info|website=judoinfo.com|accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2007, Rousey moved up to 70&nbsp;kg where she ranked as one of the top three women in the world. She won the silver medal at the [[2007 World Judo Championships]] in the middleweight division and the gold medal at the [[2007 Pan American Games]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Pan American Games Miami|url=http://www.judoinside.com/event/3985/2007_Pan_American_Games_Rio_de_Janeiro|website=JudoInside|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, Rousey competed at the [[2008 Olympic Games]] in [[Beijing]], [[China]]. She lost her quarterfinal to the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] ex-world champion [[Edith Bosch]] but qualified for a bronze medal match through the [[repechage]] bracket. Rousey defeated [[Annett Boehm]] by [[Yuko (judo)|Yuko]] to win a bronze medal (Judo offers two bronze medals per weight class.) With the victory, Rousey became the first American to win an Olympic medal in women's judo since its inception as an [[Judo at the 1992 Summer Olympics|Olympic sport in 1992]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-ufc-ronda-rousey-pg-012-photo.html |title=Ronda Rousey, Annett Boehm |website=[[LA Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/beijing/fight/2008-08-13-womensjudo_N.htm |website=USA Today |title=Rousey's bronze makes U.S. history in women's judo |date=August 13, 2008 |first=Gary |last=Mihoces}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\n===Training===\nRousey retired from judo at 21 after the Olympics. After winning her Olympic medal, Rousey shared a studio apartment with a roommate in [[Venice, Los Angeles|Venice Beach]], California and worked three jobs as a bartender and cocktail waitress to support herself and her dog.<ref name=\"UFC TOM 52\">{{cite magazine |last=Kelly |first=Seth |title=Can Anyone Beat Ronda Rousey? |url=http://den.bigleo.com/2015/02/can-anyone-beat-ronda-rousey/ |date=2015 |magazine=UFC: The Official Magazine |page=52}}</ref>\n\nWhen Rousey started learning judo, her mother took her to judo clubs run by her old teammates. Rousey went to Hayastan MMA Academy, which was run by [[Gokor Chivichyan]], where she trained with fellow future MMA fighters [[Manny Gamburyan]] and [[Karo Parisyan]]. According to Rousey, Hayastan practiced \"a more brawling style of judo versus the more technical Japanese style.\" Rousey trained mostly with males bigger than she was and often got frustrated and cried when she got thrown and could not throw somebody. \"Probably from 2002 to 2005 I cried every single night of training,\" Rousey remarked.<ref name=\"UFC TOM 54\" />\n\nRousey trained closely with Gamburyan. After injuring her knee when she was 16, Gamburyan volunteered to open the gym every afternoon and work with her personally. Back in 2004, her teammates thought Rousey \"would kill these girls\" in MMA, but also thought she was \"too pretty to get hit in the face\" and should keep doing judo. While Gamburyan and Parisyan went into MMA, Rousey stuck with judo but remained in touch with MMA through them. The first MMA fight she took an interest in watching was Manny Gamburyan versus [[Nate Diaz]] in [[The Ultimate Fighter 5|The Ultimate Fighter finale]]. Rousey stated she never got as excited watching judo or any other sport. After the 2008 Olympics the following year, she decided to start MMA through Team Hayastan.<ref name=\"UFC TOM 54\" />\n\nRousey also trained at the Glendale Fighting Club, to which she was introduced by Gamburyan and other Hayastan teammates. She started training under her long-term MMA coach Edmond Tarverdyan at GFC.<ref name=\"UFC TOM 55\">{{cite magazine |last=Kelly |first=Seth |title=Can Anyone Beat Ronda Rousey? |magazine=UFC: The Official Magazine |page=55 |date=2015 |url=http://den.bigleo.com/2015/02/can-anyone-beat-ronda-rousey/ |accessdate=December 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe trained in [[Jujutsu|Jiu Jitsu]] at Dynamix MMA with Henry Akins from 2011 to 2014<ref>U of MMA [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nwAnGZiF-Qo \"Ronda Rousey & Henry Akins of Dynamix Martial Arts Interview\"] Published November 14, 2011. Retrieved March 11, 2016</ref> and went on to train with Ryron Graice and [[Rener Gracie]] of Gracie Academy,<ref>GracieBreakdown [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kLKYeejOpGw \"Ronda Rousey Gracie Jiu-Jitsu Training Camp\"] Published February 17, 2014. Retrieved March 11, 2016</ref> as well as [[BJ Penn]] of Art of Jiu Jitsu.<ref>[http://www.mmafighting.com/2015/2/17/8051465/ronda-rousey-and-bj-penn-spar-at-art-of-jiu-jitsu \"Ronda Rousey and BJ Penn spar at Art of Jiu-Jitsu\"] By MMA Fighting Newswire on February 17, 2015.</ref>\n\n===Early career (2010\u20132011)===\nRousey made her mixed martial arts debut as an amateur on August 6, 2010. She defeated Hayden Munoz by submission due to an armbar in 23 seconds.<ref name=\"Amateur and Pro Debuts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mmarising.com/articles/2011/03/28/weekend-recap-ronda-rousey-wins-pro-mma-debut/ |title=Weekend Recap: Ronda Rousey Wins Pro MMA Debut |publisher=MMARising.com |date=March 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe entered the quarterfinals of the Tuff-N-Uff 145&nbsp;lbs women's tournament on November 12, 2010, and submitted promotional veteran Autumn Richardson with an armbar in 57 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmarising.com/articles/2010/11/12/ronda-rousey-tay-stratford-advance-at-tuff-n-uff/ |title=Ronda Rousey, Tay Stratford Advance At Tuff-N-Uff |publisher=MMARising.com |date=November 12, 2010 |accessdate=November 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nRousey faced Taylor Stratford in the Tuff-N-Uff tournament semi-finals on January 7, 2011, and won by technical submission due to an armbar in 24 seconds. She then announced plans to turn pro and was replaced in the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmarising.com/articles/2011/01/08/gray-edges-swinney-rousey-wins-quickly-at-tuff-n-uff/ |title=Gray Edges Swinney, Rousey Wins Quickly At Tuff-N-Uff |publisher=MMARising.com |date=January 8, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011}}</ref> Rousey has a 3-0 record in amateur MMA competition, and the combined duration of all her amateur fights is under 2 minutes.<ref name=UFCProfile />\n\nRousey made her professional mixed martial arts debut on March 27, 2011, at King of the Cage: Turning Point. She submitted Ediane Gomes with an armbar in 25 seconds.<ref name=\"Amateur and Pro Debuts\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Weekend-Rundown-Drwal-Demolishes-Chocolate-in-Homecoming-31140 |title=Weekend Rundown: Drwal Demolishes 'Chocolate' in Homecoming |website=Sherdog |date=March 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nRousey faced kickboxing champion Charmaine Tweet in an MMA bout at Hard Knocks Fighting Championship: School of Hard Knocks 12 on June 17, 2011, in [[Calgary]], Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmarising.com/news/2011/05/05/ronda-rousey-vs-charmaine-tweet-set-for-june-17th/ |title=Ronda Rousey vs Charmaine Tweet Set For June 17th |publisher=MMARising.com |date=May 5, 2011 |accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref> She submitted Tweet with an armbar in 49 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmarising.com/articles/2011/06/17/ronda-rousey-wins-quickly-in-hard-knocks-12-co-feature/ |title=Ronda Rousey Wins Quickly In Hard Knocks 12 Co-Feature |publisher=MMARising.com |date=June 17, 2011 |accessdate=June 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Martin, Brian |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150729/Ronda-Rousey-Pro-fight-No-2-defeated-Charmaine-Tweet-via-submission-armbar-049-first-round |title=Ronda Rousey: pro-fight No. 2 \u2013 defeated Charmaine Tweet via submission |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]] |date=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Strikeforce (2011\u20132012)===\n====Early success====\nRousey was scheduled to make her [[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)|Strikeforce]] debut against [[Sarah D'Alelio]] on July 30, 2011, at [[Strikeforce: Fedor vs. Henderson]] in [[Hoffman Estates, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmarising.com/news/2011/07/01/strikeforce-adds-two-more-womens-bouts-to-july-30-card/ |title=Strikeforce Adds Two More Women's Bouts To July 30 Card |publisher=MMARising.com |date=July 1, 2011}}</ref> The fight was postponed and eventually took place on the Strikeforce Challengers 18 main card on August 12, 2011, in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmarising.com/news/2011/07/03/ronda-rousey-vs-sarah-dalelio-now-set-for-august-12th/ |title=Ronda Rousey vs Sarah D'Alelio Now Set For August 12th |publisher=MMARising.com |date=July 3, 2011}}</ref> Rousey defeated D'Alelio by technical submission due to an armbar early in the first round. The victory was controversial. Rousey claimed that D'Alelio yelled \"tap\" more than once and that D'Alelio denied this and claimed to have yelled \"Aaaahhh\". According to the unified rules of mixed martial arts, either one of these utterances would still be a verbal submission.<ref>Martin, Brian (July 29, 2015). [http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150729/ronda-rousey-pro-fight-no-3-defeated-sarah-d8217alelio-via-technical-submission-armbar-025-first-round \"Ronda Rousey: Pro fight No. 3 \u2013 defeated Sarah D'Alelio via technical submission (armbar), 0:25, first round\"]. ''Los Angeles Daily News''.</ref>\n\nRousey faced [[Julia Budd]] at Strikeforce Challengers 20 on November 18, 2011, in Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2011/08/julia-budd-vs-ronda-rousey-booked-for-november-strikeforce-challengers-event |title=Julia Budd vs. Ronda Rousey booked for November Strikeforce Challengers event |work=[[MMAjunkie.com]] |date=August 31, 2011}}</ref> She won via submission due to an armbar in the first round, dislocating Budd's elbow in the process. Following the fight, she announced plans to move down to 135 pounds to challenge [[Miesha Tate]], the [[Strikeforce Women's Bantamweight Championship|Strikeforce Women's Bantamweight Champion]] at the time, with whom she had developed a [[Miesha Tate vs. Ronda Rousey|much-publicized rivalry]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmarising.com/articles/2011/11/18/ronda-rousey-submits-julia-budd-plans-drop-to-135/ |title=Ronda Rousey Submits Julia Budd, Plans Drop To 135 |publisher=MMARising.com |date=November 18, 2011 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150729/Ronda-Rousey-Pro-fight-No-4-defeated-Julia-Budd-via-submission-armbar-039-first-round |title=Ronda Rousey interview: pro-fight No.4 \u2013 defeated Julia Budd via submission |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|date=July 29, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nDuring his appearance on ''[[The Joe Rogan Experience]]'', Rousey's trainer Edmond Tarverdyan said that Rousey started her MMA career in the 145&nbsp;lb division because she had to be able to make weight at short notice, due to the difficulty of finding willing opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://podcasts.joerogan.net/podcasts/ronda-rousey-edmond-tarverdayn |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150903222304/http://podcasts.joerogan.net/podcasts/ronda-rousey-edmond-tarverdayn |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 3, 2015 |title=Joe Rogan Experience podcast 690 |publisher=Joe Rogan.net }}</ref>\n\n====Women's Bantamweight Champion====\nRousey challenged Tate for her Strikeforce title on March 3, 2012, in Columbus, Ohio. She defeated Tate by submission due to an armbar in the first round, again dislocating her opponent's elbow, to become the new Strikeforce Women's Bantamweight Champion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmarising.com/articles/2012/03/03/ronda-rousey-sarah-kaufman-win-big-at-strikeforce-in-ohio/ |title=Ronda Rousey, Sarah Kaufman Win Big At Strikeforce In Ohio |publisher=MMARising.com |date=March 3, 2012 |accessdate=March 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150729/Ronda-Rousey-Pro-fight-No-5-defeated-Miesha-Tate-via-submission-armbar-427-first-round |title=Ronda Rousey interview: Pro fight No.5 \u2013 defeated Miesha Tate via submission |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|date=July 29, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nRousey appeared in ''All Access: Ronda Rousey'' on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]. The half-hour special debuted on August 8, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2012/08/reminder-all-access-ronda-rousey-debuts-tonight-on-showtime |title=Reminder: 'All Access: Ronda Rousey' debuts tonight on Showtime |work=MMAjunkie.com |date=August 8, 2012 |accessdate=August 9, 2012 |author=Staff}}</ref> UFC President [[Dana White]] revealed during the program that \"In the next 10 years, if there's a woman in the octagon, it's probably going to be Ronda Rousey.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2012/08/all-access-video-white-says-rousey-would-likely-be-first-female-ufc-fighter |title='All Access' video: White says Rousey would likely be first female UFC fighter |date=August 9, 2012 |accessdate=August 9, 2012 |work=MMAjunkie.com |author=Staff}}</ref> The second installment of the special aired on August 15, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2012/08/video-showtimes-all-access-ronda-rousey-second-episode |title=Video: Showtime's 'All Access: Ronda Rousey\" second episode |author=Staff |date=August 16, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |work=MMAjunkie.com}}</ref> Rousey also appeared on ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2012/08/video-strikeforce-champ-ronda-rousey-gives-conan-obrien-a-lesson-in-armbars |title=Video: Strikeforce champ Ronda Rousey gives Conan O'Brien a lesson in armbars |work=MMAjunkie.com |author=Staff |date=August 9, 2012 |accessdate=August 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRousey defended her Strikeforce title against [[Sarah Kaufman (fighter)|Sarah Kaufman]] at ''[[Strikeforce: Rousey vs. Kaufman]]'' on August 18, 2012, in San Diego, California.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/strikeforce/2012/6/7/3072072/ronda-rousey-vs-sarah-kaufman-set-for-august-in-san-diego |title=Ronda Rousey vs. Sarah Kaufman Set for August in San Diego |publisher=MMAFighting.com |date=June 7, 2012 |accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref> Rousey said that she would throw Kaufman's arm at her corner after ripping it off with an [[armbar]], and threatened to choke or pound Kaufman's face to death.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2012/08/strikeforces-coker-rousey-cant-just-be-a-marketing-machine-with-a-pretty-face |title=Strikeforce's Coker: Rousey 'can't just be a marketing machine with a pretty face' |work=MMAjunkie.com |author=Matt Erickson |date=August 17, 2012 |accessdate=August 18, 2012}}</ref> During the fight, Rousey quickly took Kaufman down and submitted her with an armbar in 54 seconds to retain the Strikeforce Women's Bantamweight Championship. After the fight, Rousey announced that if former Strikeforce Women's Featherweight Champion [[Cristiane Santos|Cristiane \"Cyborg\" Santos]] wanted to fight her, it would have to take place at bantamweight.<ref>{{cite web |author=Sargent, Robert |url=http://www.mmarising.com/articles/2012/08/18/ronda-rousey-submits-sarah-kaufman-retains-strikeforce-title/ |title=Ronda Rousey Submits Sarah Kaufman, Retains Strikeforce Title |publisher=MMARising.com |date=August 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Ronda-Rousey-Armbars-Sarah-Kaufman-Retains-Strikeforce-Crown-in-54-Seconds-44993 |title=Ronda Rousey Armbars Sarah Kaufman, Retains Strikeforce Crown in 54 Seconds |website=Sherdog |date=August 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150729/Ronda-Rousey-Pro-fight-No-6-defeated-Sarah-Kaufman-via-submission-armbar-054-first-round |title=Ronda Rousey interview:Pro-fight No.6 \u2013 defeated Sarah Kaufman via submission |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|date=July 29, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship (2012\u20132016)===\n\n====First female UFC Champion====\n\n[[File:Ronda Rousey.jpeg|thumb|Rousey in 2012]]\nIn November 2012, the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] announced that Rousey had become the first female fighter to sign with the UFC.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/mma/story/_/id/8639858/ronda-rousey-becomes-first-female-sign-ufc-deal |title=Ronda Rousey signs landmark deal |publisher=espn.go.com |date=November 16, 2012 |accessdate=November 17, 2012 |author=Josh Gross}}</ref> UFC President Dana White officially announced at the ''[[UFC on Fox: Henderson vs. Diaz]]'' pre-fight press conference that Rousey was the first [[UFC Women's Bantamweight Championship|UFC Women's Bantamweight Champion]].\n\nRousey originally opposed using the nickname her friends gave her, \"Rowdy\", feeling it would be disrespectful to [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] [[Roddy Piper|\"Rowdy\" Roddy Piper]]. After meeting Piper (circa 2012 or 2013) through [[Gene LeBell]], who helped train both of them, Piper personally gave his approval.<ref name=PaythePiper/>\n\nRousey defended her title against [[Liz Carmouche]] on February 23, 2013, at [[UFC 157]]. Despite being caught in an early standing neck crank attempt from Carmouche, Rousey went on to successfully defend her Bantamweight Championship title, winning the fight at 4:49 into the first round by submission due to an armbar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/03/womens-mma-report-rousey-retains-ufc-title-four-advance-in-cfa-tournament |title=Women's MMA Report: Rousey retains UFC title, four advance in CFA tournament |date=March 4, 2013 |accessdate=March 6, 2013 |first=Robert |last=Sargent}}</ref> Carmouche dislocated Ronda Rousey's jaw during the fight.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ufc.com/media/UFC-168--Ronda-Rousey-Megan-Olivi-Post-Fight-Interview |title=UFC168 Ronda Rousey backstage interview |publisher=UFC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150729/Ronda-Rousey-Pro-fight-No-7-defeated-Liz-Carmouche-via-submission-armbar-449-first-round |title=Ronda Rousey: Pro fight No. 2 \u2013 defeated Charmaine Tweet via submission (armbar), 0:49, first round |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|date=July 29, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Cat Zingano]] defeated Miesha Tate at ''[[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Jones vs. Team Sonnen Finale]]'', Dana White announced that Zingano would be a coach of [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Rousey vs. Team Tate#The Ultimate Fighter 18|''The Ultimate Fighter 18'']] against Rousey. On May 28, Zingano having suffered a knee injury, it was announced Miesha Tate would coach The Ultimate Fighter 18 against Rousey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/watch/the-ultimate-fighter/story/zingano-out-082913 |title=Tate replacing Zingano on TUF |publisher=Fox Sports |date=May 28, 2013 |author=A. J. Perez}}</ref>\n\nRousey faced Miesha Tate, in a rematch from Strikeforce, at [[UFC 168]] on December 28, 2013. After going past the first two rounds, with Tate surviving an armbar attempt and a triangle attempt, Rousey finally submitted Tate via armbar in the third round to retain her Bantamweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/ufc/story/ronda-rousey-extends-armbar-streak-with-third-round-submission-122813?gt1=39002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423163612/http://msn.foxsports.com/ufc/story/ronda-rousey-extends-armbar-streak-with-third-round-submission-122813?gt1=39002 |archivedate=April 23, 2014 |title=Rousey extends armbar streak with third-round win over Tate at UFC 168 |publisher=msn.foxsports.com |date=December 28, 2013}}</ref> In an interview with ''Los Angeles Daily News'', Rousey said she had lost muscle during her film commitments and not been able to regain her full strength for the Tate fight.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150729/Ronda-Rousey-Pro-fight-No-8-defeated-Miesha-Tate-via-submission-armbar-058-third-round |title=Ronda Rousey interview: pro fight No.8&nbsp;\u2013 defeated Miesha Tate via submission |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|date=July 29, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n====Record-setting championship reign====\nIt was announced at the UFC 168 post-fight press conference that Rousey would defend the UFC Women's Bantamweight Championship against fellow Olympic medalist and undefeated fighter [[Sara McMann]] in the main event at [[UFC 170]] on February 22, 2014. Rousey won the fight by TKO after knocking down McMann with a knee to the body just over a minute into the first round. This marked Rousey's first career win via a method other than armbar. The stoppage led to controversy, with some sports writers and attendants finding it premature.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lance |last=Pugmire |title=Ronda Rousey uses a new twist to beat Sara McMann in UFC 170 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=February 22, 2014 |accessdate=May 22, 2015 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2014/feb/22/sports/la-sp-ufc-rousey-mcmann-20140223}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Iole |title=UFC 170: Ronda Rousey dominates Sara McMann, bout ends in controversial fashion |work=[[Yahoo!]] |date=February 23, 2014 |accessdate=May 22, 2015 |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/ufc-170--ronda-rousey-dominates-sara-mcmann--finishes-her-in-controversial-fashion-052344724-mma.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150729/Ronda-Rousey-Pro-fight-No-9-defeated-Sara-McMann-via-TKO-knee-to-body-106-first-round |title=Ronda Rousey interview: pro fight No.9&nbsp;\u2013 defeated Sarah McMann via TKO |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|date=July 29, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Rousey was named one of espnW's Impact 25.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-commentary/impact25/slideshow/12020053/3/ronda-rousey-27-ufc-bantamweight-champion |title=2014 espnW Impact 25 |publisher=ESPN |date=2014 |accessdate=March 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2014, it was announced that Rousey would defend the UFC Women's Bantamweight Championship against [[Alexis Davis (fighter)|Alexis Davis]] in the co-main event at [[UFC 175]] on July 5, 2014. She won the fight via knockout 16 seconds into the first round. Rousey broke her thumb during the fight.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150729/ronda-rousey-pro-fight-no-10-defeated-alexis-davis-via-ko-punches-016-first-round |title=Ronda Rousey interview: pro fight 10&nbsp;\u2013 defeated Alexis Davis via KO |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|date=July 29, 2015 }}</ref> The emphatic win also earned Rousey her second ''Performance of the Night'' bonus award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/07/ufc-175-bonuses-weidman-machida-rousey-font-get-50000 |title=UFC 175 bonuses: Weidman, Machida, Rousey, Font get $50,000 |publisher=mmajunkie.com |author=Matt Erickson |accessdate=July 6, 2014 |date=July 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA match between Rousey and [[Cat Zingano]] was scheduled to take place at [[UFC 182]] for the women's bantamweight title.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmanewsnow.com/index.php/mmanews/cat-zingano-vs-ronda-rousey-confirmed |title=Cat Zingano vs. Ronda Rousey Confirmed |publisher=Mmanewsnow.com |date=September 28, 2014 |accessdate=March 13, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229155905/http://mmanewsnow.com/index.php/mmanews/cat-zingano-vs-ronda-rousey-confirmed |archivedate=December 29, 2014  }}</ref> However, the fight was moved to February 28, 2015, at [[UFC 184]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmasucka.com/2014/10/29/ufc-president-dana-white-announces-weidman-belfort-rousey-zingano-ufc-184/ |title=UFC President Dana White announces Weidman-Belfort and Rousey-Zingano at UFC 184&nbsp;\u2013 &#124; The Leading Canadian MMA Website&nbsp;\u2013 News, Radio, Interviews |publisher=mmasucka.com |date= October 29, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2015}}</ref> Rousey defeated Zingano with an armbar in 14 seconds, the shortest match in UFC championship history until [[Conor McGregor]] defeated [[Jose Aldo]] in 13 seconds 11 months later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150729/Ronda-Rousey-Pro-fight-No-11-defeated-Cat-Zingano-via-submission-armbar-014-first-round |title=Ronda Rousey interview: pro fight 11&nbsp;\u2013 defeated Cat Zingano via submission |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|date=July 29, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsjoe.ie/amp/mma/conor-mcgregors-brutal-ko-of-jose-aldo-set-a-new-ufc-record-54724 |title=Conor McGregor's brutal KO of Jose Aldo set a new UFC record|last=McCarry|first=Patrick|date=December 13, 2015|publisher=Sports Joe|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRousey fought [[Bethe Correia]] on August 1, 2015, in Brazil, at [[UFC 190]], winning the bout by knockout 34 seconds into the first round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/08/ufc-190-results-in-latest-masterpiece-ronda-rousey-kos-bethe-correia-in-34-seconds |title=UFC 190 results: In latest masterpiece, Ronda Rousey KOs Bethe Correia in 34 seconds |publisher=mmajunkie.com |author=Matt Erickson |accessdate=August 2, 2015 |date=August 2, 2015}}</ref> Rousey dedicated the match to \"Rowdy\" Roddy Piper, who died the day before, commenting that Piper was one of her inspirations and had endorsed her use of his nickname.<ref>Auguste, David (August 2, 2015). [http://espn.go.com/sportsnation/post/_/id/13357744/ronda-rousey-pays-tribute-rowdy-roddy-piper-dedicates-match-him \"Ronda Rousey pays tribute to 'Rowdy' Roddy Piper, dedicates match to him\"]. ESPN.</ref>\n\nThe bout was Rousey's sixth with the UFC, all of which had been victories. She spent 1077 seconds in the octagon to attain all six and accumulated $1,080,000 in prize money; this equated to nearly $1002.79 for every second spent fighting.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fox |first1=Jeff |title=Ronda Rousey Career Earnings |url=http://mma-manifesto.com/ufc-fighter-salary-database/salary-main/ronda-rousey-career-earnings.html |website=MMA Manifesto |publisher=Bloguin |accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ronda Rousey Fight Results |website=ESPN |url=http://espn.go.com/mma/fighter/history/_/id/2563796/ronda-rousey |accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> Her average time of 2 minutes and 59 seconds was less than the average time of a single match in every UFC weight class, the fastest of which was the Heavyweight division with a time of 7 minutes and 59 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=Luke |title=Crunching Numbers: In MMA, There's No Such Thing as a Heavy Wait |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/ufc/2012/4/1/2917868/crunching-numbers-mma-ufc-146-heavyweight-cain-velasquez-frank-mir-alistair-overeem-news |website=MMA Fighting |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=September 30, 2015|date=April 2012 }}</ref>\n\n====Title loss and subsequent retirement====\nIn her seventh title defense, Rousey faced [[Holly Holm]] in the main event at [[UFC 193]] on November 15, 2015.<ref name=\"RouseyHolm\">{{cite news |url=http://411mania.com/mma/ronda-rousey-vs-holly-holm-named-ufc-193-main-event/ |title=Ronda Rousey vs. Holly Holm Named UFC 193 Main Event |publisher=411 Mania |author=Larry Csonka |date=August 28, 2015 |accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref> Despite being a heavy betting favorite, Rousey was unable to get Holm to the ground and had no answer for Holm's superior striking. Early in the second round, Holm knocked Rousey out with a high kick to the neck, ending Rousey's three-year reign as champion. It was also her first loss. After the fight, Rousey and Holm were each awarded a ''Fight of the Night'' bonus of $50,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/11/ufc-193-bonuses-if-you-dont-think-holly-holm-was-on-the-list-youre-insane |title=UFC 193 bonuses: If you don't think Holly Holm was on the list, you're insane |publisher=mmajunkie.com |author=Staff |date=November 15, 2015 |accessdate=November 15, 2015}}</ref> She was also medically suspended by UFC on November 18, 2015, which included a no-contact suspension for 45 days, and no fights for 60 days, and would have to depend on CT scan results to have the suspension reduced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2590602-ronda-rouseys-medical-suspension-released-after-ufc-193-knockout-by-holly-holm |title=Ronda Rousey's Medical Suspension Released After UFC 193 Knockout by Holly Holm |website=Bleacher Report |author=Matt Jones |date=November 18, 2015 |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref> She was medically cleared on December 9, 2015.<ref>{{cite av media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1TUkzHnc4LI |title=Ronda Rousey's future in the UFC |date=December 9, 2015 |publisher= |via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nAfter over a year away from the sport, Rousey returned to face current champion [[Amanda Nunes]] on December 30, 2016, in the main event at [[UFC 207]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/ufc/story/ronda-rousey-returns-at-ufc-207-to-face-amanda-nunes-101216|title=Ronda Rousey returns at UFC 207 to face Amanda Nunes|publisher=foxsports.com|author=Damon Martin|date=October 12, 2016|accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref> She lost the fight via TKO due to punches at just 48 seconds into the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Amanda-Nunes-Shreds-Ronda-Rousey-to-Retain-UFC-Womens-Bantamweight-Title-115551|title=Amanda Nunes shreds Ronda Rousey to retain UFC Women's Bantamweight title|publisher=sherdog.com|author=Brian Knapp|date=December 31, 2016|accessdate=December 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlthough she did not formally announce her retirement, when asked if she would fight MMA again by Ellen DeGeneres in 2018, Rousey replied, \"I think it's just as likely as me going back to another Olympics for judo.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/trentreinsmith/2018/03/13/ronda-rousey-not-officially-retiring-from-ufc-but-return-seems-unlikely-wwe/|title=Ronda Rousey Isn't Officially Retired From UFC, But Return Is Unlikely|first=Trent|last=Reinsmith|website=Forbes|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref> She was inducted into the UFC Hall of Fame in July 2018.\n\n===UFC pay-per-views===\n(main event and co-main event)\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Fight !! Event!! Buys\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | {{dts|2013|February|23|format=mdy}}\n| '''Ronda Rousey''' vs. '''Liz Carmouche'''\n| [[UFC 157]]\n| 450,000\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | {{dts|2013|December|28|format=mdy}}\n| '''Ronda Rousey''' vs. '''Miesha Tate''' (co)\n| [[UFC 168]]\n| 1,025,000\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | {{dts|2014|February|22|format=mdy}}\n| '''Ronda Rousey''' vs. '''Sara McMann'''\n| [[UFC 170]]\n| 375,000\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | {{dts|2014|July|5|format=mdy}}\n| '''Ronda Rousey''' vs. '''Alexis Davis''' (co)\n| [[UFC 175]]\n| 545,000\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | {{dts|2015|February|28|format=mdy}}\n| '''Ronda Rousey''' vs. '''Cat Zingano'''\n| [[UFC 184]]\n| 600,000\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | {{dts|2015|August|1|format=mdy}}\n| '''Ronda Rousey''' vs. '''Bethe Correia'''\n| [[UFC 190]]\n| 900,000\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | {{dts|2015|November|15|format=mdy}}\n| '''Ronda Rousey''' vs. '''Holly Holm'''\n| [[UFC 193]]\n| 1,100,000\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | {{dts|2016|December|30|format=mdy}}\n| '''Amanda Nunes''' vs. '''Ronda Rousey'''\n| [[UFC 207]]\n| 1,100,000\n|-\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" | Total sales\n! 6,095,000\n|}\n\n==Mixed martial arts fighting style==\n{{Quote box| quote = While some fighters strike an impassive pose \u2026 Rousey is nothing if not expressive. She smiles often, squinting so tightly that her eyes disappear. She cries easily, a girlhood habit she never outgrew. And before each fight she glares at her opponent as if she were getting ready to put a permanent end to a lifelong feud. After the fight, she is all smiles again, and usually unblemished. |source=- ''[[The New Yorker]]'', 2014<ref name=\"Sanneh\" />|align=right | width=40% }}\nIn a 2012 interview<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmainterviews.tv/2012/02/27/ronda-rousey-extended-interview-talks-miesha-tate-weight-cut-and-much-more/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20160308061240/http://mmainterviews.tv/2012/02/27/ronda-rousey-extended-interview-talks-miesha-tate-weight-cut-and-much-more/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 8, 2016 |title=Ronda Rousey extended interview, talks Miesha Tate at Strikeforce, weight cut and much more |publisher=MMA Interviews.tv }}</ref> before her first match with [[Miesha Tate]], Rousey said: \"When I was doing judo my main advantage was my conditioning and my pace; I used to wear people out.\" She had taken to heart a quote from [[Ryoko Tani]] to fight every five seconds as if it was the last five seconds of the match.\n\nA decorated judoka, Rousey typically grounds an opponent with [[Throw (grappling)|hip throws]] and [[Sweep (martial arts)|sweeps]], then seeks to finish with strikes or submissions.<ref name=hiptoss>{{cite web |title=UFC 168 Results: 'Weidman vs. Silva 2' Play-by-Play & Updates |website=Sherdog |date=December 28, 2013 |accessdate=October 12, 2014 |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-168-Results-Weidman-vs-Silva-2-PlaybyPlay-Updates-60985}}</ref><ref name=sweep>{{cite news |first=Anthony |last=Gonzalez |title=Strikeforce: Ronda Rousey vs. Sarah Kaufman Results |work=realcombatmedia.com |date=August 19, 2012 |accessdate=October 12, 2014 |url=http://realcombatmedia.com/2012/08/strikeforce-ronda-rousey-vs-sarah-kaufman-results/}}</ref> From top position, she usually attacks with punches from [[side control]]; in rear position, she often secures a [[back mount]] and attacks with head strikes.<ref name=yahoo>{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Iole |title=Ronda Rousey delivers thrilling comeback win in UFC debut, submitting Liz Carmouche |work=Yahoo |date=February 24, 2013 |accessdate=October 12, 2014 |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/mma--ronda-rousey-delivers-thrilling-comeback-win-in-ufc-debut--submitting-liz-carmouche-in-the-first-round-053129935.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Karim |last=Zidan |title=UFC 175 results recap: Ronda Rousey vs. Alexis Davis |publisher=Bloody Elbow |date=July 7, 2014 |accessdate=October 12, 2014 |url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2014/7/7/5875553/ufc-175-results-recap-ronda-rousey-vs-alexis-davis-mma-news}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Strikeforce: Tate vs. Rousey' results: Ronda Rousey armbars Miesha Tate, wins title |work=mmajunkie |date=March 4, 2012 |accessdate=October 12, 2014 |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2012/03/strikeforce-tate-vs-rousey-results-ronda-rousey-armbars-miesha-tate-wins-title}}</ref> Rousey is right-handed, but is a left-handed judoka fighting in an orthodox stance as a striker.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6NsHtXReVUY |title=BJJ Scout: Ronda Rousey Takedown Study \u2013 Judo in MMA (Redux) |date=February 23, 2015 |publisher=BJJ Scout/YouTube}}</ref>\n\nRousey's favorite MMA fighter is [[Fedor Emelianenko]], whose fighting style she works to emulate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmaweekly.com/ufc-champ-ronda-rousey-tries-to-emulate-fedor-emelianenko-when-she-fights |title=UFC CHAMP RONDA ROUSEY TRIES TO EMULATE FEDOR EMELIANENKO WHEN SHE FIGHTS |publisher=MMA Weekly |date=June 26, 2015 |accessdate=December 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRousey is well known for her skill in grappling and is particularly noted for her string of victories by [[armbar]]. Against accomplished strikers, such as Julia Budd and Sarah Kaufman, Rousey has typically brought the fight down and sought a quick submission.<ref name=sweep /><ref>{{cite news |first=Brent |last=Jones |title=Another fight, another arm for Ronda Rousey |work=USA Today |date=November 19, 2011 |accessdate=October 12, 2014 |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/mma/post/2011-11-19/another-fight-another-arm-for-rousey/568992/1}}</ref> Only powerful grapplers, such as Miesha Tate and Liz Carmouche, have been competitive with Rousey on the ground.<ref name=hiptoss /><ref name=yahoo />\n\nDuring early fights in her MMA career, Rousey mainly used striking to set up judo. She became a more proficient striker following her UFC debut, leading to her first wins by way of stoppage. While standing, Rousey normally uses [[jab]]s, [[Knee (strike)|knees]], and [[Overhand (boxing)|overhand rights]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Matt |last=Erickson |title=UFC 170: Ronda Rousey stops Sara McMann in 66 seconds |work=USA Today |date=February 23, 2014 |accessdate=October 12, 2014 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ufc/2014/02/23/ronda-rousey-beats-sara-mcmann-first-round-tko-ufc-170/5748589/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Brett |last=Okamoto |title=Rousey needs seconds to defend belt |work=espn.com |date=July 5, 2014 |accessdate=October 12, 2014 |url=http://espn.go.com/mma/story/_/id/11179650/ronda-rousey-stops-alexis-davis-defends-title}}</ref> She seldom stood side on with a set boxing stance, but would square up to the opponent, while still generating strong striking power, especially when near the fence, or clinching opponents with the left hand to close the distance.<ref>{{cite av media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tFDSPrT2Axo |title=UFC 193: Unibet presents Inside the Octagon \u2013 Rousey vs. Holm |date=November 10, 2015 |publisher= |via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nWhile discussing her signature armbar in an interview, Rousey noted that her judoka mother jumped on her every morning to wake her up with armbars.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fightland.vice.com/blog/ronda-rousey-gets-it-from-her-mother |title=Ronda Rousey Gets It From Her Mother |publisher=fightland.vice.com |date=February 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRousey is notable for introducing [[Trash-talk|trash talking]] to women's MMA. In many interviews Rousey has used harsh language and openly downplayed the abilities of her opponents, which she explains as a way to generate more publicity for the sport.<ref>{{cite web |last=Marocco |first=Steven |title=Unapologetic Rousey hopes trashtalk can elevate Strikeforce's females |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2012/01/unapologetic-rousey-hopes-trashtalk-can-elevate-strikeforces-females |publisher=MMA Junkie |accessdate=February 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214175909/http://mmajunkie.com/2012/01/unapologetic-rousey-hopes-trashtalk-can-elevate-strikeforces-females/ |archivedate=February 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Wayne |first=Mark |title=Ronda Rousey: Trash Talk Isn't Personal, Is Good For The Sport |url=http://www.fightline.com/fl/news/2012/0122/547120/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130123010824/http://www.fightline.com/fl/news/2012/0122/547120/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 23, 2013 |website=Fightline |accessdate=February 11, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Background===\nRousey is a [[professional wrestling]] fan. She, [[Shayna Baszler]], [[Jessamyn Duke]] and Marina Shafir have dubbed themselves \"The Four Horsewomen,\" a play on [[The Four Horsemen (professional wrestling)|The Four Horsemen]] professional wrestling stable, with the blessing of members [[Ric Flair]] and [[Arn Anderson]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2014/8/28/6080813/shayna-baszler-on-four-horswomen-haters-ric-flair-and-arn-anderson |title=Shayna Baszler on 'Four Horsewomen' Haters: Ric Flair and Arn Anderson gave their blessing |author=Ariel Helwani |work=MMA Fighting |accessdate=July 12, 2015|date=August 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===WWE===\n====Sporadic appearances (2014\u20132017)====\n[[File:Rock Rousey WM31.jpg|thumb|right|Rousey with [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] at [[WrestleMania 31]]]]\nThe Four Horsewomen were acknowledged on camera and commentary as such, in the front row at [[WWE]]'s [[SummerSlam (2014)|SummerSlam]] event in August 2014. The group also went backstage during the event, meeting [[Paul Heyman]], among others.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-News-Ronda-Rousey-and-the-Four-Horsewomen-backstage-at-SummerSlam-38514 |title=WWE News: Ronda Rousey and the Four Horsewomen backstage at SummerSlam |publisher= |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> Rousey was interviewed by WWE.com that night; when asked if she, like [[Brock Lesnar]], would cross over to wrestling, she replied \"You never know.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2014/wwe-ronda-rousey-interview-26577503 |title=Exclusive interview: Ronda Rousey spotted backstage at SummerSlam 2014 |work=WWE |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt [[WrestleMania 31]] in March 2015, the Four Horsewomen were seated in the front row. During an in-ring argument between [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] and [[The Authority (professional wrestling)|The Authority]] ([[Stephanie McMahon]] and [[Triple H]]), McMahon slapped the Rock and ordered him to leave \"her ring\". She taunted him, saying he would not hit a woman. He left, paused and walked over to Rousey to a loud ovation. He then helped her into the ring and said that she would be happy to hit McMahon for him. After a staredown, The Rock attacked Triple H. When he stumbled toward Rousey, she tossed him out of the ring. McMahon tried to slap her, was blocked and Rousey grabbed her arm, teasing an armbar, before throwing her out of the ring. Rousey and the Rock celebrated in the ring, while the Authority retreated with the implication of revenge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/rock-ronda-rousey-wrestlemania-in-the-news-27249603 |title=Ronda Rousey's takedown of The Authority makes headlines |work=WWE |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712102537/http://www.wwe.com/inside/rock-ronda-rousey-wrestlemania-in-the-news-27249603 |archivedate=July 12, 2015  }}</ref> The segment was replayed and discussed throughout the next night's ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' with the commentators hyping a [[Twitter|tweet]] Rousey made earlier that day, in which she implied a return to WWE with \"We're just gettin' started...\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/31/ronda-rousey-twitter-reaction-wrestlemania-moment |title=Ronda Rousey on her WrestleMania 31 moment: 'We're just gettin' started' |website=[[WWE]] |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 13, 14, and September 12, 2017, the Horsewomen appeared in the audience of the [[Mae Young Classic (2017)|Mae Young Classic]] to support their compatriot [[Shayna Baszler]], who was making her WWE debut in the tournament. Additionally during the event, all four Horsewomen had a face-off with [[Charlotte Flair]], [[Becky Lynch]], and [[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]], who, in WWE together with [[Sasha Banks]], are also known as the Four Horsewomen, hinting at a possible future [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] between the two groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2017/7/18/15992178/ronda-rousey-wwe-mae-young-classic-baszler-four-horsewomen-ufc-mma-news |title=Ronda Rousey attends WWE shows, gets involved in angle with friend Shayna Baszler |work=[[SB Nation]] | date=July 18, 2017|accessdate=September 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2017/9/4/16253326/wwe-ufc-ronda-rousey-four-horsewomen-mae-young-classic-mma-wrestling-news |title=WWE continues to build angle for Ronda Rousey's Four Horsewomen|work=[[SB Nation]] | date=September 4, 2017|accessdate=September 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2017/9/13/16300570/ronda-rousey-wwe-angle-baszler-mae-young-classic-horsewomen-ufc-mma-wrestling-news |title=Ronda Rousey angle doesn't happen at WWE's Mae Young Classic after all |work=[[SB Nation]] | date=September 13, 2017|accessdate=September 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in 2017 that Rousey had signed with the WWE on a full-time basis and had been training at the WWE Performance Center in Orlando.\n\n====Raw Women's Champion (2018\u20132019)====\n[[File:Rousey&Angle WM34 crop.jpg|thumb|Rousey at [[WrestleMania 34]] with [[Kurt Angle]]]]\nRousey made a surprise appearance at [[Royal Rumble (2018)|Royal Rumble]] on January 28, 2018, confronting [[WWE Raw Women's Championship|Raw Women's Champion]] [[Alexa Bliss]], [[WWE SmackDown Women's Championship|SmackDown Women's Champion]] [[Charlotte Flair]], and [[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]], who had just won the inaugural women's [[Royal Rumble#Match|Royal Rumble match]]. [[ESPN]] immediately revealed during the segment that she had signed a full\u2013time contract with WWE.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2018/article/2018-first-ever-womens-royal-rumble-statistics-entrants-eliminations|title=Full first-ever Women's Royal Rumble Match statistics: entrants, eliminations, times and more|publisher=WWE|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115167&p=4|title=FULL ROYAL RUMBLE COVERAGE|last=Strode|first=Cory|date=January 28, 2018|accessdate=January 28, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> The jacket which Rousey wore during this appearance belonged to [[Roddy Piper|\"Rowdy\" Roddy Piper]], given to her by his son.<ref>{{Cite url|url=http://www.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/22253621/ronda-rousey-ready-next-career-wwe|title=A fresh start for Ronda Rousey|last=Shelborne|first=Ramona|date=January 29, 2018|publisher=ESPN|access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> On February 25 at the [[Elimination Chamber (2018)|Elimination Chamber]] pay\u2013per\u2013view, Rousey was involved in an in\u2013ring altercation with [[Triple H]] and [[Stephanie McMahon]], after which she signed her contract ([[Kayfabe (professional wrestling)|in storyline]]), thus making her a part of the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]] brand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/eliminationchamber/elimination-chamber-2018/ronda-rouseys-official-contract-signing-results|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|title=Ronda Rousey puts Triple H through a table during her official Raw Contract Signing!|publisher=|date=February 25, 2018|accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=115732&p=2|title=COMPLETE WWE ELIMINATION CHAMBER PPV COVERAGE INCLUDING RAW TALK COVERAGE|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=February 25, 2018|accessdate=February 25, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref>\n\nOn the March 5 episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'', it was announced that Rousey will make her in\u2013ring debut [[WrestleMania 34]], WWE's flagship event, in a [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Mixed tag team match|mixed tag team match]] pitting Rousey and [[Kurt Angle]] as her partner against Stephanie McMahon and Triple H.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/wwe/news/14203/11278184/wwe-raw-ronda-rouseys-wrestlemania-match-confirmed|first=Jefferson|last=Lake|title=WWE Raw: Ronda Rousey's WrestleMania match confirmed|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=March 6, 2018|accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pappolla|first1=Ryan|title=Kurt Angle & Ronda Rousey vs. Triple H & Stephanie McMahon|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/kurt-angle-ronda-rousey-vs-triple-h-stephanie-mcmahon|publisher=WWE|date=March 5, 2018|accessdate=March 5, 2018}}</ref> At the event, Rousey submitted McMahon with her trademark [[Armlock|armbar submission]] hold to secure the win for her team.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Kurt Angle & Ronda Rousey def. Triple H & Stephanie McMahon|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-34/kurt-angle-ronda-rousey-triple-h-stephanie-mcmahon-results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=April 8, 2018}}</ref> Her debut performance was widely praised by both fans and wrestling critics, with [[Dave Meltzer]] of the ''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer]]'' noting that she \"at no point looked out of her element, she was crisp in just about everything\", calling her performance \"one of the better pro wrestling debuts I've ever seen\".<ref name=MeltzerWrestleMania34>{{cite web|last1=Meltzer|first1=Dave|title=WWE WrestleMania 34 live results, news & recap|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/wwe-wrestlemania-34-live-results-news-recap-254991|website=f4wonline.com|accessdate=April 9, 2018|date=April 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=de Menezes|first1=Jack|title=WrestleMania 34 results: Ronda Rousey stuns Triple H, The Undertaker returns and Brock Lesnar beats Roman Reigns|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/wwe-mma-wrestling/wwe-wrestlemania-2018-results-watch-highlights-undertaker-returns-ronda-rousey-brock-lesnar-john-a8295336.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Keller|first1=Wade|title=Keller's WWE WrestleMania 34 report: Lesnar vs. Reigns, Styles vs. Nakamura, Charlotte vs. Asuka, Rousey's debut, Bryan's return, Battle Royals, more|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/04/08/kellers-wwe-wrestlemania-34-report-lesnar-vs-reigns-styles-vs-nakamura-charlotte-vs-asuka-rouseys-debut-bryans-return-battle-royals-more/|website=pwtorch.com|accessdate=April 9, 2018|date=April 8, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' noted the positive fan reaction, stating \"The match exceeded expectations, with fans firmly behind Rousey\" and \"[fans were] surprised [at her] high\u2013level coordination and quality of wrestling. Even those who were not agreed the match was entertaining.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Needelman|first1=Joshua|title=WWE WrestleMania 34: Ronda Rousey wins debut; Daniel Bryan returns; Brock Lesnar beats Roman Reigns in dud main event|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/sports/wp/2018/04/08/wwe-wrestlemania-34-live|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May, after she was challenged by then-champion [[Nia Jax]], it was announced that Rousey would get her first opportunity at the [[WWE Raw Women's Championship|Raw Women's Championship]] at the next pay\u2013per\u2013view, [[Money in the Bank (2018)|Money in the Bank]].<ref name=\"Raw05142018\">{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=WWE Raw Live TV Review: Seth Rollins vs. Kevin Owens for the Intercontinental Championship, Baron Corbin vs. Bobby Roode vs. No Way Jose in a Men's MITB qualifier, Alexa Bliss vs. Bayley vs. Mickie James in a Women's MITB qualifier|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/05/14/wwe-raw-live-tv-review-seth-rollins-vs-kevin-owens-for-the-intercontinental-championship-baron-corbin-vs-bobby-roode-vs-no-way-jose-in-a-mens-mitb-qualifier-alexa-bliss-vs-bayley-vs-mickie-j/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=May 14, 2018|date=May 14, 2018}}</ref> At the event, Rousey went on to win the match by [[Disqualification (professional wrestling)|disqualification]] after an interference by [[Alexa Bliss]], who attacked both Rousey and Jax and cashed in her [[Money in the Bank contract]] (which she won earlier that night) to win the title instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=118196&p=2|title=A GREAT SHOW, A SURPRISE TITLE CHANGE, A RETURN & MORE: COMPLETE WWE MONEY IN THE BANK COVERAGE|author=Mike Johnson|website=PWInsider|date=June 17, 2018|accessdate=June 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"MITB2018\">{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=Powell's WWE Money in the Bank live review: Two MITB ladder matches, AJ Styles vs. Shinsuke Nakamura in a Last Man Standing match for the WWE Championship, Nia Jax vs. Ronda Rousey for the Raw Women's Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/06/17/powells-wwe-money-in-the-bank-live-review-two-mitb-ladder-matches-aj-styles-vs-shinsuke-nakamura-in-a-last-man-standing-match-for-the-wwe-championship-nia-jax-vs-ronda-rousey-for-the-raw-women/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|accessdate=June 17, 2018|date=June 17, 2018}}</ref> For her first singles match and title opportunity, she was once again praised by fans and critics for her performance, with [[CNET]] stating \"For the first time, [WWE's] biggest mainstream star is a woman.\"<ref name=\"MITB2018CNET\">{{cite web|last1=van Boom|first1=Daniel|title=WWE's Ronda Rousey experiment continues to pay off|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/wwe-ronda-rousey-succeeds-money-in-the-bank/|work=[[CNET]]|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=June 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"MITB2018PhillyVoice\">{{cite web|title=WWE Money in the Bank: Ronda Rousey vies for a title, but Alexa Bliss walks away the winner|url=http://www.phillyvoice.com/wwe-money-bank-ronda-rousey-vies-title-alexa-bliss-walks-away-winner/|work=Philly Voice|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=June 21, 2018}}</ref> They believed that despite \"worry was that the match would expose Rousey's own inexperience, which would greatly damage her aura and star power\", she \"came across as a formidable, believable star wrestler. The match was good, but she was awesome\".<ref name=\"MITB2018CNET\"/> Throughout the next two months, Rousey would start her first [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] as part of WWE with Alexa Bliss over the title, which included a suspension (again in [[kayfabe]]) after Rousey attacked Bliss, [[Kurt Angle]] and multiple officials.<ref name=\"MITBSuspension\">{{cite web|title=Ronda Rousey suspended from Raw for 30 days|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-06-18/article/ronda-rousey-raw-suspension|work=[[WWE]]|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=June 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/2018-wwe-extreme-rules-results-recap-grades-new-champions-surprises-and-a-big-return/|title=2018 WWE Extreme Rules results, recap, grades: New champions, surprises and a big return|publisher=}}</ref> After honouring her suspension from in\u2013ring competition, Rousey received a Raw Women's Championship match by [[List of WWE Raw on-air personalities#Authority figures|Raw General Manager]] Kurt Angle against Bliss at [[SummerSlam (2018)|SummerSlam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/07/16/heydorns-wwe-raw-report-7-16-alt-perspective-coverage-of-the-live-show-including-extreme-rules-fallout-the-future-of-the-universal-championship-and-more/|title=HEYDORN'S WWE RAW REPORT 7/16: Alt Perspective coverage of the live show including Extreme Rules fallout, the future of the Universal Championship, and more -|date=July 16, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> At the event on August 19, Rousey [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#S|squashed]] Bliss to win the title, her first championship win in WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/2018-wwe-summerslam-results-recap-grades-four-major-title-changes-and-a-big-time-finish/|title=2018 WWE SummerSlam results, recap, grades: Four major title changes and a big-time finish|publisher=}}</ref> In a rematch between the two that took place a month later on September 16 at [[Hell in a Cell (2018)|Hell in a Cell]], Rousey once again submitted Bliss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/2018-wwe-hell-in-a-cell-results-recap-grades-brock-lesnars-surprise-return-big-title-change/|title=2018 WWE Hell in a Cell results, recap, grades: Brock Lesnar's surprise return, big title change|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThroughout her championship reign, Rousey went on to fend off title contenders such as [[Nikki Bella]] (in the [[main event]] of the first all women's pay\u2013per\u2013view [[WWE Evolution|Evolution]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=121007&p=2|title=WWE RAW REPORT: A THREE MAN TEAM IN TURMOIL, RONDA HAS SOME CHOICE WORDS FOR NIKKI, A NUMBER OF RETURNS, AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=October 15, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=121185&p=3|title=WWE RAW REPORT: THE FUTURE OF THE SHIELD, THE TAG AND UNIVERSAL TITLE TURMOIL, A BIG ANNOUNCEMENT FROM ROMAN REIGNS, AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=October 22, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=121345&p=4|title=NIKKI BELLA VS. RONDA ROUSEY, LAST WOMAN STANDING, NXT WOMEN'S TITLE & MORE WWE EVOLUTION PPV COVERAGE|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=October 28, 2018|accessdate=October 28, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> [[Mickie James]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=121897&p=2|title=WWE RAW REPORT: RONDA DEFENDS THE TITLE, BRAUN GETS HIS MATCHES, DEAN AND SETH, AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=November 19, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> Nia Jax,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=122047&p=2|title=WWE RAW REPORT: ROLLINS HAS AN OPEN CHALLENGE AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=November 26, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/122222/wwe-raw-report-another-qa-session-abuse-of-power-by-baron-drew-is-not-in-a-good-mood-but-he-gets-a-medal-and-more.html?p=1|title=WWE RAW REPORT: ANOTHER Q&A SESSION, ABUSE OF POWER BY BARON?, DREW IS NOT IN A GOOD MOOD . . . BUT HE GETS A MEDAL, AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=December 3, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> [[Natalya Neidhart|Natalya]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=122550&p=3|title=WWE RAW REPORT: DO YOU LIKE MCMAHONS?, BARON'S SWAN SONG?, A GAUNTLET, AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=December 17, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=122713&p=3|title=WWE RAW REPORT: ROUSEY VERSUS NATALYA, TAG TITLE MATCH, MANY SANTAS, PAUL HEYMAN, AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=December 24, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> and [[Sasha Banks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=123027&p=3|title=WWE RAW REPORT: PAYING TRIBUTE TO MEAN GENE, TAG TITLE MATCH, IC TITLE MATCH, NUMBER ONE CONTENDER FOR RONDA, AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=January 7, 2019|work=PWInsider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=123228&p=1|title=WWE RAW REPORT: BE CAREFUL WHOSE CAR YOU DESTROY, CHANGE TO MAIN EVENT, INFO ON WOMEN'S TAG TITLES, DEBUTS, AND AN IC TITLE MATCH|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=January 14, 2019|work=PWInsider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=123428&p=3|title=WWE RAW REPORT: MORE NAMES FOR THE RUMBLE, TAG TITLE MATCH, BALOR AND BROCK, AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=January 21, 2019|work=PWInsider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=123626&p=5|title=COMPLETE WWE ROYAL RUMBLE 2019 COVERAGE|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=January 27, 2019|work=PWInsider}}</ref> In November, Rousey was supposed to face [[Becky Lynch]] at the [[Survivor Series (2018)|Survivor Series]] pay\u2013per\u2013view in an interbrand champion vs. champion match, however, Lynch was legitimately injured during an [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#I|invasion angle]] just minutes after she attacked Rousey backstage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=121707&p=3|title=LIVE ONGOING WWE RAW REPORT: NO OVERRUN FOR TIME. . . BUT SOMEONE GOT OVERRUN, THE TEAMS FOR SURVIVOR SERIES ARE COMPLETE, SETH STILL WANTS ANSWERS FROM DEAN, AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=November 12, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> At the event, Rousey faced [[Charlotte Flair]] instead, and won via disqualification after Flair attacked her with a kendo stick and steel chairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/121867/nakamura-vs-rollins-live-ongoing-wwe-survivor-series-2018-ppv-coverage.html?p=1|title=BROCK LESNAR VS. DANIEL BRYAN, CHARLOTTE FLAIR VS. RONDA ROUSEY, RAW VS. SMACKDOWN & MORE: COMPLETE WWE SURVIVOR SERIES 2018 PPV COVERAGE|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=November 18, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> A month later, on December 16, at [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2018)|TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs]], Rousey gained revenge against both Flair and Lynch as she pushed them off a ladder during their match, also helping [[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]] win the [[WWE SmackDown Women's Championship|SmackDown Women's Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=122523&p=4|title=THE MAN VS. THE QUEEN VS. THE EMPRESS, BRYAN VS STYLES, DEAN VS. SETH & MORE: COMPLETE WWE TLC PPV COVERAGE|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=December 16, 2018|work=PWInsider}}</ref> Shortly after she retained her title against [[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]], on the January 28, 2019, episode of ''Raw'', Rousey continued her feud with Becky Lynch (who had won the [[Royal Rumble match]]) after the latter chose to challenge her in a title match at [[WrestleMania 35]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/123658/first-wrestlemania-35-main-event-is-official.html?p=1|title=FIRST WRESTLEMANIA 35 MAIN EVENT IS OFFICIAL|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=January 28, 2019|work=PWInsider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=123656&p=3|title=WWE RAW REPORT: ONE RUMBLE WINNER MAKES THEIR CHOICE, TWO TEAMS ARE SET FOR THE WOMEN'S TAG TITLES, DANIEL BRYAN, THE MAN, AND MORE|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=January 28, 2019|work=PWInsider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/124074/vince-mcmahon-drops-a-nuclear-bomb-on-wrestlemania-main-event.html?p=1|title=VINCE MCMAHON DROPS A NUCLEAR BOMB ON WRESTLEMANIA MAIN EVENT|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=February 11, 2019|work=PWInsider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=124067&p=3|title=WWE RAW REPORT: A TAG TITLE MATCH, WHO IS FIRST IN THE CHAMBER MATCH?, AN INTERESTING END TO THE SHOW, AND MORE|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=February 11, 2019|work=PWInsider}}</ref> On the February 11 episode of ''Raw'', [[Vince McMahon]] suspended Lynch for 60 days in storyline and announced [[Charlotte Flair]] replaced Lynch as Rousey's WrestleMania opponent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2019/02/11/wwe-raw-results-news-and-notes-after-vince-mcmahon-replaces-becky-lynch-with-charlotte-flair/|title=WWE Raw Results: News And Notes After Vince McMahon Replaces Becky Lynch With Charlotte Flair|last=Konuwa|first=Alfred|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}</ref> On the March 4 episode of ''Raw'', Rousey turned [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] for the first time in her career when she cut a promo on fans and attacked both Flair and Lynch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/03/04/3-4-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-batista-follow-up-rouseys-championship-status-shield-reunion-che-jost-from-snl-weekend-update-guest-host/|title=3/4 WWE Raw Results: Keller's report on Batista follow-up, Rousey's championship status, Shield reunion, Che & Jost from SNL Weekend Update guest host|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Wade|last=Keller|authorlink=Wade Keller|date=March 4, 2019|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> At [[Fastlane (2019)|Fastlane]], Lynch faced Flair in a match where if Lynch won, she would be inserted back into the Raw Women's Championship match at WrestleMania. Rousey attacked Lynch during the match, giving Lynch the disqualification victory and thus the WrestleMania triple-threat match between Rousey, Flair and Lynch was made official. On March 25, WWE announced Rousey's title defense against Lynch and Flair would be the main event of WrestleMania 35, making it the first women's match to close WrestleMania.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/article/wrestlemania-to-feature-first-ever-womens-main-event|title=WrestleMania to feature first-ever women's main event|website=WWE|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref> At the event, in what was changed to a [[Professional wrestling match types#Winner takes all match|Winner takes all]] for Rousey's Raw and Flair's SmackDown Women's Championships, Lynch controversially pinned Rousey to win both titles. The commentary and production team commented that Rousey was in the ring saying her shoulders were not down for the full three-count and showed a replay of the ending pin-pointing this fact. Many fans and media were left wondering if this was a legitimate botched finish or if it was booked to end that way.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ftw/2019/04/08/wrestlemania-35-wwe-main-event-ending/39315187/|title=WWE fans weren't impressed with 'botched' ending to historic main event at WrestleMania 35|website=USA TODAY|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/brianmazique/2019/04/08/wwe-wrestlemania-35-results-several-reports-indicate-becky-lynch-ronda-rousey-ending-was-botched/|title=WWE WrestleMania 35 Results: Several Reports Indicate Becky Lynch-Ronda Rousey Ending Was Botched|first=Brian|last=Mazique|website=Forbes|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref> Nonetheless, this gave Rousey her first loss in WWE and ended her championship reign at 231 days, making her the now-second-longest-reigning Raw Women's Champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/article/becky-lynch-becomes-longest-reigning-raw-womens-champion|title=Becky Lynch becomes longest-reigning Raw Women's Champion|website=WWE.com|date=November 26, 2019|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other work==\nRousey appeared nude on the cover of ''ESPN The Magazine''{{'}}s 2012 ''[[Body Issue]]'' and in a pictorial therein.<ref>{{cite web |title=Body Issue 2012: Ronda Rousey \u2013 ESPN Video \u2013 ESPN |url=http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=8147390 |accessdate=July 30, 2012|date = July 29, 2012}}</ref> \nIn May 2013, Rousey was ranked 29 on the ''[[Maxim Hot 100]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Noble|first=McKinley|date=May 6, 2013|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1630981-ufc-champ-ronda-rousey-makes-nude-maxim-debut-at-no-29-in-2013-maxim-hot-100|title=UFC Champ Ronda Rousey Makes Racy Debut at No. 29 in 2013 Maxim Hot 100|website=Bleacher Report}}</ref> She also appeared on the cover and in a pictorial of the September 2013 issue.\n \n[[File:Cannes 2014 4 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Rousey (center, middle row) alongside other actors at the [[2014 Cannes Film Festival]]]] \nRousey co-starred in ''[[The Expendables 3]]'' (2014), marking her first role in a major motion picture.<ref name=MMAInsider /> In 2015, she appeared in the film ''[[Furious 7]]'', and played herself in the film ''[[Entourage (film)|Entourage]]''.<ref name=FoxNewsLatino /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmanuts.com/news/ronda-rousey-scores-two-leading-roles-hollywood/ |title=Ronda Rousey Scores Two Leading Roles in Hollywood |publisher=mmanuts.com |author=Dave Walsh |date=February 7, 2014 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Rousey became the first woman featured on the cover of ''Australian Men's Fitness'', appearing on their November edition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2015/10/05/ronda-rousey-magazine-cover-sparks-controversy/ |title=Ronda Rousey magazine cover sparks controversy |publisher=Fox News |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Rousey became the first female athlete to guest host ESPN's ''[[SportsCenter]]''.<ref>{{cite web |author=Matt Jones |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2577111-ronda-rousey-teaches-armbar-on-espns-sportscenter-talks-kobe-bryant-and-more |title=Ronda Rousey Teaches Armbar on ESPN's SportsCenter, Talks Kobe Bryant and More |website=Bleacher Report |accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRousey was on the cover of the January 2016 issue for [[The Ring (magazine)|''The Ring'' magazine]]. She became the first mixed martial artist to ever appear on the cover of the boxing magazine and the second woman as well, after [[Cathy Davis]] in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/ufc/story/ufc-ronda-rousey-becomes-first-mma-fighter-to-land-ring-magazine-cover-boxing-102615 |title=Rousey becomes first MMA fighter to land Ring Magazine cover |publisher=[[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] |date=October 26, 2015 |accessdate=December 31, 2015}}</ref> In February 2016 she appeared in [[Body painting|body paint]] as one of three cover athletes on the cover of the ''[[Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Issue]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2016/02/14/ronda-rousey-to-be-featured-on-one-of-three-sports-illustrated-swimsuit-issue-covers/?tid=a_inl |title=Ronda Rousey to be featured on one of three Sports Illustrated swimsuit issue covers |first=Jacob |last=Emert |date=February 14, 2016 |accessdate=February 14, 2016 |work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nRousey has had a range of commercial partnerships, including [[mobile network operator]] [[MetroPCS]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2013/4/22/4252394/video-watch-ronda-rousey-commercial-metro-pcs-ufc-on-fox-7-mma/ |title=Video: Watch Ronda Rousey commercial for MetroPCS from UFC on Fox 7 Broadcast |publisher=MMAmania.com |date=April 11, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2013}}</ref> [[insurance]] agency [[Insureon]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmainsider.net/4487/exclusive-new-ronda-rousey-insureon-commercial/ |title=Exclusive \u2013 Full Ronda Rousey Insureon Commercial (Update) |publisher=MMAinsider.net |date=June 11, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617180415/http://mmainsider.net/4487/exclusive-new-ronda-rousey-insureon-commercial |archive-date=June 17, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> [[Reebok]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/12/reebok-announces-partnership-with-ufc-champs-jon-jones-and-ronda-rousey |title=Reebok announces partnership with UFC champs Jon Jones and Ronda Rousey |publisher=mmajunkie.com |author=Staff |date=December 16, 2014 |accessdate=January 4, 2015}}</ref> and Carl's Jr.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dailycommercials.com/carls-jr-ronda-rousey-commercial/ |title=Carl's Jr. : Ronda Rousey commercial |publisher=Daily Commercials |date= |accessdate=September 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRousey hosted the January 23, 2016, episode of the late night variety show ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', with musical guest [[Selena Gomez]].<ref>Bacle, Ariana (January 5, 2016). [http://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/05/ronda-rousey-saturday-night-live-host-selena-gomez \"Ronda Rousey to host Saturday Night Live\"]. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''.</ref><ref>Vasquez, Miguel (January 8, 2016). [http://www.christianpost.com/news/ufc-news-2016-ronda-rousey-hosting-saturday-night-live-ufc-gennady-golovkin-both-book-madison-square-garden-for-april-23rd-154304/ \"UFC News 2016: Ronda Rousey Hosting Saturday Night Live; UFC, Gennady Golovkin Both Book Madison Square Garden For April 23rd\"]. ''[[The Christian Post]]''.</ref>\n\nRousey appeared in the Season 2, Episode 20 episode of ''[[Blindspot (TV series)|Blindspot]]'' playing the role of Devon Penberthy, a prison inmate serving time for transporting weapons across state lines.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jask Rasthborn |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/ronda-rousey-blindspot-series-ufc-10246247 |title=Ronda Rousey stars in hit tv show Blindspot and hints UFC career is over following brutal defeats |publisher=Mirror |date=April 18, 2017 |accessdate=May 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA number of starring film roles have been developed for Rousey, including an adaptation of her autobiography ''My Fight / Your Fight'' at Paramount,<ref name=\"vra\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/ronda-rousey-biopic-autobiography-my-fight-your-fight-1201553460/|title=Ronda Rousey to Star in Film Based on Her Autobiography (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=August 3, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> ''The Athena Project'' at [[Warner Bros.]],<ref name=\"vra\"/> the [[Peter Berg]]-directed action film ''[[Mile 22]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/lauren-cohan-mark-walhberg-mile-22-1202609227/|title='Walking Dead' Star Lauren Cohan Joins Mark Walhberg in 'Mile 22'|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=November 7, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Rousey was scheduled to star in a remake of the 1989 [[Patrick Swayze]] action drama ''[[Road House (1989 film)|Road House]]''. ''Road House'' would have marked her biggest acting job to date. According to ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Rousey reached out to Swayze's widow, [[Lisa Niemi]], to ask for her blessing, which Niemi gave.<ref name=Variety>Kroll, Justin (September 9, 2015). [https://variety.com/2015/film/news/ronda-rousey-road-house-reboot-1201567956/ \"Ronda Rousey to Star in 'Road House' Reboot\"]. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''.</ref> However, the ''Road House'' project was cancelled in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/terrible-amazing-canceled-remakes-movies/|title=9 Canceled Remakes That Would've Been Terrible (And 6 That Would've Been Amazing)|date=December 15, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 9, 2018, Rousey was confirmed as one of the two pre-order bonus characters for the video game ''[[WWE 2K19]]'' (the other being wrestling veteran [[Rey Mysterio]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagesideseats.com/wwe/2018/7/9/17551752/wwe-2k19-releases-first-trailer-ronda-rousey-raw|title=WWE 2K19 releases first trailer for Ronda Rousey & it's perfect|publisher=|date=July 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/wwe-2k19-features-rey-mysterio-if-you-pre-order/1100-6460032/|title=WWE 2K19 Features Rey Mysterio, If You Pre-Order|first=Patrick|last=Faller|date=July 2, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> She previously appeared in ''[[EA Sports UFC]]'', ''[[EA Sports UFC 2]]'' and ''[[EA Sports UFC 3]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.giantbomb.com/ronda-rousey/3005-28314/|title=Ronda Rousey (Character)|website=Giant Bomb|accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2019, it was confirmed that Rousey would be voicing [[Sonya Blade]] in the video game ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/01/17/ronda-rousey-confirmed-as-sonya-blade-in-mortal-kombat-11|title=Ronda Rousey Confirmed as Sonya Blade in Mortal Kombat 11 - IGN|accessdate=January 2, 2020|via=www.ign.com}}</ref>\n\nOn August 18, 2019, it was revealed that Rousey is appearing as a recurring character Lena Bosko in the third season of FOX's ''[[9-1-1 (TV series)|9-1-1]]'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/8/15/20807614/ronda-rousey-lands-recurring-role-in-foxs-drama-series-9-1-1-for-season-3|title=Ronda Rousey lands recurring role in FOX's drama series '9-1-1' for season 3 |author=Damon Martin|publisher=mmafighting.com|date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> During her first day of shooting, she injured two fingers after her left hand was jammed in a boat door. The tip of her ring finger was fractured while her middle finger was broken with the tendon nearly severed. Rousey was rushed to the hospital, where her middle finger was mended with a metal plate and screws.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/08/20/ronda-rousey-broken-finger-911-show/ |title=Ronda Rousey Says Boat Door Nearly Severed Finger Shooting '911' |website=[[TMZ]] |date=August 20, 2019 |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn February 18, 2020 Rousey announced her first stream on Facebook Gaming and donated all stream profits to charity. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/sports/ronda-rousey-facebook-gaming-stream|title=Ronda Rousey lands Facebook Gaming streaming deal|last=Barrabi|first=Thomas|date=February 14, 2020|website=FOXBusiness|language=en-US|access-date=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Rousey plane.jpg|thumb|Rousey posing with a [[United States Air Force Thunderbirds]] plane with her name on it]]\nAs of 2017, Rousey lives in [[Venice, California]].<ref>Hale, Andreas (January 10, 2017). [https://sports.yahoo.com/news/ronda-rousey-photographed-for-the-first-time-after-discovering-her-venice-beach-home-had-been-vandalized-233628648.html \"Vandalism at Ronda Rousey's home forces her out of hiding\"]. [[Yahoo! Sports]].</ref>\n\nRousey became a [[vegan]] after Beijing 2008,<ref name=\"FIRST\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/13/AR2008081303517.html |title=Rousey Is 1st U.S. Woman to Earn A Medal in Judo |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=August 13, 2008 |first=Dan |last=Steinberg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmaplayground.com/forums/topic49792-1.html |title=MMAPlayground Interview Series - Vol. 13 (\"Rowdy\" Ronda Rousey) |website=MMAPlayground.com |date=November 8, 2011}}</ref> but in 2012 described her diet as \"kind of a mix between a [[Paleo diet|Paleo]] and a Warrior diet\", trying to eat everything [[Organic food|organic]].<ref>Curreri, Frank (August 16, 2012). [http://www.ufc.com/news/The-Ronda-Rousey-Diet?id= \"The Ronda Rousey Diet\"]. UFC.</ref>\n\nRousey has discussed how she struggled with her body image in the past. She explained, \"When I was in school, martial arts made you a dork, and I became self-conscious that I was too masculine. I was a 16-year-old girl with [[ringworm]] and [[cauliflower ears]]. People made fun of my arms and called me 'Miss Man'. It wasn't until I got older that I realized: these people are idiots. I'm fabulous.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Weaver, Hilary |title=6 Feminist Quotes From Ronda Rousey That Prove She's More Than Just A Trash Talker |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/101566-6-feminist-quotes-from-ronda-rousey-that-prove-shes-more-than-just-a-trash-talker |magazine=Bustle |date=August 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRousey is an avid fan of ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'' and ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]''. Her favorite Pok\u00e9mon is [[Mew (Pok\u00e9mon)|Mew]] and she had a childhood crush on [[Vegeta]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/ronda-rousey-dishes-on-pokemon-and-dragon-ball-z-once-m-1723264525 |title=Ronda Rousey Dishes On Pok\u00e9mon and Dragon Ball Z Once More |publisher=[[Kotaku]] |date=August 10, 2015 |accessdate=December 31, 2015}}</ref> [[Christopher Sabat]], the English voice actor of Vegeta, jokingly replied in an interview, \"She has seen my power level for what it is\u2026 She also scares me.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nerdreactor.com/2015/08/04/vegeta-responds-ronda-rouseys/ |title=Vegeta responds to UFC Champ Ronda Rousey's crush on him |publisher=Nerd Reactor |date=August 4, 2015 |accessdate=December 31, 2015}}</ref> She also plays ''[[World of Warcraft]]'', primarily as a [[Races and factions of Warcraft#Night elves|night elf]] hunter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uproxx.com/sports/watch-ronda-rousey-nerd-out-on-world-of-warcraft-ahead-of-her-ufc-184-fight/ |title=Watch Ronda Rousey Nerd Out On World Of Warcraft Ahead Of Her UFC 184 Fight |publisher=[[Uproxx]] |date=February 24, 2015 |accessdate=December 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, she raised money by auctioning signed T-shirts for the [[Black Jaguar-White Tiger Foundation]], whose goal is to save big cats from circuses and zoos and provide them with the best lifestyle.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://armbarnation.com/2015/02/support-black-jaguar-white-tiger-foundation/ |title=Support Black Jaguar White Tiger Foundation |publisher=ArmbarNation.com |date=February 24, 2015 |accessdate=March 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Rousey visited [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]] for the 100th anniversary of the [[Armenian Genocide]]. While in Yerevan, she [[List of visitors to Tsitsernakaberd|visited]] the [[Tsitsernakaberd]] Armenian Genocide memorial.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronda Rousey visits Armenian Genocide Memorial |url=http://sport.news.am/eng/news/55991/ronda-rousey-visits-armenian-genocide-memorial-photos.html |agency=NEWS.am |date=April 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRousey endorsed [[Bernie Sanders]]' [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|presidential campaign]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election]].<ref name='washpost'>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/11/11/as-some-conservatives-cheer-ronda-rouseys-take-on-feminism-she-backs-bernie-sanders |title=As some conservatives cheer Ronda Rousey's antifeminism, she backs Bernie Sanders |author=Amber Phillips |date=November 11, 2015 |work=Washington Post}}</ref><ref name='maxim'>Wilson, Chris (November 10, 2015). [http://www.maxim.com/entertainment/sports/article/ronda-rousey-bernie-sanders-president-2015-11 \"EXCLUSIVE: You'll Never Guess Who Ronda Rousey Is Backing for President\"]. ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]''.</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, in an interview with [[Ellen DeGeneres]] Rousey admitted that suicidal thoughts went through her mind in the aftermath of her knockout loss to [[Holly Holm]] in November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mma/story/_/id/14785901/ronda-rousey-says-considered-suicide-loss-holly-holm|title=Ronda Rousey says she considered suicide after loss to Holly Holm|work=ESPN.com|date=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Relationships===\nRousey once dated fellow UFC fighter [[Brendan Schaub]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Holland, Jesse |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2015/8/10/9126189/ufc-brendan-schaub-im-too-much-man-for-ronda-rousey-mma |title=Brendan Schaub: I'm too much of a man for Ronda Rousey |publisher=MMAmania |date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> In August 2015, Rousey was rumored to be in a relationship with UFC fighter [[Travis Browne]], who knocked out Schaub in a bout the previous year, after a picture of the two together appeared on [[Twitter]] and Browne's estranged wife Jenna Renee Webb accused the two of seeing one another. Browne was at the time still married and under investigation by the UFC after Webb publicly accused him of domestic violence back in July.<ref>{{cite web |author=Simon, Zane |url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2015/8/25/9208063/ronda-rousey-dating-travis-browne-domestic-violence-allegations-wife-affair-ufc-news |title=Wife: Ronda Rousey dating hubby while UFC investigates him for domestic violence |publisher=Bloody Elbow |date=August 25, 2015}}</ref> Browne confirmed he and Rousey were together in October 2015.<ref>{{cite web |author=Rondina, Steven |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2578449-ronda-rousey-has-a-new-boyfriend-in-ufc-heavyweight-travis-browne |title=Ronda Rousey Has a New Boyfriend in the Form of UFC Heavyweight Travis Browne |website=Bleacher Report |date=October 12, 2015}}</ref> The next day, Rousey revealed that she was dating Browne.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronda Rousey releases statement about relationship with Travis Browne |url=http://www.foxsports.com/ufc/story/ufc-ronda-rousey-releases-statement-about-relationship-with-travis-browne-101315 |website=Fox Sports |accessdate=October 14, 2015 |publisher=[[Fox Sports]]|date=October 13, 2015 }}</ref>\nRousey and Browne got engaged on April 20, 2017, in [[New Zealand]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronda Rousey Engaged to Boyfriend Travis Browne \u2014 Find Out the Romantic Proposal Story|first=Sierra|last=Marquina|website=USWeekly.com|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/ronda-rousey-engaged-to-boyfriend-travis-browne-w478020|date=April 20, 2017}}</ref> and married on August 28, 2017 in Browne's home state of Hawaii.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronda Rousey Is Married! MMA Star Weds Travis Browne in Hawaii as Groom Gushes She's 'Perfect in Every Way'|first=Dave|last=Quinn|website=People|url=http://people.com/sports/ronda-rousey-travis-browne-married/}}</ref>\n\nIn her autobiography, ''My Fight, Your Fight'', Rousey wrote of an incident with an former boyfriend she dubbed \"Snappers McCreepy\" after she discovered that he had taken nude photos of her without her consent or knowledge, two weeks before her first fight with Miesha Tate. When a seething Rousey met him, she \"slapped him across the face so hard [her] hand hurt.\" According to Rousey, he then refused to let her leave as he was trying to explain, so she attacked his face with two punches, one more slap, one knee, then \"tossed him aside on the kitchen floor.\" She went to her car and he followed, grabbing the steering wheel, so she \"dragged him out onto the sidewalk, and left him writhing there\". Rousey deleted the photos and erased his hard drive, however fear that the pictures may still be out there influenced her to pose for [[ESPN The Magazine|''ESPN'' magazine]]'s ''[[Body Issue]]'' so that nude pictures of her would be seen on her own terms.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Rousey, Ronda |author2=Ortiz, Maria Burns |title=My Fight, Your Fight |pages=463\u2013465 |date=May 12, 2015 |publisher=[[Regan Arts]]}}</ref><ref name=\"yahoo1\">{{cite news |last=Adelson |first=Eric |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/ronda-rousey--admits-beating-up-her-ex--so-should-we-be-outraged-201418914.html |title=Ronda Rousey admitted to beating up her ex, so should we be outraged? |work=[[Yahoo Sports]] |date=October 7, 2015 |accessdate=November 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2015/10/13/9520315/ufc-travis-browne-ronda-rousey-relationship-rousey-violent-altercation-ex-boyfriend?_ga=1.132469006.1070297379.1440197599 |title=Ronda Rousey detailed violent altercation with ex-boyfriend in autobiography |publisher=Bloodyelbow.com |date=October 13, 2015 |accessdate=October 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Jan Omega |url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2491202/ronda-rousey-hypocrisy-argument-did-rowdy-commit-domestic-abuse-to-ex-boyfriend-after-finding-nude-pictures-of-herself/ |title=Ronda Rousey Hypocrisy Argument: Did 'Rowdy' Commit Domestic Abuse To Ex-Boyfriend After Finding Nude Pictures Of Herself? |publisher=Inquisitr.com |date= |accessdate=November 11, 2015}}</ref> Rousey faced some criticism that she had committed domestic abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2015/11/12/ronda-rousey-domestic-violence-autobiography/75652260/|title=Armour: Ronda Rousey shouldn't be getting a pass on domestic violence|last=ByNancyArmour|website=USA TODAY|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Honoo-no Taiiku-kai TV]]''\n| Herself\n| TV show\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Expendables 3]]''\n| Luna\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Furious 7]]''\n| [[List of The Fast and the Furious characters#Kara|Kara]]\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Entourage (film)|Entourage]]''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Drunk History]]''\n| [[Gallus Mag]]\n| Episode: \"Scoundrels\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Blindspot (TV series)|Blindspot]]''\n| Devon Penberthy\n| Episode: \"In Words, Drown I\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Mile 22]]''\n| Sam Snow\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[9-1-1 (TV series)|9-1-1]]\n| Lena Bosko\n| Recurring role (season 3)\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Total Divas]]\n| Herself\n| Guest (season 8) <br> Main (season 9)\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Charlie's Angels (2019 film)|Charlie's Angels]]''\n| Fight Instructor\n| Cameo appearance\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2014 \n| ''[[EA Sports UFC]]'' \n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 2016 \n| ''[[EA Sports UFC 2]]'' \n| Herself\n| Cover athlete \n|-\n| 2018 \n| ''[[EA Sports UFC 3]]'' \n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[WWE 2K19]]''\n| Herself\n| [[Motion capture]] <br> Pre-order bonus\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]''\n| [[Sonya Blade]] (voice)\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[WWE 2K20]]''\n| Herself\n| Motion capture\n|}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last1=Rousey |first1=Ronda |last2=with Maria Burns Ortiz |year=2015 |title=My Fight/Your Fight |location=New York |publisher=[[Judith Regan|Regan Arts]] |isbn=978-1-941-39326-0 |oclc=892041615 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cLd0BgAAQBAJ}}\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n===Judo===\n* '''[[International Judo Federation]]'''\n** 2008 World Cup Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2008 Belgian Ladies Open Senior Bronze Medalist\n** 2007 Jigoro Kano Cup Senior Silver Medalist\n** 2007 Finnish Open Senior Gold Medalist\n** [[2007 World Judo Championships#Women|2007 World Judo Championships Senior Silver Medalist]]\n** 2007 German Open Senior Bronze Medalist\n** [[Judo at the 2007 Pan American Games#Middleweight (\u2013 70 kg)|2007 Pan American Games Senior Gold Medalist]]\n** [[2007 Pan American Judo Championships#Women's events|2007 Pan American Championships Senior Bronze Medalist]]\n** 2007 World Cup Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2007 British Open Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2006 Finnish Open Senior Bronze Medalist\n** 2006 Swedish Open Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2006 World Judo Championships Junior Bronze Medalist\n** 2006 Rendez-Vous Senior Gold Medalist\n** [[2006 Pan American Judo Championships#Women's events|2006 Pan American Championships Senior Silver Medalist]]\n** [http://www.judoinside.com/event/view/4121/ 2006 World Cup Senior Gold Medalist]\n** 2006 Belgian Ladies Open Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2005 Ontario Open Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2005 Rendez-Vous Senior Gold Medalist\n** [[2005 Pan American Judo Championships#Women's events|2005 Pan American Championships Senior Gold Medalist]]\n** 2004 Ontario Open Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2004 Ontario Open Junior Gold Medalist\n** [http://www.judoinside.com/event/view/3352/ 2004 World Judo Championships Junior Gold Medalist]\n** 2004 Rendez-Vous Senior Bronze Medalist\n** 2004 Pan American Championships Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2003 Rendez-Vous Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2001 Coupe Canada Senior Cup Gold Medalist\n* '''[[Summer Olympic Games]]'''\n** [[Judo at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 70 kg#Medalists|2008 Summer Olympics Senior Bronze Medalist]]\n* '''[[USA Judo]]'''\n** USA Senior National Championship (2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2010)\n** USA Senior Olympic Team Trials Winner (2004, 2008)\n** 2007 US Open Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2006 US Open Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2006 USA Fall Classic Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2006 US Open Junior Gold Medalist\n** 2005 US Open Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2005 US Open Junior Silver Medalist\n** 2004 US Open Senior Bronze Medalist\n** 2003 US Open Senior Silver Medalist\n** 2003 USA Fall Classic Senior Gold Medalist\n** 2002 US Open Junior Gold Medalist\n\n===Other accomplishments===\n*International Sports Hall of Fame (Class of 2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/article/ronda-rousey-inducted-into-the-international-sports-hall-of-fame-2018-arnold-sports-festival|title=Ronda Rousey inducted into the International Sports Hall of Fame at the 2018 Arnold Sports Festival USA|work=[[WWE]]|author=WWE.com Staff|date=March 3, 2018|accessdate=March 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Mixed martial arts===\n* '''[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'''\n**[[UFC Hall of Fame]] (first female inductee)\n** [[UFC Women's Bantamweight Championship]] (one time; inaugural)\n** Six successful title defenses\n** [[Bonus Awards|Fight of the Night]] (two times) <small>vs. [[Miesha Tate]]</small><ref name=\"sherdog1\">{{cite web |author=Whitman, Mike |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-168-Bonuses-Rousey-Banks-Extra-36150000-Browne-Tate-Earn-3675K-Awards-61329 |title=UFC 168 Bonuses: Rousey banks extra $150,000, Browne, Tate earn $75K awards |publisher=SherDog |date=December 28, 2013}}</ref> <small>and [[Holly Holm]]</small>\n** [[Bonus Awards|Submission of the Night]] (one time) <small>vs. Miesha Tate</small><ref name=\"sherdog1\" />\n** [[Bonus Awards|Performance of the Night]] (four times) <small>vs. [[Cat Zingano]],</small><ref>{{cite web |author=Myers, Thomas |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2015/3/1/8127773/ufc-184-bonuses-ronda-rousey-jake-ellenberger-extra-50000-mma |title=UFC 184 bonuses: Ronda Rousey, Jake Ellenberger and more bank an extra $50,000 each |date=March 1, 2015 |publisher=MMA Mania}}</ref> <small> [[Sara McMann]],</small><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-170-Bonuses-Rousey-Thompson-MacDonald-Maia-Earn-3650K-Awards-64095 |title=UFC 170 Bonuses: Rousey, Thompson, MacDonald, Maia earn $50K awards |website=Sherdog |date=February 22, 2014}}</ref> <small> [[Alexis Davis (fighter)|Alexis Davis]],</small><ref>{{cite web |author=C. J. Tuttle |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-175-Bonuses-Chris-Weidman-Ronda-Rousey-Lyoto-Machida-Rob-Font-Bank-3650K-70127 |title=UFC 175 Bonuses: Chris Weidman, Ronda Rousey, Lyoto Machida, Rob Font Bank $50K |website=Sherdog |date=July 5, 2014}}</ref><small> and [[Bethe Correia]]</small>\n** First female UFC Champion\n** First Olympic medalist to win a UFC championship<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmaweekly.com/holly-holm-motivated-to-steal-ronda-rouseys-historical-thunder-at-ufc-193|title=Holly Holm Motivated to Steal Ronda Rousey's Historical Thunder at UFC 193 - MMAWeekly.com|website=www.mmaweekly.com|accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n** Fastest women's title fight victory in UFC history (fourteen seconds; vs Cat Zingano)\n** Longest title fight finish streak in UFC history (6)<ref name=\"mmajunkie1\" />\n** Most armbar finishes in UFC/WEC/Pride/Strikeforce history (9)<ref name=\"armbarconsec\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/mma/10-olympians-who-have-competed-in-the-ufc/8|title=10 Olympians who have competed in the UFC|date=November 11, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n** Most consecutive armbar finishes in UFC/WEC/Pride/Strikeforce history (8)<ref name=\"armbarconsec\"/>\n** Most post-fight bonuses amongst women's UFC fighters (6)<ref name=\"mmajunkie1\">{{cite web |author=Bohn, Mike |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/08/ufc-190-post-fight-facts-ronda-rousey-into-uncharted-territory-in-just-ufc-six-fights |title=UFC 190 post-fight facts: Ronda Rousey into uncharted territory \u2013 in just six UFC fights |work=MMAjunkie |date=August 2, 2015}}</ref>\n** Most title defenses by a woman in UFC history (6)\n** Won the first ever women's fight in UFC history<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/02/24/us/ufc-women-fight/index.html|title=Rousey wins first UFC women's match - CNN|first=Jill |last=Martin|publisher=|accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''[[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)|Strikeforce]]'''\n** [[Strikeforce Women's Bantamweight Championship]] (one t